976. On the historical source of immediate-constituent analysis. In: Notes from the linguistic underground, James McCawley (ed.), Syntax and Semantics 7, 229\u2013242. New York: Academic Press.\n*Percival, K. 1990. [http://www.jbe-platform.com/content/journals/10.1075/hl.17.1-2.05per Reflections on the history of dependency notions in linguistics]. Historiographia Linguistica, 17, 29\u201347.\n*Robinson, J. 1970. [https://www.jstor.org/stable/412278 Dependency structures and transformational rules]. Language 46, 259\u2013285.\n*Schubert, K. 1988. Metataxis: Contrastive dependency syntax for machine translation. Dordrecht: Foris.\n*Sgall, P., E. Haji\u010dov\u00e1, and J. Panevov\u00e1 1986. The meaning of the sentence in its semantic and pragmatic aspects. Dordrecht: D. Reidel Publishing Company.\n*Starosta, S. 1988. The case for lexicase. London: Pinter Publishers.\n*Tesni\u00e8re, L. 1959. \u00c9l\u00e9ments de syntaxe structurale. Paris: Klincksieck.\n*Tesni\u00e8re, L. 1966. \u00c9l\u00e9ments de syntaxe structurale, 2nd edition. Paris: Klincksieck.\n*Tesni\u00e8re, L. 2015. Elements of structural syntax [English translation of Tesni\u00e8re 1966]. John Benjamins, Amsterdam.\n*van Valin, R. 2001. An introduction to syntax. Cambridge, UK: Cambridge University Press.\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://universaldependencies.github.io/docs/ Universal Dependencies \u2013 a set of treebanks in a harmonized dependency grammar representation]\n\n[[Category:Grammar frameworks]]\n[[Category:Natural language parsing]]\n", "name_user": "Hooman Mallahzadeh", "label": "safe", "comment": "A hyperlink added.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dependency_grammar"}
{"title_page": "Eddie Large", "text_new": "{{Recent death}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name              = Eddie Large\n| image             = Eddie Large.jpg\n| imagesize         = 180px\n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = Edward Hugh McGinnis\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1941|6|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|2020|4|2|1941|6|25|df=y}}\n| medium            = Comedian\n| nationality       = Scottish\n| genre             = \n| subject           = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| spouse            = {{ubl|{{marriage|Sandra Bigwood|1965||end=div}}|{{marriage|Patsy Ann Scott|1983|<!--Year is omitted when marriage ends by death of subject of article-->}}}} \n| children          = 3\n| notable_work      = [[Little and Large]]}}\n'''Edward Hugh McGinnis''' (25 June 1941 \u2013 2 April 2020), better known by the stage name '''Eddie Large''', was a Scottish comedian. He was best known as one half of the double act [[Little and Large]], with [[Syd Little]]. He died on 02 April 2020 due to Corona Virus.\n\n==Early life==  \nLarge was born Edward Hugh McGinnis in [[Glasgow]] in 1941. His father Teddy served as a [[Petty Officer]] in the [[Royal Navy]] during World War II and after he returned from the war the family moved to a [[tenement]] in [[Oatlands, Glasgow|Oatlands]].<ref name=Autobiography>{{cite book|date=1 July 2005|author=Eddie Large and Stafford Hildred|isbn=1844541282|title=Larger Than Life: My Autobiography|publisher=John Blake}}</ref> When he was nine years old the family moved again to [[Manchester]], where he attended Claremont Road Primary School<ref name=wythenshawe>[http://wythenshawe.btck.co.uk/FamousLocals/LittleandLarge Wythenshawe Famous locals Little and Large] Retrieved 11 February 2016</ref> and a [[grammar school]].<ref>''Who's Who on Television''. ITV Books, 1982</ref>  He played football as a schoolboy, became a supporter of nearby [[Manchester City]] which had its ground opposite his home<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/lifestyle/showbiz/heart-swap-for-eddie-large-1655690|title=Heart swap for Eddie Large|first=Evening|last=Chronicle|date=18 June 2003|website=nechronicle}}</ref> and maintained a life long devotion to the club. After he left school he worked as an electrician and was a singer.{{cn}}\n\n==Little and Large==\n{{main|Little and Large}}\nHe met singer and guitarist Cyril Meed in the Stonemason's Arms pub in [[Wythenshawe]] and they formed a double act following the reaction to Eddie's comic heckling of Cyril,<ref name=wythenshawe></ref> who switched to comedy. The duo then performed in northern clubs. As Little and Large they began their TV career on the talent show ''[[Opportunity Knocks (UK TV series)|Opportunity Knocks]]'' winning in 1971 and went on to star in many television comedy programmes, including their own series ''[[The Little and Large Show]]'' and the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] series ''[[Who Do You Do?]]'' doing impressions and also becoming popular as [[pantomime]] stars. \n\nIn an interview in 2010, Large said that he and Syd Little had not spoken to each other for several years.<ref>{{cite news |author= |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/little-and-large-havent-spoken-for-a-long-time-1988413.html |title=Little and Large 'haven't spoken for a long time' |work=The Independent |date=1 June 2010 |accessdate=23 July 2013}}</ref> During the 2010\u201311 football season, football entertainment show ''[[Soccer AM]]'' produced comedy sketches with Peterborough footballer [[Mark Little (footballer)|Mark Little]], and Eddie Large, as the newly reformed Little and Large.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.socceram.com/story/0,21644,13871_6310041,00.html |title=Soccer AM &#124; Sky Sports |publisher=Soccer AM |date=13 August 2010 |accessdate=23 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\n\nLarge worked on the after-dinner circuit, and in recent years performed some cameo acting roles in dramas such as ''[[The Brief (ITV)|The Brief]]'' and ''[[Blackpool (TV serial)|Blackpool]]''. In 2006 he appeared on a comedy edition of ''[[The Weakest Link (UK game show)|The Weakest Link]]'', but was eliminated prior to the penultimate round. His autobiography entitled ''Larger than Life'' was published in 2005. \n\nIn 2013, Large released his first single without Little, a parody of \"[[Je t'aime... moi non plus]]\" by [[Serge Gainsbourg]] entitled \"Gee Musky... Moi Non Plus\".{{cn|date=August 2018}}\n\n==Personal life==\nLarge lived in [[Portishead, Somerset|Portishead]], near [[Bristol]], with his wife Patsy and 26-year-old son.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} He also had two daughters and three grandchildren.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nAfter being admitted to hospital in March 2002 due to kidney problems, he underwent a [[heart transplant]] at [[Papworth Hospital]], Cambridge in 2003 at the age of 62, and recovered fully.{{cn}} Large was hospitalised for some weeks in late 2013 after tripping over a road sign near his Portishead home.<ref>{{cite web|title=Comedian Eddie Large in hospital after road sign fall|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-24971363|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref> Large died on 2 April 2020 after contracting [[COVID-19]] while in hospital receiving treatment for heart failure. Large had suffered from kidney and heart problems for a number of years.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eddie Large dies aged 78 |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/people/news/5726/rip-eddie-large/ |website=[[British Comedy Guide]] |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0488116}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Large, Eddie}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:British male comedians]]\n[[Category:Heart transplant recipients]]\n[[Category:People from Gorbals]]\n[[Category:People from Portishead, Somerset]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Manchester]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:British television personalities]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n", "text_old": "{{Recent death}} \n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=June 2012}}\n{{refimprove|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| name              = Eddie Large\n| image             = Eddie Large.jpg\n| imagesize         = 180px\n| caption           = \n| birth_name        = Edward Hugh McGinnis\n| birth_date        = {{Birth date|1941|6|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place       = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| death_date        = {{Death date and age|2020|4|2|1941|6|25|df=y}}\n| medium            = Comedian\n| nationality       = Scottish\n| genre             = \n| subject           = \n| influences        = \n| influenced        = \n| spouse            = {{ubl|{{marriage|Sandra Bigwood|1965||end=div}}|{{marriage|Patsy Ann Scott|1983|<!--Year is omitted when marriage ends by death of subject of article-->}}}} \n| children          = 3\n| notable_work      = [[Little and Large]]}}\n'''Edward Hugh McGinnis''' (25 June 1941 \u2013 2 April 2020), better known by the stage name '''Eddie Large''', was a Scottish comedian. He was best known as one half of the double act [[Little and Large]], with [[Syd Little]].\n\n==Early life==  \nLarge was born Edward Hugh McGinnis in [[Glasgow]] in 1941. His father Teddy served as a [[Petty Officer]] in the [[Royal Navy]] during World War II and after he returned from the war the family moved to a [[tenement]] in [[Oatlands, Glasgow|Oatlands]].<ref name=Autobiography>{{cite book|date=1 July 2005|author=Eddie Large and Stafford Hildred|isbn=1844541282|title=Larger Than Life: My Autobiography|publisher=John Blake}}</ref> When he was nine years old the family moved again to [[Manchester]], where he attended Claremont Road Primary School<ref name=wythenshawe>[http://wythenshawe.btck.co.uk/FamousLocals/LittleandLarge Wythenshawe Famous locals Little and Large] Retrieved 11 February 2016</ref> and a [[grammar school]].<ref>''Who's Who on Television''. ITV Books, 1982</ref>  He played football as a schoolboy, became a supporter of nearby [[Manchester City]] which had its ground opposite his home<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/lifestyle/showbiz/heart-swap-for-eddie-large-1655690|title=Heart swap for Eddie Large|first=Evening|last=Chronicle|date=18 June 2003|website=nechronicle}}</ref> and maintained a life long devotion to the club. After he left school he worked as an electrician and was a singer.{{cn}}\n\n==Little and Large==\n{{main|Little and Large}}\nHe met singer and guitarist Cyril Meed in the Stonemason's Arms pub in [[Wythenshawe]] and they formed a double act following the reaction to Eddie's comic heckling of Cyril,<ref name=wythenshawe></ref> who switched to comedy. The duo then performed in northern clubs. As Little and Large they began their TV career on the talent show ''[[Opportunity Knocks (UK TV series)|Opportunity Knocks]]'' winning in 1971 and went on to star in many television comedy programmes, including their own series ''[[The Little and Large Show]]'' and the [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]] series ''[[Who Do You Do?]]'' doing impressions and also becoming popular as [[pantomime]] stars. \n\nIn an interview in 2010, Large said that he and Syd Little had not spoken to each other for several years.<ref>{{cite news |author= |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/little-and-large-havent-spoken-for-a-long-time-1988413.html |title=Little and Large 'haven't spoken for a long time' |work=The Independent |date=1 June 2010 |accessdate=23 July 2013}}</ref> During the 2010\u201311 football season, football entertainment show ''[[Soccer AM]]'' produced comedy sketches with Peterborough footballer [[Mark Little (footballer)|Mark Little]], and Eddie Large, as the newly reformed Little and Large.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.socceram.com/story/0,21644,13871_6310041,00.html |title=Soccer AM &#124; Sky Sports |publisher=Soccer AM |date=13 August 2010 |accessdate=23 July 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\n\nLarge worked on the after-dinner circuit, and in recent years performed some cameo acting roles in dramas such as ''[[The Brief (ITV)|The Brief]]'' and ''[[Blackpool (TV serial)|Blackpool]]''. In 2006 he appeared on a comedy edition of ''[[The Weakest Link (UK game show)|The Weakest Link]]'', but was eliminated prior to the penultimate round. His autobiography entitled ''Larger than Life'' was published in 2005. \n\nIn 2013, Large released his first single without Little, a parody of \"[[Je t'aime... moi non plus]]\" by [[Serge Gainsbourg]] entitled \"Gee Musky... Moi Non Plus\".{{cn|date=August 2018}}\n\n==Personal life==\nLarge lived in [[Portishead, Somerset|Portishead]], near [[Bristol]], with his wife Patsy and 26-year-old son.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}} He also had two daughters and three grandchildren.{{citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nAfter being admitted to hospital in March 2002 due to kidney problems, he underwent a [[heart transplant]] at [[Papworth Hospital]], Cambridge in 2003 at the age of 62, and recovered fully.{{cn}} Large was hospitalised for some weeks in late 2013 after tripping over a road sign near his Portishead home.<ref>{{cite web|title=Comedian Eddie Large in hospital after road sign fall|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-24971363|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=16 November 2013}}</ref> Large died on 2 April 2020 after contracting [[COVID-19]] while in hospital receiving treatment for heart failure. Large had suffered from kidney and heart problems for a number of years.<ref>{{cite web |title=Eddie Large dies aged 78 |url=https://www.comedy.co.uk/people/news/5726/rip-eddie-large/ |website=[[British Comedy Guide]] |accessdate=2 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0488116}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Large, Eddie}}\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:British male comedians]]\n[[Category:Heart transplant recipients]]\n[[Category:People from Gorbals]]\n[[Category:People from Portishead, Somerset]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Manchester]]\n[[Category:Comedians from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:British television personalities]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7d:46f8:1d00:c09a:7c37:a07e:9d4", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eddie_Large"}
{"title_page": "Coco (2017 film)", "text_new": "{{short description|2017 computer-animated film produced by Pixar Animation Studios}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Coco\n| image          = Coco (2017 film) poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| alt            = Theatrical release poster depicting the characters Coco, Dante the dog, Miguel, H\u00e9ctor, Ernesto, and Imelda when viewing clockwise from the bottom left around Ernesto's white, [[Day of the Dead]]-styled guitar. The guitar has a [[calavera]]-styled headstock with a small black silhouette of Miguel, who is carrying a guitar, and Dante (a dog) at the bottom. The neck of the guitar splits the background with their village during the day on the left and at night with fireworks on the right. The film's logo is visible below the poster with the \"Thanksgiving\" release date.\n| director       = [[Lee Unkrich]]\n| producer       = [[Darla K. Anderson]]\n| screenplay     = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Adrian Molina]]\n* Matthew Aldrich\n}}\n| story          = {{Plainlist|\n* Lee Unkrich\n* Jason Katz\n* Matthew Aldrich\n* Adrian Molina\n}}\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Anthony Gonzalez (actor)|Anthony Gonzalez]]\n* [[Gael Garc\u00eda Bernal]]\n* [[Benjamin Bratt]]\n* [[Alanna Ubach]]\n* [[Ren\u00e9e Victor]]\n* [[Ana Ofelia Murgu\u00eda]]\n* [[Edward James Olmos]]}}\n| music          = [[Michael Giacchino]]<ref name=\"CocoMusic\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/new-incredibles-2-toy-story-4-details-revealed-at-d23-1021250|title=New ''Incredibles 2'', ''Toy Story 4'' Details Revealed at D23|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|last1=Giardina|first1=Carolyn|last2=Kit|first2=Borys|date=July 14, 2017|accessdate=July 14, 2017}}</ref>\n| cinematography = {{Plainlist|\n* Matt Aspbury {{small|(camera)}}<ref name=AwardCategories>{{cite web|url=http://disneystudiosawards.com/coco|title=''Coco'' Award Categories|website=Disneystudiosawards.com|accessdate=October 10, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Danielle Feinberg]] {{small|(lighting)}}<ref name=AwardCategories/>\n}}\n| editing        = Steve Bloom<ref name=AwardCategories/>\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Walt Disney Pictures]]<ref name=\"PressKit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.wdsmediafile.com/media/Coco/writen-material/Coco5a023fe31b99f.pdf|title=''Coco'' Press Kit|website=Wdsmediafile.com|format=PDF|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref> \n* [[Pixar Animation Studios]]<ref name=\"PressKit\"/>\n}}\n| distributor    = [[Walt Disney Studios Motion Pictures|Walt Disney Studios<br />Motion Pictures]]<!-- Piping is used in this link to ensure correct formatting at all screen resolutions. -->\n| released       = {{Film date|2017|10|20|[[Morelia International Film Festival|Morelia]]|2017|11|22|United States|ref1=<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hecht |first1=John |title=Pixar's ''Coco'' to World Premiere at Mexico's Morelia Fest |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/pixars-coco-world-premiere-at-mexicos-morelia-fest-1018933 |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=July 5, 2017 |accessdate=July 5, 2017 }}</ref>}}\n| runtime        = 105 minutes<ref name=\"BBFC\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bbfc.co.uk/releases/coco-2017-0 |title=''Coco'' (2017) |work=[[British Board of Film Classification]] |date=December 20, 2017 |accessdate=December 26, 2017 }}</ref>\n| country        = United States\n| language       = English<ref name=\"BBFC\"/>\n| budget         = $175{{nbsp}}million<ref>{{Cite journal|date=August 2018|title=2017 Feature Film Study|url=https://www.filmla.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/2017_film_study_v3-WEB.pdf|journal=FilmL.A. Feature Film Study|page=23|accessdate=August 9, 2018}}</ref>\n| gross          = $807.1{{nbsp}}million<ref name=BOM>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=pixar1117.htm|title=''Coco'' (2017)|work=[[Box Office Mojo]]|publisher=[[IMDb]]|accessdate=July 23, 2018}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Coco''''' is a 2017 American [[3D film|3D]] [[computer-animated]] [[fantasy film|fantasy]] film produced by [[Pixar Animation Studios]] and released by [[Walt Disney Pictures]]. Based on an original idea by [[Lee Unkrich]], it is directed by him and co-directed by [[Adrian Molina]]. The film's voice cast stars [[Anthony Gonzalez (actor)|Anthony Gonzalez]], [[Gael Garc\u00eda Bernal]], [[Benjamin Bratt]], [[Alanna Ubach]], [[Ren\u00e9e Victor]], [[Ana Ofelia Murgu\u00eda]] and [[Edward James Olmos]]. The story follows a 12-year-old boy named Miguel who is accidentally transported to the Land of the Dead, where he seeks the help of his deceased musician great-great-grandfather to return him to his family among the living and to reverse his family's ban on music.\n\nThe concept for ''Coco'' is inspired by the Mexican holiday [[Day of the Dead]]. The film was scripted by Molina and Matthew Aldrich from a story by Unkrich, Jason Katz, Aldrich and Molina. Pixar began developing the animation in 2016; Unkrich and some of the film's crew visited Mexico for research. Composer [[Michael Giacchino]], who had worked on prior Pixar animated features, composed the score. ''Coco'' is the first film with a nine-figure budget to feature an all-Latino principal cast, with a cost of $175{{nbsp}}million.\n\n''Coco'' premiered on October 20, 2017, during the [[Morelia International Film Festival]] in [[Morelia, Mexico]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://moreliafilmfest.com/en/coco-la-nueva-pelicula-de-disney%E2%80%A2pixar-abrira-el-15o-ficm/|title=''Coco'', the new Disney\u2022Pixar movie, will open the 15th FICM|date=July 21, 2017|publisher=Festival Internacional del Cine en Morelia|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref> It was theatrically released in Mexico the following week, the weekend before {{lang|es|D\u00eda de los Muertos}}, and in the United States on November 22, 2017. The film was praised for its animation, voice acting, music, emotional story, and respect for [[Culture of Mexico|Mexican culture]]. It grossed over $807{{nbsp}}million worldwide, becoming [[list of highest-grossing animated films|the 16th highest-grossing animated film ever]] at the time of its release.<ref name=\"MexicoRecord1\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/coco-pixar-mexico-highest-grossing-film-all-time-box-office-record-1202209221/|title=''Coco''{{'}}s Otherworldly Mexico Run Lands Pixar Toon As Market's No. 1 Movie Ever|first=Nancy | last=Tartaglione |date=November 15, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=November 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"MexicoRecord2\">{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/justice-league-thor-ragnarok-coco-paddington-weekend-results-international-box-office-1202211796/|title='Justice League' Lassos $185M Overseas, $279M WW; 'Thor' Rocks To $739M Global \u2013 International Box Office|first=Nancy | last=Tartaglione |date=November 20, 2017|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|accessdate=November 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"MexicoRecord3\">{{cite web|url=http://collider.com/coco-box-office-mexico/|title=This Week in Animation: Pixar's ''Coco'' Now Mexico's #1 Film of All-Time|first=Dave | last=Trumbore |date=November 18, 2017|work=[[Collider (website)|Collider]]|accessdate=November 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"MexicoRecord4\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/box-office/disney-pixar-animated-coco-box-office-record-mexico-1202615942/amp/|title=Disney-Pixar's ''Coco'' Breaks Box Office Record in Mexico|first=Dave | last=McNary |date=November 15, 2017|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=November 21, 2017}}</ref> Recipient of [[list of accolades received by Coco (2017 film)|several accolades]], ''Coco'' was chosen by the [[National Board of Review]] as the [[National Board of Review Award for Best Animated Film|Best Animated Film]] of 2017. The film won two [[Academy Awards]] for [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature|Best Animated Feature]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] (\"[[Remember Me (Coco song)|Remember Me]]\"). It also won Best Animated Film at the [[BAFTA Award for Best Animated Film|BAFTA Awards]], [[Golden Globe Award for Best Animated Feature Film|Golden Globe Awards]], [[Critics' Choice Movie Award for Best Animated Feature|Critic's Choice Movie Awards]], and [[Annie Award for Best Animated Feature|Annie Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://oscar.go.com/news/2018/oscar-winners-2018-see-the-full-list|title=9OSCARS|date=2018-03-04|website=ABC|access-date=2018-03-05}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\n<!-- Per WP:FILMPLOT, plot summaries for feature films should be between 400 to 700 words. As of this note, there are 696 words. Also, keep the summary short please.-->\nIn Santa Cecilia, [[Mexico]], Miguel dreams of becoming a musician, even though his family strictly forbids it. His great-great-grandmother Imelda was married to a man who left her and their daughter Coco to pursue a career in music, and when he never returned, Imelda banished music from her family's life before starting a shoemaking business. Miguel now lives with the elderly Coco and their family, including Miguel's parents and grandmother, who are all shoemakers. He idolizes famous deceased musician Ernesto de la Cruz. Miguel made a makeshift guitar and he secretly teaches himself to play it from Ernesto's old films. On the Day of the Dead, Miguel accidentally damages the picture frame that holds a photo of Coco with her mother on the family {{lang|es|[[ofrenda]]}}, discovering that a hidden section of the photograph shows his great-great-grandfather holding Ernesto's famous guitar. Though the image's face has been torn off, Miguel concludes that Ernesto is his great-great-grandfather. Ignoring his family's objections, he decides to enter a Day of the Dead talent show.\n\nBreaking into Ernesto's mausoleum, Miguel takes his guitar to use in the show, but once he strums it, he becomes invisible to everyone in the village plaza. However, he can interact with his [[calaca|skeletal]] dead relatives, who are visiting from the Land of the Dead for the holiday. Taking him back with them, they learn that Imelda cannot visit, since Miguel accidentally removed her photo from the {{lang|es|ofrenda}}. Miguel discovers that he is cursed for stealing from the dead, and must return to the Land of the Living before sunrise, or he will become one of the dead; to do so, he must receive a blessing from a member of his family. Imelda offers Miguel a blessing on the condition he end his dream of becoming a musician, but Miguel refuses and resolves to seek Ernesto's blessing instead. He meets H\u00e9ctor, who declares that he knows Ernesto, offering to help him reach him in return for Miguel taking his photo back with him, so that he might visit his daughter before she forgets him, causing him to disappear completely. H\u00e9ctor helps Miguel enter a talent competition to win entry to Ernesto's mansion, but Miguel's family tracks him down, forcing him to flee. Miguel sneaks into the mansion, where Ernesto welcomes him as his descendant, but H\u00e9ctor confronts them, again imploring Miguel to take his photo to the Land of the Living. Ernesto and H\u00e9ctor renew an argument from their partnership in life, and Miguel realizes that when H\u00e9ctor decided to leave the duo to return to his family, Ernesto poisoned him and stole his guitar and songs, passing them off as his own to become famous. To protect his legacy, Ernesto seizes the photo and has his security guards throw Miguel and H\u00e9ctor into a [[cenote]] pit. There, Miguel realizes that H\u00e9ctor is his real great-great-grandfather, and that Coco is H\u00e9ctor's daughter. \n\nAfter Imelda and the family rescue the duo, Miguel reveals the truth about H\u00e9ctor's death. Imelda and H\u00e9ctor reconcile, and the family infiltrates Ernesto's concert to retrieve H\u00e9ctor's photo. Ernesto's crimes are exposed to the audience, who jeer at him as he is thrown out of the stadium, then crushed by a giant bell (the same way he died); in the chaos, however, H\u00e9ctor's photograph is lost. As the sun rises, Coco's life and memory are fading; Imelda and H\u00e9ctor bless Miguel, so that he can return to the Land of the Living. After Miguel plays \"[[Remember Me (Pixar song)|Remember Me]]\" (a song that H\u00e9ctor wrote for Coco, that Ernesto uses as his number one hit), Coco brightens and sings along with Miguel. She reveals that she had saved the torn-off piece of the family photo with H\u00e9ctor's face on it, then tells her family stories about her father, thus saving his memory as well as his existence in the Land of the Dead. Miguel's family reconciles with him, ending the ban on music; one year later, Miguel presents the family {{lang|es|ofrenda}} (which now includes the deceased Coco) to his new baby sister. Coco's collected letters from H\u00e9ctor prove that Ernesto stole his songs, destroying Ernesto's legacy and allowing H\u00e9ctor to be rightfully honored in his place. In the Land of the Dead, H\u00e9ctor and Imelda rekindle their romance and join Coco for a visit to the living, where Miguel plays and sings for his living and dead relatives.\n\n==Cast==\n{{Div col|colwidth=}}\n* [[Anthony Gonzalez (actor)|Anthony Gonzalez]] as Miguel, a 12-year-old aspiring musician.<ref name=VFMexicoAgeTrump /><ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\">{{cite news|last1=Milligan|first1=Mercedes|title=Disney-Pixar Introduces the 'Coco' Character Family|url=http://www.animationmagazine.net/features/disney-pixar-introduces-the-coco-character-family/|language=English|accessdate= June 8, 2017|work=Animation Magazine|date=June 6, 2017}}</ref>\n* [[Gael Garc\u00eda Bernal]] as H\u00e9ctor, a charming [[trickster]] in the Land of the Dead who enlists Miguel to help him visit the Land of the Living. He is later revealed to be Miguel\u2019s true great-great grandfather.<ref name=VFMexicoAgeTrump>{{cite web|last1=Robinson |first1=Joanna |title=Pixar's Coco is a 'Love Letter to Mexico' in the Age of Trump |url=http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/12/pixar-coco-gael-garcia-bernal-dia-de-los-muertos-miguel |date=December 6, 2016 |work=Vanity Fair |accessdate=December 6, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161207151356/http://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/12/pixar-coco-gael-garcia-bernal-dia-de-los-muertos-miguel |archivedate=December 7, 2016 }}</ref>\n* [[Benjamin Bratt]] as Ernesto de la Cruz, the most famous [[musician]] in the history of [[Mexico]] and Miguel's idol. Revered by fans worldwide until his untimely death, the charming and charismatic musician is even more beloved in the Land of the Dead.<ref name=VFMexicoAgeTrump /><ref>{{cite web|last1=Wintraub |first1=Steve |title=Benjamin Bratt on 'The Infiltrator', 'Shot Caller' and Pixar's 'Coco' |url=http://collider.com/benjamin-bratt-the-infiltrator-coco-pixar-interview/ |publisher=Collider |accessdate=July 23, 2016 |date=July 13, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160717192244/http://collider.com/benjamin-bratt-the-infiltrator-coco-pixar-interview/ |archivedate=July 17, 2016 }}</ref>\n** Antonio Sol provides de la Cruz's singing voice, with the exception of \"[[Remember Me (Pixar song)|Remember Me]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/coco-original-motion-picture-soundtrack/1293552700|title=\"Coco (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\" by Various Artists on iTunes|date=November 10, 2017|website=Itunes.apple.com}}</ref>\n* [[Alanna Ubach]] as Mam\u00e1 Imelda, Miguel's late great-great-grandmother, H\u00e9ctor's wife, Coco's mother, and the [[matriarch]] of the family.<ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\" />\n* [[Ren\u00e9e Victor]] as Abuelita, Coco's daughter Elena, and Miguel's grandmother who strictly enforces the Rivera family's music ban.<ref name=VFMexicoAgeTrump />\n* [[Ana Ofelia Murgu\u00eda]] as Mam\u00e1 Coco, Miguel's great-grandmother and the daughter of H\u00e9ctor and Imelda.<ref name=\"LATUnkrichGetsDown\">{{cite news|last1=Crust |first1=Kevin |title='Coco' director Lee Unkrich gets down with the Day of the Dead for Pixar's fall release |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-2017-movie-television-preview-coco-director-lee-unkrich-gets-down-1484182217-htmlstory.html |accessdate=January 16, 2017 |work=Los Angeles Times |date=January 16, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170115164037/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/la-2017-movie-television-preview-coco-director-lee-unkrich-gets-down-1484182217-htmlstory.html |archivedate=January 15, 2017 }}</ref>\n** Libertad Garc\u00eda Fonzi as a young Coco.\n* [[Edward James Olmos]] as Chicharr\u00f3n, a friend of H\u00e9ctor's who becomes forgotten in the Land of the Dead.<ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\" />\n* [[Alfonso Arau]] as Pap\u00e1 Julio, Coco's husband and Miguel's late great-grandfather.<ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\" /><ref name=\"ancestry.com\">{{cite web |url=http://family.disney.com/wp-content/uploads/2017/11/rivera-family-tree.jpg |title=Family tree |website=family.disney.com |format=JPG}}</ref>\n* [[Selene Luna]] as T\u00eda Rosita, Miguel's late aunt.<ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\" />\n* Dyana Ortell\u00ed as T\u00eda Victoria, Miguel's late aunt.\n* [[Herbert Sig\u00fcenza]] as T\u00edos Oscar and Felipe, Miguel's late identical twin uncles.<ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\" />\n* [[Jaime Camil]] as Pap\u00e1, Miguel's father and Abuelita's son.<ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\" />\n* [[Sof\u00eda Espinosa]] as Mam\u00e1, Miguel's mother.<ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\" />\n* [[Luis Valdez]] as T\u00edo Berto, Miguel's uncle.<ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\" />\n** Valdez also voices Don Hidalgo.\n* [[Lombardo Boyar]] as Plaza Mariachi, a [[Mariachi]] whom Miguel meets in Santa Cecilia Plaza.<ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\" />\n** Boyar also voices Gustavo, a musician of the Land of the Dead.\n* [[Octavio Solis]] as Arrival Agent.<ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\" />\n* [[Gabriel Iglesias]] as Clerk.<ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\" />\n* [[Cheech Marin]] as Corrections Officer.<ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\" />\n* [[Carla Medina]] as Departure Agent.<ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\" />\n* Blanca Araceli as [[Emcee]].<ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\" />\n* [[Natalia Cordova-Buckley]] as [[Frida Kahlo]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/10/nolan-gerard-funk-berlin-i-love-you-natalia-cordova-buckley-coco-1202194115/|title=Nolan Gerard Funk Joins 'Berlin, I Love You'; Natalia Cordova-Buckley Set In 'Coco'|last=N'Duka|first=Amanda|website=Deadline Hollywood|date=October 24, 2017|accessdate=October 25, 2017}}</ref>\n* Salvador Reyes as a Security Guard.<ref name=\"AMCharacterFamily\" />\n* [[John Ratzenberger]] as Juan Ortodoncia\n\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Production==\n===Development===\n[[File:Lee Unkrich cropped 2009.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Lee Unkrich]] (''pictured in 2009'') first conceptualized ''Coco'' in 2010.]]\n[[Lee Unkrich]] first pitched an idea for the film in 2010, when ''[[Toy Story 3]]'', which he also directed, was released.<ref name=\"VFMexicoAgeTrump\" /> Initially the film was to be about an American child, learning about his Mexican heritage, while dealing with the death of his mother. Eventually, the team decided that this was the wrong approach and reformed the film to focus on a Mexican child instead.<ref name=\"vergecoco\">{{cite web|last1=Robinson|first1=Tasha|title=Pixar's Lee Unkrich on the 'anxiety' of directing Coco|url=https://www.theverge.com/2017/11/22/16691932/pixar-interview-coco-lee-unkrich-behind-the-scenes|website=The Verge|accessdate=December 17, 2017}}</ref> Of the original version, Unkrich noted that it \"reflected the fact that none of us at the time were from Mexico.\"<ref name=\"vergecoco\"/> The fact that the film depicted \"a real culture\" caused anxiety for Unkrich, who \"felt an enormous responsibility on [his] shoulders to do it right.\"<ref name=\"vergecoco\"/>\n\nThe Pixar team made several trips to [[Mexico]] to help define the characters and story of ''Coco''. Unkrich said, \"I'd seen it portrayed in folk art. It was something about the juxtaposition of skeletons with bright, festive colors that captured my imagination. It has led me down a winding path of discovery. And the more I learn about ''[el] D\u00eda de los Muertos'', the more it affects me deeply.\"<ref>{{citeweb|url=http://blogs.disney.com/insider/2015/08/14/meet-the-newest-disneypixar-marvel-coco/|title=Meet the Newest Disney\u2022Pixar Marvel, Coco|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150817212444/http://blogs.disney.com/insider/2015/08/14/meet-the-newest-disneypixar-marvel-coco/|archivedate=August 17, 2015|publisher=Disney Insider|accessdate=November 6, 2017|date=August 15, 2015|first=Drew|last=Taylor|url-status=live}}</ref> The team found it difficult working with skeletal creatures, as they lacked any [[muscular system]], and as such had to be animated differently from their human counterparts.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Debruge|first1=Peter|date=June 16, 2017|title=Pixar Shares 'Coco' Secrets at Annecy Animation Festival|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/festivals/coco-pixar-secrets-annecy-animation-film-festival-1202468872/|website=Variety|accessdate=July 20, 2017}}</ref> ''Coco'' also took inspiration from [[Hayao Miyazaki]]'s [[anime]] films ''[[Spirited Away]]'' (2001) and ''[[Howl's Moving Castle (film)|Howl's Moving Castle]]'' (2004) as well as the [[action film]] ''[[John Wick (film)|John Wick]]'' (2014).<ref>{{cite news|title=The World of Coco Influenced by John Wick, Hayao Miyazaki, Mexican History|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/world-of-coco/2/|work=[[/Film]]|date=August 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Disney made a request to trademark the phrase \"D\u00eda de los Muertos\" for merchandising applications. This was met with criticism from the [[Mexican Americans|Mexican American]] community in the United States.<ref name=CNNTrademarkBacklash>{{cite news|last1=Y. Rodriguez |first1=Cindy |title=Day of the Dead trademark request draws backlash for Disney |url=http://edition.cnn.com/2013/05/10/us/disney-trademark-day-dead/ |accessdate=September 12, 2015 |publisher=[[CNN]] |date=May 11, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120110541/http://edition.cnn.com/2013/05/10/us/disney-trademark-day-dead |archivedate=November 20, 2015 }}</ref> [[Lalo Alcaraz]], a Mexican-American cartoonist, drew a film poster titled ''Muerto Mouse'', depicting a skeletal [[Godzilla]]-sized [[Mickey Mouse]] with the byline \"It's coming to trademark your ''cultura''.\"<ref name=NBCNewsAlcaraz /> More than 21,000 people signed a petition on [[Change.org]] stating that the trademark was \"cultural appropriation and exploitation at its worst\".<ref name=CNNTrademarkBacklash /> A week later, Disney canceled the attempt, with the official statement saying that the \"trademark filing was intended to protect any title for our film and related activities. It has since been determined that the title of the film will change, and therefore we are withdrawing our trademark filing.\"<ref name=DeadlineDropsTrademark>{{cite web|last1=Yamato |first1=Jen |title=Disney Drops Controversial Dia De Los Muertos Trademark Bid After Online Uproar |url=http://deadline.com/2013/05/disney-withdraws-dia-de-los-muertos-trademark-bid-492506/ |publisher=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |accessdate=September 12, 2015 |date=May 7, 2013 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120054645/http://deadline.com/2013/05/disney-withdraws-dia-de-los-muertos-trademark-bid-492506/ |archivedate=November 20, 2015}}</ref> In 2015, Pixar hired Alcaraz to consult on the film,<ref name=NBCNewsAlcaraz>{{cite news|last1=Nevarez |first1=Griselda |title=Cartoonist Lalo Alcaraz to Work on Pixar's Day of the Dead Film 'Coco' |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/cartoonist-lalo-alcaraz-work-pixars-coco-n413771 |accessdate=September 12, 2015 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=August 21, 2015 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150830050610/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/latino/cartoonist-lalo-alcaraz-work-pixars-coco-n413771 |archivedate=August 30, 2015 }}</ref> joining playwright [[Octavio Solis]] and former CEO of the Mexican Heritage Corp. Marcela Davison Aviles, to form a cultural consultant group.<ref name=\"VFMexicoAgeTrump\" />\n\n===Story===\nUnkrich found writing the script \"the toughest nut to crack\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.awn.com/animationworld/interview-pixars-lee-unkrich-talks-success-diversity-and-coco|title=Interview: Pixar's Lee Unkrich Talks Success, Diversity and 'Coco'|website=Awn.com}}</ref> Earlier versions of the film had different universe rules regarding how Miguel (originally called Marco) would get back from the land of the dead; in one case he physically had to run across the bridge. In one version of the story, his family is cursed with singing when trying to speak, which was included as a technique to add music to a story where music is banned. Originally, Lopez and Anderson-Lopez had written many more songs for the film than what ended up in the released version; one piece that survived in storyboard until late into the production was an expository song that explained the Mexican holiday to viewers to begin the film. In another song, Miguel's mother explains the tradition of shoe-making in their family, and how this means he is not allowed to pursue music.<ref>{{Citation|title=Coco: Deleted Scenes with commentary|date=2017|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qurIuw_LCgc|volume=|pages=|publisher=Pixar Animation Studios|access-date=2018-06-22}}</ref>\n\n===Casting===\n''Coco'' is the first-ever motion picture with a nine-figure budget to feature an all-Latino cast, with a cost of $175\u2013200{{nbsp}}million.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nhregister.com/news/article/Pixar-s-Coco-feasts-on-Justice-12384697.php|title=Pixar's 'Coco' feasts on 'Justice League' at box office|date=November 26, 2017|publisher=[[New Haven Register]]|accessdate=November 27, 2017}}</ref> Gonzalez first auditioned for the role of Miguel when he was nine, and was finalized in the role two years later.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2017/11/24/meet-anthony-gonzalez-teen-breakout-star-pixars-animated-coco/885828001/|title=Meet Anthony Gonzalez, the teen breakout star of Pixar's animated 'Coco'|website=Usatoday.com}}</ref> Speaking of his character, Gonzalez said: \"[Miguel and I] both know the importance of following our dream and we know the importance of following our tradition, so that's something that I connected with Miguel a lot\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/redeye/culture/ct-redeye-coco-movie-actor-anthony-gonzalez-interview-20180223-story.html|title='Coco' star Anthony Gonzalez connects his passion for music with his love for family|first=Sad\u00e9|last=Carpenter|website=Chicagotribune.com}}</ref> During the film's pre-production, Miguel was originally set to be voiced by a child named Emilio Fuentes, but was removed from the role after his voice deepened due to puberty over the course of the film's production.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/coco-how-pixar-brought-day-dead-story-life-1065932|title='Coco': How Pixar Brought Its \"Day of the Dead\" Story to Life|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, the ''Coco'' team made an official announcement about the cast, which revealed that Gael Garcia Bernal, Benjamin Bratt, Ren\u00e9e Victor, and Anthony Gonzalez would voice the characters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/12/pixar-coco-gael-garcia-bernal-dia-de-los-muertos-miguel|title=Pixar's Coco Is a \"Love Letter to Mexico\" When It's Needed Most|first=Joanna|last=Robinson|website=Vanityfair.com}}</ref> Bratt, who voiced De la Cruz, was \"moved\" when he realized that Disney-Pixar wanted to make a film on Latin culture.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/gael-garc-a-bernal-talks-singing-pixars-coco-1056611|title=Gael Garc\u00eda Bernal Talks About Singing in Pixar's 'Coco'|website=Hollywoodreporter.com|accessdate=May 26, 2018}}</ref> Disney officials closely monitored Bernal's movements and expressions while he voiced the characters and used their input for animating H\u00e9ctor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/coco-interview-gael-garcia-bernal/|title=Coco Was A 'Collaborative Process' At Pixar|date=November 21, 2017|website=Screenrant.com|accessdate=May 26, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBratt voiced Ernesto De la Cruz, a character who he described as \"the Mexican Frank Sinatra\"; \"[a] larger than life persona\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://screenrant.com/coco-interview-benjamin-bratt-anthony-gonzalez/|title=Benjamin Bratt Is Mexican Sinatra In Coco|date=November 21, 2017|publisher=}}</ref> On the advice of the filmmakers, Bratt watched videos of equivalent Mexican actors including [[Jorge Negrete]] and [[Pedro Infante]]. Bratt found the character similar to his father in physical appearance, \"swagger and confidence\", and worked in the film as a tribute to him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/movies/features/902531-benjamin-bratt-on-playing-ernesto-de-la-cruz-in-coco|title=Benjamin Bratt on His Character in Disney/Pixar's Coco|date=November 13, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nThe character Mama Imelda's voice was provided by Alanna Ubach. Ubach felt that the film \"is [giving] respect to one quality that all Latin families across the universe do have in common, and that is giving respect and prioritizing the importance of family\". Mama Imelda's voice was influenced by Ubach's t\u00eda Flora, who was a \"profound influence in [her] life\". Ubach felt her t\u00eda was the family's matriarch, and dedicated the film to her t\u00eda.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hiplatina.com/alanna-ubach-pixars-coco/|title=Alanna Ubach on Playing the Fiercely Strong Mama Imelda in Pixar's 'Coco'|date=November 21, 2017|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nUnkrich stated that it was a struggle to find a role in the film for [[John Ratzenberger]], who is not Latino but has voiced a character in every Pixar film. As Unkrich did not want to break Pixar's tradition, Ratzenberger was given a minor role with one word making it Ratzenberger's shortest Pixar role.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laughingplace.com/w/news/2017/08/28/john-ratzenberger-confirmed-coco/|title=John Ratzenberger Confirmed for \"Coco\"|author=Laughing Place Disney Newsdesk|work=Laughing Place|date=August 28, 2017|accessdate=August 28, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Animation===\nOn April 13, 2016, Unkrich announced that they had begun work on the animation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ohmy.disney.com/movies/2016/04/13/lee-unkrich-confirms-that-animation-has-officially-started-on-coco/ |title=Lee Unkrich Confirms That Animation Has Officially Started on Coco! |first=Rachel|last=Berman|date=April 13, 2016 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160506080229/https://ohmy.disney.com/movies/2016/04/13/lee-unkrich-confirms-that-animation-has-officially-started-on-coco/ |archivedate=May 6, 2016 }}</ref> The film's writer, [[Adrian Molina]], was promoted to co-director in late 2016.<ref name=\"VFMexicoAgeTrump\" /> Unkrich said that Pixar wanted \"to have as much contrast between\" the Land of the Living and the Land of the Dead, and that many techniques were used to differentiate the worlds. Color was one: \"Given the holiday and the iconography, [Pixar] knew the Land of the Dead had to be a visually vibrant and colorful place, so [they] deliberately designed Santa Cecilia to be more muted\" said Unkrich.<ref name=\"PressKit\"/>\n\nAccording to Harley Jessup, the film's production designer, Santa Cecilia is based on real Mexican villages, as the production team \"stayed grounded in reality in the Land of the Living\". Chris Bernardi, the film's set supervisor, said that the town was made small so Miguel could feel confined. Bert Berry, the film's art director, said that aged building materials were used in order to depict Santa Cecilia \"as an older charming city\".<ref name=\"PressKit\"/> According to Unkrich, Miguel's guitar playing is authentic, as they \"videotaped musicians playing each song or melody and strapped GoPros on their guitars\" to use as a reference. For the scene in which Miguel plays music in his secret hideout, the filmmakers used \"very elegant, lyrical camera moves\" and \"gentle drifts and slow arcing moves around Miguel as he plays his guitar with very shallow depth of \ufb01eld to enhance the beauty of the soft-focus foreground candles\".<ref name=\"PressKit\"/>\n\nChristian Hoffman, the film's character supervisor, said that all of the details in Mama Coco's face were not modeled. Instead, his team used special software to design separate layers of detail, which were then added to her face with a shader. The character's model was made with higher resolution to get all the wrinkles right, according to Hoffman.<ref name=\"PressKit\"/> Pixar used some Xolo dogs to use as reference for the character Dante, while a tentacle from ''[[Finding Dory]]'''s Hank was used for his tongue.\n\nJessup called the Marigold petal bridge that connects both worlds \"elegant and magical\". Michael K. O'Brien, the film's effects supervisor, called it \"a huge technical challenge\" for the animation team, but referred to it as something \"so visually exciting with petals dripping from it; it was a massive artistic undertaking. [the production team] wanted it to glow \u2014 to feel alive\". The scenes in which Miguel takes a few petals off of the bridge and in which Hector sinks into the bridge were given more effects and special art direction.<ref name=\"PressKit\"/>\n\nFor the Land of the Dead, Unkrich did not want \"to have just a free-for-all, wacky world\", wanting instead to add logic and be \"ever-expanding because  new residents would arrive regularly\". Jessup said that the animation team wanted the Land of the Dead \"to be a vibrant explosion of color\" when Miguel arrives. Jessup also said that \"Lee [Unkrich] described a vertical world of towers, contrasting with the flatness of Santa Cecilia. The lights and reflections are dazzling and there's a crazy transportation system that connects it all. The costume colors are much more vibrant than in the Land of the Living, where [the animation team] tried to stay grounded in reality. [They] really went all out in the Land of the Dead to make it a reflection of the holiday\". According to David Ryu, the film's supervising technical director, the animation team \"\ufb01gured out a way to introduce a single light \u2014 but give it a million points\" for the scenes on the outside in the Land of the Dead: \"The renderer sees it as one light, but we see a million lights\".<ref name=\"PressKit\"/>\n\nAccording to art director Daniel Arraiga, the animators \"had to \ufb01gure out how to give [the skeletons] personality without skin, muscles, noses or even lips\" and that they \"played with shapes and did a lot of paintings. [They] sculpted and studied skulls from every angle to \ufb01gure out where [they] could add appeal and charm\". Global technology supervisor J.D. Northrup was hired early in the film's production in order to avoid potential issues in the film's animation process. Northrup said that \"Each [of the skeletons' pieces] had to be independent so the complexity of the rig and the stress that it puts on the pipeline were something like we've never seen before.\" Northrup was also tasked with simplifying the skeleton's elements to render the skeleton crowds. In order to create the skeletons, several additional controls were used, as they \"needed to move in ways that humans don't,\" according to character modeling and articulation lead Michael Honse. Honse said that the bones were a particular problem, stating that \"there was a lot of back-and-forth with animation to get it right,\" but found \"really cool ways\" to move the skeletons.<ref name=\"PressKit\"/>\n\n===Music and soundtrack===\n{{Infobox album\n| name         = Coco (Original Motion Picture Soundtrack)\n| type         = Soundtrack\n| artist       = Various Artists\n| cover        = \n| alt          = \n| released     = {{Start date|2017|11|10}}\n| recorded     = August\u2013October 2017\n| venue        = \n| studio       = {{flat list|*[[Warner Bros. Studios, Burbank|Eastwood Scoring Stage]] (score)\n*[[Avatar Studios]]\n*[[Henson Recording Studios]]\n*Estudio 13\n*Audio By the Bay\n*Crawford Media Services}}\n| genre        = {{flat list|\n*[[Son mexicano]]\n*[[Mariachi]]\n*[[Son jarocho]]\n*[[Ranchera]]\n*[[Huapango]]\n*[[Bolero]]\n*[[Mexican pop]]\n}}\n| length       = 79:09\n| label        = [[Walt Disney Records|Walt Disney]]\n| producer     = {{flat list|*[[Michael Giacchino]]\n*Tom MacDougall\n*[[Germaine Franco]]\n*[[Kristen Anderson-Lopez]]\n*[[Robert Lopez]]}}\n| chronology   = [[Pixar]]\n| prev_title   = [[Cars 3#Music|Cars 3]]\n| prev_year    = 2017\n| next_title   = [[Incredibles 2]]\n| next_year    = 2018\n| misc         = {{Extra chronology\n | artist     = [[Michael Giacchino]]\n | type       = Soundtrack\n | prev_title = [[War for the Planet of the Apes]]\n | prev_year  = 2017\n | title      = Coco\n | year       = 2017\n | next_title = [[Incredibles 2]]\n | next_year  = 2018\n}}\n}}\n\nThe film's score was composed by [[Michael Giacchino]]. [[Germaine Franco]], Adrian Molina, [[Robert Lopez]], and [[Kristen Anderson-Lopez]] wrote the songs.<ref name=\"CocoMusic\"/> Recording for the score began on August 14, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Get a Peek into Michael Giacchino's Scoring Process for Pixar's 'Coco' \u2013 Courtesy of Director, Lee Unkrich|author=T.J. & Julie|url=http://www.pixarpost.com/2017/08/pixar-coco-orchestration.html|work=Pixar Post|date=August 17, 2017|accessdate=August 20, 2017}}</ref> The score was released on November 10, 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|title=First listen: Hear three new songs from Pixar's Coco|first=Marc|last=Snetiker|url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/09/15/pixar-coco-songs/|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|date=September 15, 2017|accessdate=September 15, 2017}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the [[90th Academy Awards]] ceremony, where \"Remember Me\" won the award for [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]], the album broke the top 40 on the [[Billboard 200]] charts, jumping from 120 to 39,<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/amp/articles/columns/chart-beat/8241251/coco-soundtrack-hits-top-40-billboard-200-after-oscars|title='Coco' Soundtrack Hits Top 40 on Billboard 200 Chart After Oscars, Plus: Gains for Sufjan Stevens, 'The Greatest Showman' & More|website=www.billboard.com}}</ref> where it peaked before dropping to 64.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/charts/billboard-200/2018-03-24|title=Top 200 Albums - Billboard 200 chart|publisher=}}</ref> In the week of March 8, the Miguel version of \"Remember Me\" gained 1.58{{nbsp}}million plays via online streaming, according to the Nielsen Music.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n{{Track listing\n| extra_column = Performer(s)\n| total_length = 79:09\n| all_music = [[Michael Giacchino]] except where indicated\n| title1 = [[Remember Me (Coco song)|Remember Me]]\n| writer1 = [[Kristen Anderson-Lopez]] & [[Robert Lopez]]\n| extra1 = [[Benjamin Bratt]]\n| length1 = 1:49\n| title2 = Much Needed Advice\n| writer2 = [[Germaine Franco]], [[Michael Giacchino]], & [[Adrian Molina]]\n| extra2 = Bratt & Antonio Sol\n| length2 = 1:45\n| title3 = Everyone Knows Juanita\n| writer3 = Franco & Molina\n| extra3 = [[Gael Garc\u00eda Bernal]]\n| length3 = 1:15\n| title4 = Un Poco Loco\n| writer4 = Franco & Molina\n| extra4 = Garc\u00eda Bernal & [[Anthony Gonzalez (actor)|Anthony Gonzalez]]\n| length4 = 1:52\n| title5 = J\u00e1lale (Instrumental)\n| writer5 = Holger Beier, Pat Beier, & [[Camilo Lara]]\n| extra5 = [[Mexican Institute of Sound]]\n| length5 = 2:54\n| title6 = The World Es Mi Familia\n| writer6 = Franco & Molina\n