|title37         = One Year Later\n|writer37        =\n|extra37         =\n|length37        = 1:01\n|title38         = Coco \u2013 D\u00eda de los Muertos Suite\n|writer38        =\n|extra38         =\n|length38        = 5:47\n\n|}}\n\n==Marketing and release==\nThe first teaser of ''Coco'' was released on March 15, 2017, two days before Disney's ''[[Beauty and the Beast (2017 film)|Beauty and the Beast]]'' opened worldwide.<ref name=\"F\"/> The teaser trailer introduced the basic concept of the film, while highlighting its focus on music.<ref name=\"SF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/coco-trailer/ |title='Coco' Trailer: Pixar's Next Original Movie Reveals Its First Footage |first=Jacob|last=Hall |publisher=[[/Film]] |date=March 15, 2017 |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315161314/http://www.slashfilm.com/coco-trailer/ |archivedate=March 15, 2017 }}</ref> Scott Mendelson of ''[[Forbes]]'' praised the trailer as \"a terrific old-school Pixar sell, mostly consisting of a single sequence and offering just the barest hint of what's to come.\"<ref name=\"F\"/> The film's themes and imagery drew comparison to another animated film that centered around D\u00eda de Muertos, ''[[The Book of Life (2014 film)|The Book of Life]]'' (2014).<ref name=\"SF\"/><ref name=\"EP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.empireonline.com/people/gael-garcia-bernal/first-teaser-trailer-pixar-coco/ |title=First Teaser Trailer For Pixar's Coco |first=James|last=White |work=[[Empire (magazine)|Empire]] |date=March 15, 2017 |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315173627/http://www.empireonline.com/people/gael-garcia-bernal/first-teaser-trailer-pixar-coco/ |archivedate=March 15, 2017 }}</ref> A two-minute short film, titled ''Dante's Lunch \u2013 A Short Tail'', was released online on March 29, 2017. It introduces the film's supporting character, a [[Mexican Hairless Dog|Xoloitzcuintle]] named Dante. The short was created early in the animation process by Unkrich and his team to have a better sense of the character.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Watkins|first1=Gwynne|title=New Pixar Short 'Dante's Lunch' Introduces 'Coco' Dog, Plus Director Lee Unkrich on Whether 'Coco' Will Make You Cry (Exclusive)|url=https://www.yahoo.com/movies/new-pixar-short-dantes-lunch-introduces-coco-dog-plus-director-lee-unkrich-on-whether-coco-will-make-you-cry-exclusive-155901674.html|publisher=Yahoo! Movies|accessdate=April 1, 2017|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170401142909/https://www.yahoo.com/movies/new-pixar-short-dantes-lunch-introduces-coco-dog-plus-director-lee-unkrich-on-whether-coco-will-make-you-cry-exclusive-155901674.html|archivedate=April 1, 2017|date=March 29, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe first official trailer was released on June 7, 2017,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lawrence|first1=Derek|title=Coco: New trailer digs deeper into the Land of the Dead|url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/06/07/coco-new-trailer-land-of-the-dead/|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|accessdate=September 18, 2017|date=June 7, 2017}}</ref> followed by a second trailer on September 13.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Mendelson|first1=Scott|title=Trailer: 'Coco' May Help Pixar Bounce Back From 'Cars 3'|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2017/09/13/trailer-coco-may-help-pixar-bounce-back-from-cars-3/|work=[[Forbes]]|accessdate=September 18, 2017|date=September 13, 2017}}</ref> The film was marketed extensively in Mexico, including traditional wall-painted advertising usually used for local events and never for films.<!-- WP:RS needed; removed link to WP:SPS (Twitter, FB, WP)--> [[Cin\u00e9polis]], a movie chain in the country, held a contest for dubbing a character in the film,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cinepolis.com/coco/ganadores|title=Inmortaliza Tu Voz|first=IA|last=Interactive|website=Cinepolis.com|accessdate=November 24, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171214112245/http://www.cinepolis.com/coco/ganadores|archive-date=December 14, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> and another movie chain held a contest to become an interviewer for the cast and crew of the film.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ganapromo.com/concursos/conviertete-en-el-reportero-cinemex-y-entrevista-a-los-creadores-de-coco/|title=Convi\u00e9rtete en el reportero Cinemex y entrevista a los creadores de Coco|website=Ganapromo.com|accessdate=November 24, 2017}}</ref>\n\n''Coco'' was released in Mexico on October 27, 2017, the weekend before D\u00eda de los Muertos. The film was released in the United States on November 22, 2017, during the [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving]] weekend, and three weeks after D\u00eda de los Muertos, and in the United Kingdom on January 19, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dcm.co.uk/news/latest-film-release-changes-coco-pops-in-2018|title=Latest film release changes: Coco pops in 2018|first=Ryan|last=Watson|publisher=[[Digital Cinema Media]]|date=May 10, 2017|accessdate=May 10, 2017}}</ref> The film was released in a crowded market, preceded by ''[[Thor: Ragnarok]]'', ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]'' and another animated film, ''[[The Star (2017 film)|The Star]]'', and followed by ''[[Star Wars: The Last Jedi]]'' and another animated film, ''[[Ferdinand (film)|Ferdinand]]'', three weeks after Thanksgiving. It is one of the three Disney film productions being released in the November\u2013December corridor.<ref name=\"F\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2017/03/15/pixars-coco-is-trapped-between-justice-league-and-star-wars/ |title=Pixar's 'Coco' Is Trapped Between 'Justice League' And 'Star Wars' |first=Scott|last=Mendelson |work=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] |date=March 15, 2017 |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315171554/https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2017/03/15/pixars-coco-is-trapped-between-justice-league-and-star-wars/ |archivedate=March 15, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n''Coco'' is the second Pixar offering of the year, following ''[[Cars 3]]'', with 2017 being the second year Pixar released two films, after 2015 (with ''[[Inside Out (2015 film)|Inside Out]]'' and ''[[The Good Dinosaur]]'').<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.avclub.com/article/strum-along-first-teaser-pixars-coco-252106 |title=Strum along with the first teaser for Pixar's Coco |first=Esther|last=Zuckerman |publisher=[[The A.V. Club]] |date=March 15, 2017 |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315171039/http://www.avclub.com/article/strum-along-first-teaser-pixars-coco-252106 |archivedate=March 15, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/coco-trailer-pixar-new-original-film-2017-release-date-a7631396.html |title=Coco trailer: First footage from Pixar Studio's upcoming original film released |first=Jack|last=Shepherd |work=[[The Independent]] |date=March 15, 2017 |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315222018/http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/news/coco-trailer-pixar-new-original-film-2017-release-date-a7631396.html |archivedate=March 15, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/mar/15/pixar-film-coco-trailer-launch |title=First trailer launched for new Pixar film Coco |work=[[The Guardian]] |date=March 15, 2017 |accessdate=March 15, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170315155014/https://www.theguardian.com/film/2017/mar/15/pixar-film-coco-trailer-launch |archivedate=March 15, 2017 }}</ref> The film was accompanied in theaters by [[Walt Disney Animation Studios]]' 21-minute featurette ''[[Olaf's Frozen Adventure]]'' as a limited time offering,<ref>{{cite web|last=Booth|first=Kaitlyn|title=Olaf's Frozen Adventure Trailer For The 21-Minute Featurette In Front Of Coco|url=https://www.bleedingcool.com/2017/06/13/olafs-frozen-adventure-trailer-featurette-front-coco/|publisher=[[Bleeding Cool]]|accessdate=December 2, 2017|date=June 13, 2017}}</ref> featuring the characters from ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]'', making ''Coco'' the first Pixar film not to be accompanied by a Pixar short in theaters since their first film, ''[[Toy Story]]'', in 1995.<ref>{{cite web|last=Snetiker |first=Marc |title=John Lasseter talks Olaf's Frozen Adventure, debuts first look |url=http://ew.com/movies/2017/06/13/olafs-frozen-adventure-john-lasseter-exclusive/ |work=[[Entertainment Weekly]] |accessdate=June 13, 2017 |date=June 13, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170613201807/http://ew.com/movies/2017/06/13/olafs-frozen-adventure-john-lasseter-exclusive/ |archivedate=June 13, 2017 }}</ref> The film also has its own VR game, being Pixar's first VR development.<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://variety.com/2017/digital/news/pixar-coco-vr-1202587504/|title=Pixar Makes Its Virtual Reality Debut With 'Coco VR'|first=Janko|last=Roettgers|date=October 11, 2017|website=Variety|accessdate=November 6, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Home media===\n''Coco'' was released for High Definition online streaming and digital download on February 13, 2018, and on [[DVD]], [[Blu-ray]], and [[4K Ultra HD Blu-ray]] on February 27, 2018, by [[Walt Disney Studios Home Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thekingdominsider.com/coco-blu-ray-dvd-and-digital-release-date-is-february-27-2018/|title='Coco' Blu-ray and DVD Release Date is February 27, 2018|website=The Kingdom Insider|date=January 15, 2018|accessdate=February 17, 2018}}</ref> ''Coco'' became available on [[Netflix]] in the United States on May 29,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whats-on-netflix.com/news/disneys-coco-will-be-on-netflix-in-2018/|title=Disney's Coco will be on Netflix in May 2018|website=What's on Netflix|date=April 25, 2018|accessdate=April 25, 2018}}</ref> before transferring to [[Disney+]] on November 29, 2019.\n\n==Reception==\n===Box office===\n''Coco'' grossed $209.7{{nbsp}}million in the United States and Canada, and $597.3{{nbsp}}million in other countries, for a worldwide total of $807.1{{nbsp}}million.<ref name=BOM/>\n\n====Mexico====\n\n''Coco'' was released in Mexico on October 27, nearly a month before its release in the United States. It grossed $9.3{{nbsp}}million on its opening weekend, the biggest opening weekend for an original animated film and the biggest debut for an animated film outside of the summer movie season in the market.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/10/thor-ragnarok-opening-weekend-results-blade-runner-china-coco-international-box-office-1202196942/|title='Thor: Ragnarok' Thunders To $109M In Overseas Debut \u2013 International Box Office|first=Nancy | last=Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=October 31, 2017|accessdate=November 5, 2017}}</ref> In its second weekend, it earned another $10.8{{nbsp}}million, a 12% increase over its first weekend, bringing its total to $28{{nbsp}}million. It became the fastest ten-day grosser ever for an animated feature in Mexico, as well as the biggest original animated release ever in the territory.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2017/11/05/box-office-blade-runner-2049-nears-240m-coco-soars-in-mexico/|title=Box Office: 'Blade Runner 2049' Nears $240M, 'Coco' Soars In Mexico|first=Scott | last=Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=November 5, 2017|accessdate=November 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/thor-ragnarok-china-weekend-results-international-box-office-1202202193/|title='Thor: Ragnarok' & Rolls To $431M WW, $308M Offshore With Record November China Start \u2013 International Box Office|first=Nancy | last=Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 6, 2017|accessdate=November 8, 2017}}</ref> It dropped by 23% in its third weekend, grossing $8.4{{nbsp}}million. That brought its total to MX$792{{nbsp}}million (US$41.4{{nbsp}}million), making it the highest-grossing animated film and the second-highest-grossing film of all time in Mexico, behind Marvel's ''[[The Avengers (2012 film)|The Avengers]]'', in local currency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/thor-ragnarok-murder-on-the-orient-express-paddington-2-coco-china-international-box-office-weekend-results-1202206533/|title='Thor' Rocks $650M WW; 'Orient Express' Rolls $57M Offshore; 'Coco', 'Paddington 2' Feel Embrace \u2013 International Box Office|first=Nancy | last=Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 12, 2017|accessdate=November 12, 2017}}</ref> A few days later, on November 15, it passed ''The Avengers'' to become the highest-grossing film in the Mexican market.<ref name=MexicoRecord1/><ref name=MexicoRecord2/><ref name=MexicoRecord3/><ref name=MexicoRecord4/>\n\n====United States and Canada====\nIn the United States and Canada, ''Coco'' was projected to gross $55\u201365{{nbsp}}million from 3,987 theaters in its first five days, including around $40{{nbsp}}million in its opening weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/justice-league-coco-gal-gadot-wonder-roman-j-israel-esq-thanksgiving-box-office-1202212680/|title=Can 'Coco' Whip 'Justice League' For Top Spot Over Thanksgiving Stretch? \u2013 Box Office Preview|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 20, 2017|accessdate=November 20, 2017}}</ref> It made $2.3{{nbsp}}million from Tuesday night previews, landing between Disney's previous two November releases ''[[Moana (2016 film)|Moana]]'' ($2.6{{nbsp}}million) and ''[[The Good Dinosaur]]'' ($1.3{{nbsp}}million), and $13.2{{nbsp}}million on its first day. It went on to debut to $50.8{{nbsp}}million (including a five-day total of $72.9{{nbsp}}million), finishing first at the box office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/box-office-top-20-coco-displaces-justice-league/2017/11/27/675715a0-d3c9-11e7-9ad9-ca0619edfa05_story.html|title=Box office top 20: 'Coco' displaces 'Justice League'|agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=November 26, 2017|accessdate=November 28, 2017}}</ref> It was the 4th-biggest [[Thanksgiving (United States)|Thanksgiving]] opening weekend ever, behind fellow animated films ''[[Frozen (2013 film)|Frozen]]'', ''Moana'', and ''[[Toy Story 2]]''.<ref name=opening>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/coco-justice-league-wonder-thanksgiving-box-office-1202213755/|title=Thanksgiving B.O. At $268M, +3% Over 2016 Spurred By 'Coco' & Holdovers \u2013 Sunday Update |first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=November 26, 2017|accessdate=November 26, 2017}}</ref> In its second weekend, the film dropped by 46% to $27.5{{nbsp}}million, a smaller drop than ''Moana'', ''Frozen'', ''Tangled'', and ''The Good Dinosaur'', and again topping the box office.<ref name=second>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/12/coco-three-billboards-shape-of-water-wonder-post-thanksgiving-weekend-box-office-1202217467/|title='Coco' Looking At Sweet $26M+ As Specialty Sector Pops With Awards Contenders \u2013 Sunday Final|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 3, 2017|accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref><ref name=weekend2global>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/scottmendelson/2017/12/03/box-office-coco-soars-to-280m-worldwide-wonder-tops-100m-global/#478183985408|title=Box Office: 'Coco' Soars To $280M Worldwide, 'Wonder' Tops $100M Global|first=Scott | last=Mendelson |work=[[Forbes]] |date=December 3, 2017|accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> It topped the box office once again in its third weekend, dropping by 33% and grossing $18.5{{nbsp}}million, a similar hold to ''Moana''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/12/box-office-coco-the-disaster-artist-guillermo-del-toro-shape-of-water-margot-robbie-i-tonya-1202223071/|title=December Still Asleep Before 'Last Jedi' Awakens: 'Coco' $18M+, 'Disaster Artist' $6M+, 'Wonder' Crosses $100M|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 10, 2017|accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref> It became the fourth film of 2017 to top the box office three times, following ''[[Split (2016 American film)|Split]]'', ''[[The Fate of the Furious]]'' and ''[[The Hitman's Bodyguard]]'', before being overtaken by Disney's own ''[[Star Wars: The Last Jedi]]'' and another animated film, '' [[Ferdinand (film)|Ferdinand]]'', in its fourth weekend.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/box-office/coco-box-office-star-wars-last-jedi-1202635245/|title=Box Office: 'Coco' Wins as 'Star Wars: The Last Jedi' Waits in the Wings|first=Dave | last=McNary |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=December 10, 2017|accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/12/the-last-jedi-star-wars-opening-box-office-records-1202228444/|title='The Last Jedi' Opens To $220M & Will Send 2017 To $11B: How Disney Still Wins With 'Star Wars' Franchise \u2013 Monday Final|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 18, 2017|accessdate=December 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIt fell to number six in its fifth weekend, due to competition from three new releases \u2013 ''[[Jumanji: Welcome to the Jungle]]'', ''[[Pitch Perfect 3]]'', and ''[[The Greatest Showman]]'' \u2013 despite a small drop again; it grossed $2.8{{nbsp}}million on Christmas Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/12/last-jedi-dwayne-johnson-jumanji-zac-efron-greatest-showman-box-office-1202230784/|title='Last Jedi' Now At $99M, 'Jumanji' Huge At $72M+; 'All The Money In The World' Opens To $2.6M \u2013 Christmas Weekend|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 26, 2017|accessdate=December 31, 2017}}</ref> On the holiday week of December 22\u201328, the film finished at number six with a gross of $16.3{{nbsp}}million, which was 6% up from the previous week, despite losing over 1,000 theaters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=weekly&id=pixar1117.htm|title=Coco (2017) \u2013 Weekly Box Office Results|work=Box Office Mojo|date=December 29, 2017|accessdate=December 31, 2016}}</ref> It finished at number six in its sixth weekend, going up 39% and 87%, respectively, during the three-day<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2017&wknd=52&p=.htm|title=December 29 \u2013 31, 2017|work=Box Office Mojo|date=January 2, 2018|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref> and four-day weekends;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2017&wknd=52a&p=.htm|title=December 29 \u2013 January 1, 2018|work=Box Office Mojo|date=January 2, 2018|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref> it grossed $2.6{{nbsp}}million on New Year's Day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/daily/chart/?sortdate=2018-01-01&track=pixar1117.htm|title=Daily Box Office for Monday, January 1, 2018|work=Box Office Mojo|date=January 2, 2018|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref> It fell outside the top 10 in its eighth weekend (which included [[Martin Luther King Jr. Day]]), dropping 38% and 14% respectively, during the three-day<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2018&wknd=02&p=.htm|title=January 12\u201314, 2018|work=Box Office Mojo|date=January 16, 2018|accessdate=January 22, 2018}}</ref> and four-day weekends.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/weekend/chart/?yr=2018&wknd=02a&p=.htm|title=January 12\u201315, 2017|work=Box Office Mojo|date=January 16, 2018|accessdate=January 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n====Other countries====\n\nIn China, ''Coco'' finished number one at the weekend box office, with a three-day total of $18.2{{nbsp}}million, making it the second-highest opening ever for a Disney or Pixar animated release in that market, behind ''[[Zootopia]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/coco-debuts-at-number-one-in-china/5124495.article|title='Coco' debuts at number one in China|first=Elbert | last=Wyche |work=Screen Daily |date=November 26, 2017|accessdate=November 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/11/justice-league-thor-ragnarok-coco-weekend-results-international-box-office-1202214590/|title='Justice League' Tops $300M Overseas; 'Coco' Charms China & 'Thor' Rocks Near $800M WW \u2013 International Box Office|first=Nancy | last=Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=November 26, 2017|accessdate=November 26, 2017}}</ref> After seeing increases each weekday on its first week,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2017/12/01/coco-rockets-to-epic-300-friday-to-friday-gain-in-china-for-39m-8-day-cume/#1dde64ff5eb1|title='Coco' Rockets To Epic 300% Friday-To-Friday Gain In China For $39M 8-Day Cume|first=Rob | last=Cain |work=[[Forbes]] |date=December 1, 2017|accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> the film increased by 148% on its second weekend, bringing its total to $75.6{{nbsp}}million in the market.<ref name=weekend2global/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/12/coco-thor-ragnarok-justice-league-china-weekend-results-international-box-office-1202219137/|title=Hot 'Coco' Sings In China; 'Thor' Tops $816M, 'Justice League' Lassos $567M WW \u2013 International Box Office|first=Nancy | last=Tartaglione |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=December 3, 2017|accessdate=December 3, 2017}}</ref> It dropped by 21% in its third weekend, finishing first once again and grossing $35{{nbsp}}Million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/box-office/coco-international-box-office-justice-league-2-1202635329/|title=Box Office: 'Coco' Stays Strong With $55 Million at International Box Office|first=Dave | last=McNary |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=December 10, 2017|accessdate=December 10, 2017}}</ref> The film fell to number three in its fourth weekend, due to competition from two new domestic releases, grossing an additional $17.1{{nbsp}}million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/china-box-office-feng-xiaogangs-youth-opens-48m-coco-crosses-150m-1068785|title=China Box Office: Feng Xiaogang's 'Youth' Opens to $48M, 'Coco' Crosses $150M|first=Patrick | last=Brzeski |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=December 17, 2017|accessdate= January 1, 2018}}</ref> ''Coco's'' success in China came as a surprise to most box office analysts who were projecting a gross of $30\u201340{{nbsp}}million. By its second weekend, it had become the highest-grossing Pixar release ever in China, nearly doubling previous record-holder ''[[Finding Dory]]'', and by its fifth weekend, it had surpassed ''[[Despicable Me 3]]'' to become the second highest-grossing animated movie of all time in the country, behind ''Zootopia''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2017/12/16/with-1-billion-rmb-152m-cume-coco-has-now-quadrupled-pixars-previous-china-record/#5e58389a2d49|title=With 1 Billion+ RMB / $152M Cume 'Coco' Has Now Quadrupled Pixar's Previous China Record|first=Rob | last=Cain |work=[[Forbes]] |date=December 16, 2017|accessdate=December 26, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/robcain/2017/12/26/coco-has-single-handedly-out-grossed-the-earnings-of-all-12-prior-pixar-releases-in-china-combined/#1ae1a62f3412|title='Coco' Has Single-Handedly Out-Grossed The Earnings of All 12 Prior Pixar Releases In China Combined|first=Rob | last=Cain |work=[[Forbes]] |date=December 26, 2017|accessdate=January 1, 2018}}</ref> The movie was released in Japan, its final market, on March 16, 2018. {{as of|2018|May|1|df=US}} the film's largest markets were China ($189.2{{nbsp}}million), Mexico ($57.8{{nbsp}}million), Japan ($41.4{{nbsp}}million),  France ($33.2{{nbsp}}million), United Kingdom ($26.1{{nbsp}}million), South Korea ($25.9{{nbsp}}million), Spain ($21.4{{nbsp}}million), Argentina ($17.6{{nbsp}}million), Italy ($14.4{{nbsp}}million) and Germany ($12.3{{nbsp}}million).<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2018/05/coco-crosses-800-million-global-box-office-disney-pixar-1202380459/|title='Coco' Sweet With $800M Milestone At Worldwide Box Office|last=Tartaglione|first=Nancy|date=2018-05-01|website=Deadline Hollywood|access-date=2018-05-02|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n===Critical response===\nOn [[review aggregator]] website [[Rotten Tomatoes]], the film holds an approval rating of 97% based on 337 reviews, with an [[average rating]] of 8.3/10. The website's critical consensus reads, \"''Coco''{{'}}s rich visual pleasures are matched by a thoughtful narrative that takes a family-friendly\u2014and deeply affecting\u2014approach to questions of culture, family, life, and death.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/coco_2017|title=Coco (2017)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> It was the site's highest-rated animated film and ninth highest-rated wide release of 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/guide/best-animated-movies-2017/|title=Best-Reviewed Animated Movies 2017|website=Rotten Tomatoes|accessdate=January 4, 2018|date=January 4, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://editorial.rottentomatoes.com/guide/best-movies-2017-wide-release/|title=BEST-REVIEWED MOVIES 2017 > WIDE RELEASES|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|publisher=[[Fandango (company)|Fandango]]|accessdate=January 4, 2018|date=January 4, 2018}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], which assigns a normalized rating to reviews, the film has a weighted average score of 81 out of 100, based on 48 critics, indicating \"universal acclaim.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/movie/coco-2017 |title=Coco Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=January 16, 2018}}</ref> Audiences polled by [[CinemaScore]] gave the film a grade of \"A+\" on an A+ to F scale, one of fewer than 90 films in the history of the service to receive such a score; it was also the sixth Pixar film to earn the rating \u2013 the previous being ''[[Up (2009 film)|Up]]'' in 2009.<ref name=opening/> It also earned a 95% positive score, including a rare five-out-of-five rating, from filmgoers on [[PostTrak]], along with a 76% \"definite recommend\".<ref name=second/>\n\nMichael Rechtshaffen of ''[[The Hollywood Reporter]]'' said, \"At every imaginative juncture, the filmmakers (the screenplay is credited to Pixar veteran Molina and Matthew Aldrich) create a richly woven tapestry of comprehensively researched storytelling, fully dimensional characters, clever touches both tender and amusingly macabre, and vivid, beautifully textured visuals.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Rechtshaffen|first=Michael|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/coco-review-1050825|title='Coco': Film Review|newspaper=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|date=October 20, 2017|accessdate=November 10, 2017}}</ref> Robert Abele of ''[[TheWrap]]'' praised the film, saying: \"If an animated movie is going to offer children a way to process death, it's hard to envision a more spirited, touching and breezily entertaining example than ''Coco''.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Abele|first=Robert|url=https://www.thewrap.com/coco-review-pixar-disney-day-of-the-dead-dia-de-los-muertos/|title='Coco' Review: Pixar's Journey Down Mexico Way Pays Colorful, Moving Tribute to Family|newspaper=[[TheWrap]]|date=October 20, 2017|accessdate=October 28, 2017}}</ref> In his review for ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'', Peter Debruge wrote, \"In any case, it works: ''Coco''{{'}}s creators clearly had the perfect ending in mind before they'd nailed down all the other details, and though the movie drags in places, and features a few too many childish gags... the story's sincere emotional resolution earns the sobs it's sure to inspire.\" Debruge also described the film as \"[An] effective yet hardly exceptional addition to the Pixar oeuvre.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Debruge|first=Peter|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/reviews/coco-review-pixar-1202595605/|title=Film Review: Pixar's 'Coco'|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=October 20, 2017|accessdate=October 28, 2017}}</ref> [[Matt Zoller Seitz]] of [[RogerEbert.com]] gave the film four out of four, writing that \"There's a touch of Japanese master [[Hayao Miyazaki]] in the film's matter-of-fact depiction of the dead interacting with the living, as well as its portrayal of certain creatures\" such as Dante and Pepita. He concluded his review by stating, \"I had some minor quibbles about [''Coco''] while I was watching it, but I can't remember what they were. This film is a classic.\"<ref>{{cite web|last1=Seitz|first1=Matt Zoller|authorlink1=Matt Zoller Seitz|title=Coco Movie Review & Film Summary (2017)|url=https://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/coco-2017|website=[[RogerEbert.com]]|accessdate=November 24, 2017|date=November 21, 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[Peter Travers]] of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' rated the film 3.5 out of four, calling it a \"loving tribute to Mexican culture\", while praising the animation, vocal performances (particularly of Gonzalez, Garc\u00eda Bernal, and Bratt), and its emotional and thematic tone and depth.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/movies/reviews/peter-travers-pixars-day-of-the-dead-coco-is-as-lively-as-they-come-w512244|title='Coco' Review: Pixar's Day-of-the-Dead Gem Is as Lively as They Come|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|first=Peter|last=Travers|date=November 25, 2017|accessdate=November 25, 2017}}</ref> The ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''{{'}}s [[Michael Phillips (critic)|Michael Phillips]] called the film \"vividly good, beautifully animated\", praising Giacchino's musical score and the songs, as well drawing a comparison to the emotional tone of ''[[Inside Out (2015 film)|Inside Out]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/movies/sc-mov-coco-review-1121-story.html|title='Coco' review: While not Pixar's best, 'Coco' is 'vividly good,' beautifully animated|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|first=Michael | last=Phillips |date=November 21, 2017|accessdate=November 29, 2017}}</ref> [[A. O. Scott]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' praised the film as \"a time-tested tune with captivating originality and flair, and with roving, playful pop-culture erudition\", and called the film's cultural vibe \"inclusive\" and \"a 21st-century Disney hallmark\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/21/movies/coco-review-pixar-disney.html|date=November 21, 2017|title=Review: 'Coco' Brings the Pixar Touch to Death|work=[[The New York Times]]|first=A. O. |last=Scott|author-link=A. O. Scott}}</ref> [[Richard Roeper]] of the ''[[Chicago Sun-Times]]'' found the film to be \"full of life\" and deemed it \"a bouncy and heart-tugging adventure\", while lauding the vocal performances as \"fantastic\" and \"first-rate\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/the-exciting-land-of-the-dead-is-where-coco-really-comes-to-life/|title=The exciting Land of the Dead is where 'Coco' really comes to life|first=Richard |last=Roeper|author-link=Richard Roeper|date=November 21, 2017|accessdate=November 30, 2017|work=[[Chicago Sun-Times]]}}</ref> Brian Truitt of ''[[USA Today]]'' described the film as \"effervescent, clever and thoughtful,\" calling it one of \"Pixar's most gorgeously animated outings\", and \"the most musical Pixar film, with a host of catchy tunes\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2017/11/21/review-joyful-coco-breaks-pixar-pack-mexican-musical-spectacular/882699001/|date=November 21, 2017|title=Review: Joyful 'Coco' breaks from the Pixar pack as a Mexican musical spectacular|work=[[USA Today]]|first=Brian |last=Truitt}}</ref> Stephen Whitty of the ''[[Newark Star-Ledger]]'' wrote that the backgrounds \"have a vibrancy, and its atmosphere carries a warmth. And even after it's done, both linger, just a bit\u2014like a perfectly struck guitar chord\".<ref>{{cite web|title='Coco' review: Disney and Pixar set out a Mexican feast|url=http://www.nj.com/entertainment/index.ssf/2017/11/coco_review_disney_and_pixar_set_out_a_mexican_fea.html|work=[[New York Daily News]]|accessdate=December 1, 2017|date=November 22, 2017|first=Stephen|last=Whitty}}</ref>\n\n===Accolades===\n{{Main|List of accolades received by Coco (2017 film)}}\n''Coco'' was nominated for various awards and won a number of them, including several for Best Animated Feature.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/feature/2017-film-awards-and-nominations-scorecard?|title=Best of 2017: Film Awards and Nominations Scorecard|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=January 3, 2018}}</ref> The song \"[[Remember Me (Pixar song)|Remember Me]]\" was particularly praised. At the [[75th Golden Globe Awards]], it won [[Golden Globe Award for Best Animated Feature Film|Best Animated Feature Film]]  while it was nominated for [[Golden Globe Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]] for the song, \"Remember Me\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2017/film/news/golden-globe-nominations-2018-nominees-full-list-1202634435/|title=Golden Globe Nominations: Complete List|last=Rubin|first=Rebecca|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=December 11, 2017|accessdate=December 11, 2017}}</ref> It led the [[45th Annie Awards]] with most nominations, garnering thirteen, among them [[Annie Award for Best Animated Feature|Best Animated Feature]], [[Annie Award for Directing in a Feature Production|Outstanding Achievement for Directing in an Animated Feature Production]], [[Annie Award for Writing in a Feature Production|Outstanding Achievement for Writing in an Animated Feature Production]], and [[Annie Award for Voice Acting in a Feature Production|Outstanding Achievement for Voice Acting in an Animated Feature Production]] for Gonzalez.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://deadline.com/2017/12/annie-awards-nominations-coco-the-breadwinner-full-list-1202219487/|title=Annie Awards: Disney/Pixar's 'Coco' Tops Nominations|last=Hipes|first=Patrick|website=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=December 4, 2017|accessdate=December 4, 2017}}</ref> At the [[90th Academy Awards]], it won the [[Academy Award for Best Animated Feature|Best Animated Feature]] and [[Academy Award for Best Original Song|Best Original Song]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/03/04/arts/oscar-winners.html|title=The 2018 Oscar Winners: Full List|date=March 4, 2018|work=The New York Times|accessdate=March 5, 2018}}</ref>  ''Coco'' was chosen by the [[National Board of Review]] as the [[National Board of Review Award for Best Animated Film|Best Animated Film]] of 2017.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nationalboardofreview.org/2017/11/national-board-review-announces-2017-award-winners/|title=National Board of Review Announces 2017 Award Winners|date=November 28, 2017|publisher=[[National Board of Review]]|accessdate=December 7, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy===\nIn 2018, news outlets discovered that Disney Pixar had failed to disclose that producers for ''Coco'' had based the character of \"Mama Coco\" on Mar\u00eda de la Salud Ram\u00edrez Caballero from the [[Pur\u00e9pecha]] village of [[Santa Fe de la Laguna]], \"a town of Pur\u00e9pecha potters in [[Quiroga, Michoac\u00e1n|Quiroga]], [[Michoac\u00e1n]].\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mexiconewsdaily.com/news/mama-coco-recognized-in-purepecha-town/|title=\u2018Mam\u00e1 Coco\u2019 recognized in Pur\u00e9pecha town in Michoac\u00e1n|date=December 31, 2018|website=Mexico News Daily|access-date=July 16, 2019}}</ref> In a news interview, Salud stated that the producers \"offered me so many things, but nothing came of it. They only came and took my picture and took it with them. They asked me what I need. Well, look at how I live and alone. My daughters live here, behind the house. And I'm here alone, that's what I have.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8YObt5BAqVw|title=The person who inspired Mama Coco|work=New China TV|access-date=July 16, 2019}}</ref> In a report by [[Telemundo]], residents and artisans of Santa Fe da la Laguna recognized that the attention Salud has received by people throughout the world has increased tourism for the town.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6aoYVi2v2UI|title=\u00a1Te presentamos a la mujer que inspir\u00f3 a \"mam\u00e1 Coco\"!|date=November 2, 2018|work=Telemundo|access-date=July 16, 2019}}</ref> Gabriela Gabriel Fabi\u00e1n, a potter of the town, noted that \"It has benefited us because many more tourists come. This town is known because of the lady's fame, they buy our artwork, everything we do and figures of her.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.eluniversal.com.mx/english/woman-behind-mama-coco|title=The woman behind Mam\u00e1 Coco|last=Arrieta|first=Carlos|date=December 31, 2018|website=El Universal|access-date=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWhile the production team at Disney Pixar have recognized that they \"based the Rivera family \u2013 a multigenerational matriarchy headed by Miguel\u2019s formidable grandmother \u2013 on real-world families with whom they embedded while visiting the Mexican states of [[Oaxaca]] and [[Guanajuato]] between 2011 and 2013,\" they have not acknowledged Salud's contribution to the film.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/19/movies/coco-pixar-politics.html|title=How Pixar Made Sure \u2018Coco\u2019 Was Culturally Conscious|last=Ugwu|first=Reggie|date=November 19, 2017|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 16, 2019}}</ref> Co-director Adrian Molina stated, \"not only is [''Coco''] based in a real place, in Mexico, but it\u2019s based in real traditions, so we knew it was very important to do the research, to get every detail recorded, so that when we get back to Pixar and we start deciding what is this town going to look like, what is this grandmother going to wear, what kind of dancing and music are they going to listen to, it can all come from an informed place.\" However, Salud remains unmentioned in all reports Disney Pixar have made regarding inspiration for the film.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ohmy.disney.com/news/2018/02/27/mexico-pixar-coco-research-trip/|title=We Took a Trip to Mexico With the Filmmakers Behind Disney Pixar\u2019s Coco|last=Uribe|first=Mariana|date=2018|website=Oh My Disney|access-date=July 16, 2019}}</ref>\n\nSalud reported that since the release of the film, many people, even internationally, have visited her and will refer to her as \"Mama Coco.\" In response, she replied, \"Yes, but [\"Mama Coco's\"] not my name. [The producers] chose that name. And now all the people who come and visit tell us that's my name. But I tell them no, it's not my name. My name is Mar\u00eda de la Salud.\"<ref name=\":0\" /> Prior to the film's release, Salud was diagnosed with [[chronic obstructive pulmonary disease]] (COPD), and now she has to use oxygen tanks to breathe. The family however has expressed that they \"aren't looking to receive royalties, or money, despite her grandmother's need to recharge her oxygen tank every two days.\" They are, however, asking \"that the company acknowledge her contribution\" to the film, which has yet to occur.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n{{reflist|group=lower-alpha}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Official|http://movies.disney.com/coco}}\n* {{IMDb title|2380307}}\n* {{Tcmdb title|2073302|Coco}}\n* {{Bcdb title|141576}}\n* {{Allmovie title|563671|Coco}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|coco_2017|Coco}}\n\n{{Disney theatrical animated features}}\n{{Pixar}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = [[List of accolades received by Coco (2017 film)|Awards for ''Coco'']]\n|list  =\n{{Academy Award Best Animated Feature}}\n{{Annie Award for Best Animated Feature}}\n{{BAFTA Award for Best Animated Film}}\n{{Broadcast Film Critics Association Award for Best Animated Feature}}\n{{Golden Globe Award for Best Animated Feature Film}}\n{{Producers Guild of America Award for Best Animated Motion Picture}}\n{{Satellite Award Best Animated or Mixed Media Feature Film}}\n{{Saturn Award for Best Animated Film}}\n{{Teen Choice Award Choice Movie Sci-Fi/Fantasy}}\n}}\n{{Portal bar|Disney|Cartoon|Animation}}\n\n[[Category:3D animated films]]\n[[Category:2010s adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2010s children's fantasy films]]\n[[Category:2010s fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:2010s comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s ghost films]]\n[[Category:2017 3D films]]\n[[Category:2017 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2017 films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American adventure comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated adventure films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:American children's animated fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American comedy-drama films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy-comedy films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American ghost films]]\n[[Category:Animated comedy films]]\n[[Category:Animated coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Animated films about death]]\n[[Category:Annie Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature Annie Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature BAFTA winners]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature Broadcast Film Critics Association Award winners]]\n[[Category:Best Animated Feature Film Golden Globe winners]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Frida Kahlo]]\n[[Category:Day of the Dead films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about children]]\n[[Category:Films about families]]\n[[Category:Films about guitars and guitarists]]\n[[Category:Films about old age]]\n[[Category:Films about music and musicians]]\n[[Category:Films about the afterlife]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Lee Unkrich]]\n[[Category:Films featuring anthropomorphic characters]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michael Giacchino]]\n[[Category:Films set in Mexico]]\n[[Category:Films that won the Best Original Song Academy Award]]\n[[Category:IMAX films]]\n[[Category:Mexican culture]]\n[[Category:Pixar animated films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "Wasaydominickcobb", "label": "safe", "comment": "Not needed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coco_(2017_film)"}
{"title_page": "Chrism Mass", "text_new": "[[File:P Villanueva Messe im Lateran.jpg|thumb|Chrism Mass in the [[Lateran Basilica]]]]\nThe '''Chrism Mass''' is a religious service held in Roman Catholicism, Lutheranism, and Anglicanism.<ref name=\"ELCA2013\">{{cite book|title=How is oil used in worship?|year=2013|publisher=[[Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]]|language=English|page=2|quote=This service, also called a Chrism Mass, is held during Holy Week and presided over by a synodical bishop. At this unique liturgy, the blessing of oil is coupled with a renewal of vows for rostered leaders. The traditional day for this service is Holy Thursday (when some traditions believe the first ordinations took place).}}</ref><ref name=Tennessee>[http://edtn.org/chrism-mass-2017/ \"Chrism Mass 2017\", The Episcopal Diocese of Tennessee]</ref>\n\n[[Holy Thursday]] is notable for being the day on which the Chrism Mass is celebrated in each [[diocese]]. The Chrism Mass is one of the most solemn and important liturgies of the liturgical year. Usually held in the diocesean [[cathedral]], it is generally held on the morning of Holy Thursday, but may in some dioceses take place on another day during Holy Week.<ref>[http://catholicexchange.com/what-is-the-chrism-mass Saunders, William. \"What is the Chrism Mass?\", ''Arlington Catholic Herald'', March 23, 2017]</ref> It is often the largest annual gathering of clergy and faithful held in most dioceses.<ref name=Jalbert>[https://www.catholicnh.org/worship-and-sacraments/faith/worship/chrism/ Jalbert, Jason. \"Chrism Mass\", Diocese of Manchester (New Hampshire)]</ref> In some dioceses, attendance is sufficiently significant that, due to limited seating, tickets are distributed to parishes.<ref>[http://www.thebostonpilot.com/article.asp?ID=179001 \"Chrism Mass 2017\", Diocese of Green Bay]</ref> The Mass is a celebration of the institution of the priesthood with Jesus' words at the Last Supper, \"Do this in memory of me.\"<ref>[http://www.themonitor.com/article_8d0fa9c4-1f2e-11e7-bbf9-c313ec45cbb7.html \"What is the Chrism Mass?\", ''The Monitor'', McAllen, Texas April 11, 2017]</ref> During the Mass, those present are called to renew their baptismal promises; priests/ministers and deacons also reaffirm their ministry by renewing the promises made at their ordination.<ref name=\"ELCA2013\"/><ref name=Jalbert/><ref>[https://dol-in.org/news/chrism-mass \"Chrism Mass\", Cathedral of St. Mary's, Diocese of Lafayette-in-Indiana, April 4, 2017] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413153251/https://dol-in.org/news/chrism-mass |date=13 April 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe Mass takes its name from the blessing of the [[Chrism|holy oils]] used in the sacraments throughout the year, which are then given to priests/ministers to take back to their parishes.<ref>[http://www.nola.com/religion/index.ssf/2017/04/chrism_mass_to_be_celebrated_a.html Chatelain, Kim. \"Chrism Mass to be celebrated at 10 a.m. at St. Louis Cathedral\", ''Times-Picayune'', April 11, 2017]</ref> The Rite of Reception of the Oils by representatives of the diocesan parishes is a sign of each parish's unity with the Bishop and the diocesan Church.<ref>[http://www.usccb.org/prayer-and-worship/liturgical-year/triduum/reception-of-holy-oils.cfm \"Reception of the Holy Oils\", USCCB]</ref> Whenever the holy oils are used, the ministry of the bishop who consecrated them is symbolically present.<ref>[http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/valley/article_39b6f2f2-1f22-11e7-8fa2-133fec2d4fff.html \"Chrism Mass celebrates priesthood, allows for blessing of oils\", ''the Brownsville Herald'', April 12, 2017]</ref> The oils distributed are meant to last all year, although extra oil is also blessed during the Mass and is kept at the cathedral as a reserve if a parish runs out.<ref>[http://www.thebostonpilot.com/article.asp?ID=179001 Labbe, Mark. \"Sacred Oils Prepared for chrism Mass\", ''The Boston Pilot'', April 7, 2017]</ref>\n\nThe service is a 1967 restoration of the rite recorded in the early 200s by the historian [[Hippolytus of Rome|Hippolytus]] who writes of a ceremony taking place during the [[Easter Vigil]] at which two holy oils were blessed and one was consecrated. In the fifth century, the ceremony of the oils was transferred from the Easter Vigil to Holy Thursday during a special Mass for that purpose, distinct from the Mass of the Lord's Supper. The change took place, partly, because of the large crowds that assembled for the Easter Vigil, but also to emphasize Christ's institution of this ordained priesthood at Holy Thursday's Last Supper.<ref name=Baltimore>[https://www.archbalt.org/about-us/our-bishops/cardinal-obrien/articles/chism-mass.cfm \"Chrism Mass\", ''Catholic Review'', Archdiocese of Baltimore, March 27, 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413153522/https://www.archbalt.org/about-us/our-bishops/cardinal-obrien/articles/chism-mass.cfm |date=13 April 2017 }}</ref> In the decree renewing this rite [[Pope Paul VI]] said:\u201cThe Chrism Mass is one of the principal expressions of the fullness of the bishop\u2019s priesthood and signifies the closeness of the priests with him.\u201d<ref name=Baltimore/>\n\nThe Holy Oils are:\n* [[Chrism]] \u2013 used in the sacraments of [[Baptism]], [[Confirmation in the Catholic Church|Confirmation]] and [[Holy orders in the Catholic Church|Holy Orders]], as well as for the consecration of altars and the dedication of churches.<ref>[http://www.stjames-cathedral.org/Events/2017/album-chrismmass.aspx \"Chrism Mass 2017\", St. James Cathedral, Seattle, April 6, 2017]</ref>\n* the [[oil of catechumens]] \u2013 also used in the sacrament of Baptism, and\n* the oil of the sick \u2013 used in the rite of the [[Anointing of the Sick]]\n[[File:BlessingChrism.jpg|thumb|left|Blessing Chrism]]\nThe oil of the catechumens and chrism are used on the upcoming [[Holy Saturday]] at the [[Easter Vigil]], for the [[baptism]] and [[confirmation]] of those entering the church.\n\nWhile the Oil of the Catechumens and the Oil of the Sick, are simply \"blessed,\" the Sacred Chrism is \"consecrated,\". Holy chrism is a mixture of olive oil and balsam, an aromatic resin. Balsam is poured into the oil, which gives it a sweet smell intended to remind those who encounter it of the \"odor of sanctity\" to which those who are marked with it, are called to strive. The bishop breathes over the vessel containing the chrism, a gesture which symbolizes the Holy Spirit coming down to consecrate this oil, and recalls the actions of Jesus in John 20:22, when he breathed on the apostles and said, \"Receive the Holy Spirit...\" The priests concelebrating the Mass extend their hands toward the vessel containing the chrism and say the prayer of consecration silently as the bishop pronounces it over the chrism.<ref name=Jalbert/><ref name=Baltimore/>\n\n==Anglicanism==\n\nThe 1979 BCP (p. 307) calls for chrism to be consecrated by the bishop. This may be done when the bishop is present in the parish for Confirmation. In many dioceses, the consecration of chrism by the bishop may be done at a service of reaffirmation of ordination vows during Holy Week. Similar to the Roman Catholic ritual, during the Chrism Eucharist, the Bishop will bless the oils used throughout the next year for baptisms and healing. In addition, the Bishop and clergy in attendance will reaffirm their Ordination Vows.<ref name=Tennessee/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Liturgical year of the Catholic Church}}\n\n[[Category:Anglican liturgy]]\n[[Category:Holy Week]]\n[[Category:Lutheran liturgy and worship]]\n[[Category:Mass in the Catholic Church]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:P Villanueva Messe im Lateran.jpg|thumb|Chrism Mass in the [[Lateran Basilica]]]]\nThe '''Chrism Mass''' is a religious service held in Roman Catholicism, Lutheranism, and Anglicanism.<ref name=\"ELCA2013\">{{cite book|title=How is oil used in worship?|year=2013|publisher=[[Evangelical Lutheran Church in America]]|language=English|page=2|quote=This service, also called a Chrism Mass, is held during Holy Week and presided over by a synodical bishop. At this unique liturgy, the blessing of oil is coupled with a renewal of vows for rostered leaders. The traditional day for this service is Maundy Thursday (when some traditions believe the first ordinations took place).}}</ref><ref name=Tennessee>[http://edtn.org/chrism-mass-2017/ \"Chrism Mass 2017\", The Episcopal Diocese of Tennessee]</ref>\n\n[[Maundy Thursday]] is notable for being the day on which the Chrism Mass is celebrated in each [[diocese]]. The Chrism Mass is one of the most solemn and important liturgies of the liturgical year. Usually held in the diocesean [[cathedral]], it is generally held on the morning of Maundy Thursday, but may in some dioceses take place on another day during Holy Week.<ref>[http://catholicexchange.com/what-is-the-chrism-mass Saunders, William. \"What is the Chrism Mass?\", ''Arlington Catholic Herald'', March 23, 2017]</ref> It is often the largest annual gathering of clergy and faithful held in most dioceses.<ref name=Jalbert>[https://www.catholicnh.org/worship-and-sacraments/faith/worship/chrism/ Jalbert, Jason. \"Chrism Mass\", Diocese of Manchester (New Hampshire)]</ref> In some dioceses, attendance is sufficiently significant that, due to limited seating, tickets are distributed to parishes.<ref>[http://www.thebostonpilot.com/article.asp?ID=179001 \"Chrism Mass 2017\", Diocese of Green Bay]</ref> The Mass is a celebration of the institution of the priesthood with Jesus' words at the Last Supper, \"Do this in memory of me.\"<ref>[http://www.themonitor.com/article_8d0fa9c4-1f2e-11e7-bbf9-c313ec45cbb7.html \"What is the Chrism Mass?\", ''The Monitor'', McAllen, Texas April 11, 2017]</ref> During the Mass, those present are called to renew their baptismal promises; priests/ministers and deacons also reaffirm their ministry by renewing the promises made at their ordination.<ref name=\"ELCA2013\"/><ref name=Jalbert/><ref>[https://dol-in.org/news/chrism-mass \"Chrism Mass\", Cathedral of St. Mary's, Diocese of Lafayette-in-Indiana, April 4, 2017] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413153251/https://dol-in.org/news/chrism-mass |date=13 April 2017 }}</ref>\n\nThe Mass takes its name from the blessing of the [[Chrism|holy oils]] used in the sacraments throughout the year, which are then given to priests/ministers to take back to their parishes.<ref>[http://www.nola.com/religion/index.ssf/2017/04/chrism_mass_to_be_celebrated_a.html Chatelain, Kim. \"Chrism Mass to be celebrated at 10 a.m. at St. Louis Cathedral\", ''Times-Picayune'', April 11, 2017]</ref> The Rite of Reception of the Oils by representatives of the diocesan parishes is a sign of each parish's unity with the Bishop and the diocesan Church.<ref>[http://www.usccb.org/prayer-and-worship/liturgical-year/triduum/reception-of-holy-oils.cfm \"Reception of the Holy Oils\", USCCB]</ref> Whenever the holy oils are used, the ministry of the bishop who consecrated them is symbolically present.<ref>[http://www.brownsvilleherald.com/news/valley/article_39b6f2f2-1f22-11e7-8fa2-133fec2d4fff.html \"Chrism Mass celebrates priesthood, allows for blessing of oils\", ''the Brownsville Herald'', April 12, 2017]</ref> The oils distributed are meant to last all year, although extra oil is also blessed during the Mass and is kept at the cathedral as a reserve if a parish runs out.<ref>[http://www.thebostonpilot.com/article.asp?ID=179001 Labbe, Mark. \"Sacred Oils Prepared for chrism Mass\", ''The Boston Pilot'', April 7, 2017]</ref>\n\nThe service is a 1967 restoration of the rite recorded in the early 200s by the historian [[Hippolytus of Rome|Hippolytus]] who writes of a ceremony taking place during the [[Easter Vigil]] at which two holy oils were blessed and one was consecrated. In the fifth century, the ceremony of the oils was transferred from the Easter Vigil to Maundy Thursday during a special Mass for that purpose, distinct from the Mass of the Lord's Supper. The change took place, partly, because of the large crowds that assembled for the Easter Vigil, but also to emphasize Christ's institution of this ordained priesthood at Maundy Thursday's Last Supper.<ref name=Baltimore>[https://www.archbalt.org/about-us/our-bishops/cardinal-obrien/articles/chism-mass.cfm \"Chrism Mass\", ''Catholic Review'', Archdiocese of Baltimore, March 27, 2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170413153522/https://www.archbalt.org/about-us/our-bishops/cardinal-obrien/articles/chism-mass.cfm |date=13 April 2017 }}</ref> In the decree renewing this rite [[Pope Paul VI]] said:\u201cThe Chrism Mass is one of the principal expressions of the fullness of the bishop\u2019s priesthood and signifies the closeness of the priests with him.\u201d<ref name=Baltimore/>\n\nThe Holy Oils are:\n* [[Chrism]] \u2013 used in the sacraments of [[Baptism]], [[Confirmation in the Catholic Church|Confirmation]] and [[Holy orders in the Catholic Church|Holy Orders]], as well as for the consecration of altars and the dedication of churches.<ref>[http://www.stjames-cathedral.org/Events/2017/album-chrismmass.aspx \"Chrism Mass 2017\", St. James Cathedral, Seattle, April 6, 2017]</ref>\n* the [[oil of catechumens]] \u2013 also used in the sacrament of Baptism, and\n* the oil of the sick \u2013 used in the rite of the [[Anointing of the Sick]]\n[[File:BlessingChrism.jpg|thumb|left|Blessing Chrism]]\nThe oil of the catechumens and chrism are used on the upcoming [[Holy Saturday]] at the [[Easter Vigil]], for the [[baptism]] and [[confirmation]] of those entering the church.\n\nWhile the Oil of the Catechumens and the Oil of the Sick, are simply \"blessed,\" the Sacred Chrism is \"consecrated,\". Holy chrism is a mixture of olive oil and balsam, an aromatic resin. Balsam is poured into the oil, which gives it a sweet smell intended to remind those who encounter it of the \"odor of sanctity\" to which those who are marked with it, are called to strive. The bishop breathes over the vessel containing the chrism, a gesture which symbolizes the Holy Spirit coming down to consecrate this oil, and recalls the actions of Jesus in John 20:22, when he breathed on the apostles and said, \"Receive the Holy Spirit...\" The priests concelebrating the Mass extend their hands toward the vessel containing the chrism and say the prayer of consecration silently as the bishop pronounces it over the chrism.<ref name=Jalbert/><ref name=Baltimore/>\n\n==Anglicanism==\n\nThe 1979 BCP (p. 307) calls for chrism to be consecrated by the bishop. This may be done when the bishop is present in the parish for Confirmation. In many dioceses, the consecration of chrism by the bishop may be done at a service of reaffirmation of ordination vows during Holy Week. Similar to the Roman Catholic ritual, during the Chrism Eucharist, the Bishop will bless the oils used throughout the next year for baptisms and healing. In addition, the Bishop and clergy in attendance will reaffirm their Ordination Vows.<ref name=Tennessee/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Liturgical year of the Catholic Church}}\n\n[[Category:Anglican liturgy]]\n[[Category:Holy Week]]\n[[Category:Lutheran liturgy and worship]]\n[[Category:Mass in the Catholic Church]]\n", "name_user": "1995hoo", "label": "safe", "comment": "The text of this article is more focused on Catholicism than Protestantism, so the article should use the Catholic name, Holy Thursday, not the Protestant name.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chrism_Mass"}
{"title_page": "Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)", "text_new": "{{short description|English singer-songwriter and multi-instrumentalist}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Roger Taylor\n| image            = Queen And Adam Lambert - The O2 - Tuesday 12th December 2017 QueenO2121217-47 (39066610085) Cropped.jpg\n| caption          = Taylor performing with [[Queen + Adam Lambert]] in December 2017\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Roger Meddows Taylor\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1949|7|26}}\n| birth_place      = [[King's Lynn]], [[Norfolk]], England\n| genre            = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Drums}}{{hlist|Guitar}}{{hlist|Bass}}{{hlist|Keyboard}}{{hlist|Vocals}}<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| occupation       = {{flat list|\n* Musician\n* singer-songwriter\n* record producer\n}}\n| years_active     = 1968\u2013present\n| label            = {{flat list|\n* [[EMI Records|EMI]]\n* [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n* [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n* [[Parlophone]]\n* [[Hollywood Records|Hollywood]]\n* [[Virgin EMI Records|Virgin EMI]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flat list|\n* [[Queen (band)|Queen]]\n* [[Queen + Paul Rodgers]]\n* [[Queen + Adam Lambert]]\n* [[The Cross (band)|The Cross]]\n* [[Smile (band)|Smile]]\n* Felix & Arty\n* [[Yoshiki (musician)|Yoshiki]]\n* [[Lydia Canaan]]\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|rogertaylorofficial.com}}\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100|OBE}}\n}}\n\n'''Roger Meddows Taylor''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}} (born 26 July 1949)  is an English musician, singer, songwriter, and multi-instrumentalist, best known as the drummer for the rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]].<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite web|last1=Macnab|first1=Geoffrey|title=Roger Taylor interview: The Queen drummer has written the soundtrack for British film Solitary|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/roger-taylor-interview-the-queen-drummer-has-written-the-soundtrack-for-british-film-solitary-10179509.html|website=Independent|accessdate=6 October 2016}}</ref> As a drummer, Taylor was recognised early in his career for his unique sound.<ref name=\"rs-149\">''[[Rolling Stone]]'' \u2013 Issue 149 \u2013 12 June 1973</ref>  He was voted by radio listeners as the eighth-greatest drummer in classic rock music history in a poll conducted by [[Planet Rock (radio station)|Planet Rock]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/4669597.stm |accessdate=28 January 2008 |work=  BBC News| date=10 July 2005 | title=Zeppelin voted 'ideal supergroup'}}</ref>\n\nAs a songwriter, Taylor contributed songs to Queen's albums from the beginning, composing at least one track on every album, and often singing lead vocals on his own compositions. He wrote or co-wrote three UK number 1s (\"[[These Are the Days of Our Lives]]\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sebastian.queenconcerts.com/s-tatdool.htm |title=These Are the Days of Our Lives |accessdate=28 January 2008 |work=Bechstein Debauchery |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071217074920/http://sebastian.queenconcerts.com/s-tatdool.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 17 December 2007}}</ref> \"[[Innuendo (song)|Innuendo]]\" and \"[[Under Pressure]]\") and contributed a further five major hits (\"[[Radio Ga Ga]]\", \"[[A Kind of Magic (song)|A Kind of Magic]]\", \"[[Heaven for Everyone]]\", \"[[Breakthru (song)|Breakthru]]\", and \"[[The Invisible Man (Queen song)|The Invisible Man]]\").<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sebastian.queenconcerts.com/s-im.htm |title=The Invisible Man |accessdate=28 January 2008 |work=Bechstein Debauchery |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071217144950/http://sebastian.queenconcerts.com/s-im.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 17 December 2007}}</ref> He is also the main writer on the international top-ten hit \"[[One Vision]]\", although the track is credited to the whole band. He has collaborated with such artists as [[Eric Clapton]], [[Roger Waters]], [[Roger Daltrey]], [[Robert Plant]], [[Phil Collins]], [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]], [[Jimmy Nail]], [[Kansas (band) |Kansas]], [[Elton John]], [[Gary Numan]], [[Shakin' Stevens]], [[Foo Fighters]], [[Al Stewart]], [[Steve Vai]], [[Yoshiki (musician)|Yoshiki]], [[Cyndi Almouzni]], and [[Bon Jovi]]. As a producer, he has produced albums by [[Virginia Wolf]], [[Jimmy Nail]], and [[Magnum (band)|Magnum]].\n\nIn addition to his drum work, Taylor is well known for his [[falsetto]] vocal range. He sometimes played keyboards, guitars and bass on his own songs. During the 1980s, in addition to his work with Queen, he formed a parallel band known as [[The Cross (band)|the Cross]], in which he was the lead singer and rhythm guitarist. During the early 1980s, Taylor was also a panellist on the popular UK quiz show ''[[Pop Quiz]]'', hosted by [[Mike Read]]. In 2014, he appeared in ''[[The Life of Rock with Brian Pern]]'' as himself.\n\n== Early life ==\nRoger Taylor was born on 26 July 1949 at West Norfolk & Lynn Hospital in [[King's Lynn]], [[Norfolk]]. The new maternity ward was opened by Princess Elizabeth (the future queen, [[Elizabeth II]]), where she was introduced to 16 new mothers including Winifred Taylor, his mother. Taylor first lived at 87 High Street in King's Lynn, and later moved to Beulah Street in the town. Taylor's first school was Rosebury Avenue school.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Trevor|first1=Heaton|title=Rock Star's Norfolk Childhood|url=http://www.queenarchives.com/index.php?title=Roger_Taylor_-_03-20-1999_-_Eastern_Daily_Press_-_Rock_Star%27s_Norfolk_Childhood|website=Queen Archives|publisher=Eastern Daily Press}}</ref> Taylor moved to [[Truro]], [[Cornwall]], south west England, with his mother Winifred, father Michael and younger sister Clare. When he was seven years old, he and some friends formed his first band, the Bubblingover Boys, in which he played the [[ukulele]]. He briefly attended [[Truro Cathedral School]]; at the age of 13, he joined [[Truro School]] as a day boy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://themarchoftheblackqueen.piczo.com/?g=57322673&cr=6|title=Roger|publisher=themarchoftheblackqueen.piczo.com|accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> At the age of 15, Taylor became a member of the Reaction, a semi-professional rock band formed mainly of boys from Truro School. Taylor had originally learned guitar, but became a drummer when he realised he had a more natural aptitude for it. Taylor taught himself to tune his drums, inspired by [[Keith Moon]] of [[the Who]] because of the \"great drums sounds\" on the early Who records.<ref name=\"Roger Taylor Interview\">{{cite web | url= http://www.queenzone.com/articles/roger-taylor-interview.aspx | title= Roger Taylor Interview | publisher= Queen Zone | accessdate= 10 August 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150715215326/http://www.queenzone.com/articles/roger-taylor-interview.aspx | archivedate= 15 July 2015 | df= dmy-all }}</ref> Another key influence on Taylor was drummer [[Mitch Mitchell]] of [[the Jimi Hendrix Experience]], who Taylor stated was his early role model.<ref name=\"Roger's Drum Master Class\">{{cite web | url= http://www.queenonline.com/en/the-band/interviews/roger-taylor-1/drum-master-class/ | title= Roger's Drum Master Class (Music Works - BBC World Service, November 28, 1993) | publisher=Queen Online | accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1967, Taylor went to London to study dentistry at the [[Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry|London Hospital Medical College]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/en/the-band/members/roger-taylor/|title=Roger Taylor |website=Queen official website|access-date=15 January 2017}}</ref> but he became bored with dentistry. He changed to biology and obtained a BSc at [[University of East London|East London Polytechnic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.queenarchives.com/index.php?title=Roger_Taylor_-_09-XX-1975_-_Circus|title=Heavy Meddows Kid|last=Rose|first=Frank|date=|website=Queen Archives|publisher=Eastern Daily Press|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== 1968\u20131970: Smile ===\n{{Main|Smile (band)}}\n\nTaylor met [[Brian May]] and [[Tim Staffell]] in 1968 after a friend saw an advert on a noticeboard at [[Imperial College London|Imperial College]] for a drummer. Smile included May on lead guitar, Staffell on lead vocals and bass, and later Taylor on drums. The band lasted for two years before Staffell departed to join [[Humpy Bong]], leaving the band with a catalogue of nine songs.\n\nSmile reunited for several songs on 22 December 1992. Taylor's band [[The Cross (band)|the Cross]] were headliners and he brought May and Staffell on to play \"Earth\" and \"If I Were a Carpenter\".<ref>[http://www.queenzone.com/queenzone/article_show.aspx?Q=11]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208151834/http://www.queenzone.com/queenzone/article_show.aspx?Q=11 |date=8 February 2007 }}</ref>\n\n=== 1970s\u2013present: Queen ===\n{{Main|Queen (band)}}\n[[Image:Hannover7907.jpg|thumb|right|Taylor performing with [[Queen (band)|Queen]] in 1979.]]\n\nIn 1969, Taylor was working with [[Freddie Mercury]] at the Kensington Market (they were sharing a flat at around the same time). Mercury, then known as Freddie Bulsara, was an avid fan of Smile. The band split up in 1970. In the same year, Taylor turned down the chance to become drummer for [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]], which led to [[Phil Collins]] joining instead.<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/8784298/Queen-40th-anniversary-10-things-you-never-knew.html | title= Queen 40th anniversary: 10 things you never knew | work=The Daily Telegraph | date=24 September 2011 | accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref> Bulsara convinced the remaining two members of Smile to continue and he eventually joined the band, which he renamed Queen. In 1971, they recruited bass guitarist [[John Deacon]], before going on to release their [[Queen (Queen album)|self-titled debut album]] in 1973. Taylor is the third most credited songwriter for the band, usually contributing one or two tracks per album.\n\n===1977\u2013present: Solo career===\nTaylor has had a productive solo career, releasing five albums. His first single was his 1977 \"I Wanna Testify\". He recorded it during Queen's sessions for the ''[[News of the World (album)|News of the World]]'' album. The A-side, although a cover of the Parliaments song of the same name, was completely different from the original. The B-side was a self-penned song \"Turn on the TV\".\n\nTaylor's first solo album, ''[[Fun in Space]]'', was released in 1981. Taylor performed all vocals and played all instruments aside of about half of the keyboards, which were done by engineer [[David Richards (record producer)|David Richards]]. With Queen still touring heavily and recording at the time of release, Taylor was unable to promote the album to its fullest extent, so he appeared on some European TV shows to promote the single, \"Future Management\", including ''[[Top of the Pops]]''. The only other single to come from the album was \"My Country\". The only US single released from the album was \"Let's Get Crazy\".\n\nTaylor's next venture, ''[[Strange Frontier]]'', came in June 1984. The three singles from the album were the title track, \"Beautiful Dreams\" (in Portugal only) and \"Man on Fire\", the latter becoming a live favourite for him in later years. No attempts to promote the singles were made since Queen toured to promote ''[[The Works (Queen album)|The Works]]'', and Taylor did not perform on any TV shows. ''Strange Frontier'' included guest appearances by bandmates Freddie Mercury, Brian May and John Deacon. Mercury sang backing vocals on \"Killing Time\", Deacon remixed the B-side \"I Cry For You\" and [[Rick Parfitt]] co-wrote and played on \"It's An Illusion\". David Richards, Queen's engineer and producer at the time, also co-wrote two of the tracks. The album includes covers of [[Bruce Springsteen]]'s \"[[Racing in the Street]]\" and [[Bob Dylan]]'s \"[[Masters of War]]\".\n\nIn 1986, Taylor co-produced ''[[Vigilante (Magnum album)|Vigilante]]'', the sixth studio album by rock band [[Magnum (band)|Magnum]].<ref>{{cite book |author1=Patrick Lemieux | author2=Adam Unger |title=The Queen Chronology: The Recording & Release History of the Band|year=2013|page=54|publisher=Across the Board Books|isbn=978-0991984046}}</ref>\n\nAfter Queen finished their 1986 [[A Kind of Magic|Magic Tour]], Taylor started a new band, [[The Cross (band)|the Cross]], which released three albums over their six years of existence. In 1993, the band split up, after performing one final gig at the [[Wickham Festival#History|Gosport Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/people/roger-taylor-21213223|title=Roger Taylor|website=Biography|language=en-us|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Taylor worked with [[Yoshiki (musician)|Yoshiki]], drummer and pianist of [[X Japan]] and released the song \"Foreign Sand\" and a reworking of the Cross's \"Final Destination\". The album ''Happiness?'' was \"Dedicated to the tasmanian tiger \u2013 thylacinus cynocephalus, but most especially... for Freddie\". \"Nazis 1994\" from this album became Taylor's first hit single in England and was followed by two other top 40 UK hits, \"Happiness\" and \"Foreign Sand\".\n\nIn 1998, Taylor released his fourth solo album ''[[Electric Fire]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gZIjT8PgJMEC&pg=PA499&lpg=PA499&dq=In+1998,+Taylor+released+his+fourth+solo+album+Electric+Fire.&source=bl&ots=XBU0kDQe4_&sig=BBO6TCasZB87g_GSrP6vLq5xblE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinuvqOrMvZAhVBmBQKHZAEB34Q6AEIajAI#v=onepage&q=In%201998,%20Taylor%20released%20his%20fourth%20solo%20album%20Electric%20Fire.&f=false|title=The International Who's Who in Popular Music 2002|last=Gregory|first=Andy|date=2002|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=9781857431612|language=en}}</ref> He supported it with a small tour in the spring of 1999, on which Brian May joined him at the gig in Wolverhampton. Taylor also performed one of the first Internet-gigs \u2013 for which he got a mention in the [[Guinness Book of World Records]].<ref>[http://www.queencollector.com/Articles/Solo10/roger.html]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930042840/http://www.queencollector.com/Articles/Solo10/roger.html |date=30 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, after nearly twelve years between solo albums, Taylor planned to release a new studio album titled ''[[The Unblinking Eye (Everything Is Broken)|The Unblinking Eye]]''. The first single, of the same name, was released on 23 November 2009 as a digital download, but due to popular demand it was released as a limited edition single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/news/1517/|title=QueenOnline \u2013 News |date=17 November 2009 |accessdate=1 December 2009}}</ref> Originally leaked to the official Queen fan club's website for members only, it still managed to be on YouTube within hours of the early bird release. It was announced in late 2012 that fans would be able to vote on which songs appeared on the new album, with the album itself slated for release that year.\n\nThe album is called ''[[Fun on Earth]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planetrock.com/news/rock-news/roger-taylor-to-release-solo-album/ |title=Roger Taylor To Release Solo Album &#124; Rock News &#124; News |publisher=Planet Rock |date=22 November 2012 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> and was released on 11 November 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6296827/queen-roger-taylor-solo-record-adam-lambert|title=Queen's Roger Taylor Talks Solo Work, Hopes Band Will Record With Adam Lambert|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref>\n\n=== The Cross ===\n{{Main|The Cross (band)}}\n\nThe Cross were a side project of Taylor's that existed from 1987 to 1993 and released three albums. While still the drummer for Queen, Taylor fronted the Cross as rhythm guitarist and lead vocalist. On its debut release, ''The Cross'' incorporated dance influences which they dropped on their remaining two albums. The band never enjoyed much commercial success, except in Germany.\n\n=== ''Shove It'' ===\n[[Image:The Cross 1990 Neu Isenburg 1.jpg|thumb|Taylor performing with [[The Cross (band)|the Cross]] in 1990]]\n\nAfter Queen's 1986 Magic Tour, the band members went their separate ways to do various solo work. Taylor decided to form a new band with whom he could tour. He had already written and recorded the album himself before finding a band to play the songs with. He eventually placed an ad for band members in a national newspaper, hinting he was a famous rock musician. The position of keyboard player was duly offered to [[Spike Edney]] after two successful Queen tours in which Edney had played. When the auditions were over, the line-up was completed by Peter Noone on bass, Clayton Moss on guitar and [[Josh Macrae]] on drums. Taylor himself would take the responsibility on lead vocals and rhythm guitar.\n\nThe first album, ''Shove It'', was released in 1988.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Cross-Shove-It/release/6351445|title=The Cross (3) - Shove It|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/shove-it-mw0000651910|title=Shove It - Cross {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits {{!}} AllMusic|website=AllMusic|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref> In Europe, '[[Heaven for Everyone]]\" (later a Queen song) contained Freddie Mercury on lead vocals and Taylor on backing vocals. However, on the single version and American album version the roles were switched. The European CD contained an extra track (compared to cassette and LP) in the 2nd Shelf Mix, the US version having \"Feel the Force\" as its extra track. The band promoted hard (especially in Germany), with many TV performances of singles including an appearance at the Montreux Golden Rose festival in 1988. The tour took in dates in the UK and Germany. Three singles were released from the album: \"Cowboys and Indians\", \"Heaven for Everyone\" and \"Shove It\". Another single, \"Manipulator\", was released in 1988, but it was not included on any album. It was also the only song from the time that had joint writing credits, Taylor sharing them with Edney and Steve Strange.\n\n=== ''Mad, Bad and Dangerous to Know'' ===\n[[Image:The Cross 1990 Neu Isenburg 2.jpg|thumb|Taylor performing with the Cross in 1990.]]\n\nAfter finishing Queen's 1989 album ''[[The Miracle (album)|The Miracle]]'', Taylor went into the studio with the rest of the Cross for the first time to record ''[[Mad, Bad and Dangerous to Know (The Cross album)|Mad, Bad and Dangerous to Know]]''. The band composed the opening track \"On Top of the World Ma\" with a riff bearing a resemblance to the [[Led Zeppelin]] track \"[[Whole Lotta Love]]\". The rest of the album consisted mainly of individually written songs, except for \"Power To Love\" which was the result of the combined effort of Macrae, Noone and Moss. Clayton Moss sang lead vocals on his own track \"Better Things\", and Spike Edney played [[mandolin]] on \"Final Destination\", which was written by Taylor. \"Final Destination\" was released as a single, as were \"Liar\" and \"Power To Love\", the latter being the last single to be released in the UK by the band. \"Final Destination\" came with a live rendition of Taylor's song \"Man on Fire\" as a B-side, and \"Liar\" (Noone) had a brand new track, \"In Charge of My Heart\", which was also penned by Taylor. The 12\" single and CD of \"Liar\" also included extended remixes of both \"Liar\" and \"In Charge of My Heart\". The instrumental section at the beginning of \"In Charge of My Heart\" was used as the opening to concerts on the accompanying tour. \"Closer To You\" (Edney) had been planned to be released in America, but never was. The group having seemingly given up on the UK market, the accompanying tour only included dates in Germany, Austria, Switzerland and Ibiza. Unusual for such tours, every song from the new album was played live.\n\n=== ''Blue Rock'' ===\nMade at a time when Taylor's efforts were concentrated on Queen and Mercury himself, ''[[Blue Rock (album)|Blue Rock]]'' gave the other members of the band a chance to take control of the upcoming album. It was in fact mostly written by Edney, who contributed three of his own tracks and contributed to four more. Once again the opening track was penned by the entire band, \"Bad Attitude\" was written (although not complete) by the Christmas fan club party of 1990. The album itself contained a lot of vocals not from Taylor, but mainly of Edney and Noone. Examples of this can be heard in \"Put It All Down To Love\" (Edney), \"Life Changes\" (Moss, Noone, Edney and Macrae) and \"Heartland\" (The B-side to Life Changes, penned by Noone). Blue Rock itself was only released in Germany (although promo copies were released in Italy and Japan), so copies are somewhat rare. \"New Dark Ages\" (Taylor) was released in Germany with another live version of \"Man on Fire\", whilst \"Life Changes\" was released with the B-side \"Heartland\". It was however immediately withdrawn due to Mercury's death. The tour was in support of [[Magnum (band)|Magnum]], so the concert lengths were short (45 mins.) and very few bootlegs have survived. The tour pace was rapid, covering 20 dates in one month.\n\n=== Break-up of the Cross ===\nThe band broke up in 1993 after performing a final show. Taylor continued working with Queen and produced solo albums. Drummer Macrae accompanied Taylor on his solo tours and also played percussion at the Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert. Both Taylor and keyboardist Edney participated in the [[Queen + Paul Rodgers]] tours, while Macrae worked behind the scenes as co-producer, sound engineer and Pro Tools engineer for them. In the late 1990s, Edney formed the SAS Band (\"Spike's All Stars\"), a group with an ever-changing line-up of popular '80s musicians.\n\n=== 21st century ===\nTaylor has appeared along with May for various other events and promotions, including Queen's induction into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] in 2001<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockhall.com/inductees/queen |title=Queen: inducted in 2001 &#124; The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum |publisher=Rockhall.com |date=15 April 2013 |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref> and the \"[[Party at the Palace]]\" in 2002, celebrating the golden jubilee of [[Queen Elizabeth II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.queenvault.com/patp.html |title=Party at the Palace |publisher=QueenVault.com |date=3 June 2002 |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref> In 2004, Taylor, May, and Mike Dixon received the [[Helpmann Award]] for Best Music Direction for the musical [[We Will Rock You (musical)|''We Will Rock You'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.helpmannawards.com.au/2004/past-nominees-and-winners/industry-awards|title=Past nominees and winners Helpmann Awards|accessdate=16 December 2016}}</ref>  At [[Live Earth]] in 2007, Taylor opened the concert with [[Taylor Hawkins]] of [[Foo Fighters]] and [[Chad Smith]] of [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]].\n\nTaylor and May, performing as Queen, also appeared three times on the American singing contest television show ''[[American Idol]]''. The first appearance was on 11 April 2006, during which that week's contestants were required to sing a Queen song. Songs performed included \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\", \"[[Fat Bottomed Girls]]\", \"[[The Show Must Go On (Queen song)|The Show Must Go On]]\", \"[[Who Wants to Live Forever]]\", and \"[[Innuendo (song)|Innuendo]]\". The second time Queen appeared was on the show's [[American Idol (season 8)|season 8]] finale in May 2009, performing \"We Are the Champions\" with finalists [[Adam Lambert]] and [[Kris Allen]]. The third appearance was during the [[American Idol (season 11)|eleventh season]] on 25 and 26 April 2012, performing a Queen medley with the six finalists on the first show. The following day, they performed \"[[Somebody to Love (Queen song)|Somebody to Love]]\" with the Queen Extravaganza band.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/the-queen-extravaganza-somebody-to-love-on-american-idol-20120427 |title='Somebody to Love' on 'American Idol' \u2013 Video |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=27 April 2012 |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, Taylor appeared on the reality TV show ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]'' with May as Queen mentoring the contestants, performing \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\". Also in that month, Taylor confirmed he was planning to tour with Taylor Hawkins, which Taylor described as a \"quick tour\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/53482/Queen-And-Foo-Fighters-Drummers-To-Team-Up-For-2010-Tour |title=Queen And Foo Fighters Drummers To Team Up For 2010 Tour |publisher=Gigwise |date=17 November 2009 |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref> At the [[2011 MTV Europe Music Awards]] on 6 November, Queen received the [[MTV Europe Music Award for Global Icon|Global Icon Award]], and Taylor and May closed the awards ceremony, with [[Adam Lambert]] on vocals, performing \"The Show Must Go On\", \"We Will Rock You\", and \"We Are the Champions\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Penny Newton |url=http://www.mtv.com.au/news/61c139e8-katy-perry-adam-lambert-honour-queen/ |title=Katy And Adam Honour Queen! &#124; Queen &#124; News &#124; MTV Australia |publisher=Mtv.com.au |date=6 November 2011 |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref> In 2011, Taylor, along with [[Steven Tyler]] and [[Roger Daltrey]], joined the advisory board of Edge Music Network. Taylor performed in the [[2012 Summer Olympics closing ceremony]] in London on 12 August.\n\nIn 2013 and 2014, Taylor served as an executive producer of the film ''Solitary'', directed by Sasha Krane. In addition to those duties, he provided original music, including the song \"When We Were Young\" and three instrumental songs which serve as incidental/background music in the film and during the closing credits. Taylor also appeared as special guest for Welsh Rock artist [[Jayce Lewis]] and his project Protafield, with Taylor providing drums on the track \"Wrath\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rogertaylor.info/guestdet.html|title=Roger Taylor of Queen guest appearances discography.|publisher=Rogertaylor.info|accessdate=29 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809224804/http://www.rogertaylor.info/guestdet.html|archivedate=9 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/will-will-rock-you-jayce-7233750|title=He will, he will, rock you! Jayce Lewis is granted an audience with Queen star \u2013 Wales Online|work=walesonline|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/queen-drummer-roger-taylor-agrees-5324038|title=Queen drummer Roger Taylor agrees to play on Welsh rocker Jayce Lewis' new album|work=walesonline|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> On 15 November 2014, Taylor joined the charity group [[Band Aid 30]], playing drums alongside current British and Irish pop acts on the latest version of the track \"[[Do They Know It's Christmas?]]\" at [[Sarm West Studios]] in [[Notting Hill]], London, to raise money for the [[2014 Ebola outbreaks|2014 Ebola crisis]] in Western Africa.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Band Aid 30: One Direction among celebrity line-up|newspaper=Telegraph|date=11 November 2014 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/11220735/Band-Aid-30-line-up-revealed.html |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 and 6 September 2015, Taylor, along with [[Led Zeppelin]]'s [[John Paul Jones (musician)|John Paul Jones]], joined [[Foo Fighters]] on stage in [[Milton Keynes]] to perform a cover of the Queen and [[David Bowie]] song \"[[Under Pressure]]\".\n\nOn 1 April 2019, Taylor released a new single called \"Gangsters Are Running This World\" and on 8 April 2019 he released a more rock version of this song called \"Gangsters Are Running This World-Purple Version\". Both versions became available for streaming on 8 April 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.queenonline.com/news/gangsters-are-running-this-world-available-now-inc-new-purple-version|title=Gangsters Are Running This World Available Now - Inc. New \u2018Purple Version\u2019}}</ref> On 10 May 2019 he and Czech [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] goalkeeper [[Petr \u010cech]] released a song called \"That's Football\" which \u010cech wrote for his retiring football career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/news/out-today-thats-football-petr-cech-ft-roger-taylor|title=Out Today! 'That\u2019s Football' - Petr Cech ft. Roger Taylor|website=www.queenonline.com|access-date=2019-05-10}}</ref>\n\nTaylor was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[2020 New Year Honours]] for services to music.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62866|supp=y|page=N15|date=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Influences and favourite drummers==\nTaylor has stated that his early role model as a drummer was [[Mitch Mitchell]] of [[the Jimi Hendrix Experience]]. He said: \"I still think listening to Mitch Mitchell, especially the early stuff with Hendrix, is just fantastic. This fusion of jazz technique and wonderful riffs but with this rolling ferocious attack on the whole kit, it had lots of jazz influences I think. In fact for me he played the kit like a song, it was just wonderful. Total integration into the song. Not just marking time\".<ref name=\"Roger's Drum Master Class\"/>\n\nTaylor has also expressed great admiration for [[John Bonham]] of [[Led Zeppelin]]. Speaking of Bonham, Taylor said, \"The greatest rock and roll drummer of all time was John Bonham, who did things that nobody had ever even thought possible before with the drum kit. And also the greatest sound out of his drums \u2013 they sounded enormous, and just one bass drum. So fast on it that he did more with one bass drum than most people could do with three, if they could manage them. And he had technique to burn and fantastic power and tremendous feel for rock and roll\".<ref name=\"Roger's Drum Master Class\"/> However, for just sheer technique, Taylor described the jazz and [[big band]] drummer [[Buddy Rich]] as \"the best I've ever seen\".<ref name=\"Roger's Drum Master Class\"/>\n\nSpeaking to ''[[Modern Drummer]]'' in 1984, Taylor also described [[Keith Moon]], the drummer of [[the Who]], as \"absolutely brilliant...he had a total unique style; he didn't owe anyone anything.\"<ref name=\"Roger Taylor Interview\"/>\n\n== Tributes ==\nIn 2013, a newly-discovered species of the genus ''[[Heteragrion]]'' (Odonata : Zygoptera) from Brazil was named ''Heteragrion rogertaylori'' after Taylor, in honour of his \"powerful sound, wonderful lyrics and raspy voice \"{{spaced ndash}}one of four ''Heteragrion'' flatwing [[Damselfly|damselflies]] named after the bandmates, paying tribute to the 40th anniversary of Queen's founding.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/2013/f/z03685p080f.pdf|title = Diagnoses and discussion of the group 1 and 2 Brazilian species of Heteragrion, with descriptions of four new species (Odonata: Megapodagrionidae). Zootaxa 3685 (1): 001\u2013080.|date = 9 July 2013|accessdate = 26 September 2015|website = Zootaxa|publisher = Magnolia Press \u2013 Auckland, New Zealand|last = Lencioni|first = F.A.A.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Taylor became the second living person, other than members of the British Royal Family and Sir [[Francis Chichester]] in 1967, to appear on a [[Royal Mail]] [[postage stamp|stamp]], being seen behind Freddie Mercury as part of a \"Great Britons\" issue. This caused controversy as it was an understood rule that the only living people allowed to appear on British stamps could be members of the Royal Family.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rohrer |first=Finlo |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/7669252.stm |title=The politics of stamps |publisher=BBC News |date=14 October 2008 |accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Alex Spence |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article636773.ece |title=Royal Mail unveils Beatles album cover stamps (''Times'' Online) |work=The Times |location=UK |accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Taylor appeared on the \"Twelve Drummers Drumming\" Christmas card in the \"[[Twelve Days of Christmas]]\" set sold at [[Woolworths Group|Woolworths]] to raise money for the [[National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children]] \u2013 alongside [[Duran Duran]]'s drummer [[Roger Taylor (Duran Duran drummer)|of the same name]].<ref>[http://www.moderndrummer.com/web_exclusive?mdid=900001187 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928165839/http://www.moderndrummer.com/web_exclusive?mdid=900001187 |date=28 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Roger Taylor discography}}\n{{See also|The Cross (band)#Discography}}\n{{See also|Queen discography}}\n\n=== Solo albums ===\n* ''[[Fun in Space]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Strange Frontier]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Happiness? (Roger Taylor album)|Happiness?]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Electric Fire]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Fun on Earth]]'' (2013)\n\n== Portrayal in film ==\nHe was portrayed by [[Ben Hardy (actor)|Ben Hardy]] in the film [[Bohemian Rhapsody (film)|Bohemian Rhapsody]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=nm0003547}}\n* [http://www.queenincornwall.blogspot.com/ Queen in Cornwall] \u2013 includes an extensive description of Roger Taylor's early career\n* [http://www.rogertaylor.info/ RogerTaylor.info] \u2013 includes most detailed discography of Roger Taylor as a solo artist, member of the Cross, as well as his numerous guest appearances\n{{Roger Taylor}}\n{{Queen}}\n{{Queen + Paul Rodgers}}\n{{Queen + Adam Lambert}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taylor, Roger Meddows}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century English singers]]\n[[Category:21st-century English singers]]\n[[Category:Countertenors]]\n[[Category:English male singers]]\n[[Category:English male singer-songwriters]]\n[[Category:English multi-instrumentalists]]\n[[Category:English rock drummers]]\n[[Category:English rock singers]]\n[[Category:English tenors]]\n[[Category:English rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:Rhythm guitarists]]\n[[Category:Helpmann Award winners]]\n[[Category:Ivor Novello Award winners]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Parlophone artists]]\n[[Category:People from King's Lynn]]\n[[Category:People from Truro]]\n[[Category:People educated at Truro Cathedral School]]\n[[Category:People educated at Truro School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the London Hospital Medical College]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of East London]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Norfolk]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Cornwall]]\n[[Category:Queen (band) members]]\n[[Category:Singers with a four-octave vocal range]]\n[[Category:Timpanists]]\n[[Category:Gong players]]\n[[Category:Triangle players]]\n[[Category:Tambourine players]]\n[[Category:Tubular bells players]]\n[[Category:Maracas players]]\n[[Category:Timbaleros]]\n[[Category:Castanets players]]\n[[Category:Conga players]]\n[[Category:Marimbists]]\n[[Category:Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)| ]]\n[[Category:Queen + Paul Rodgers members]]\n[[Category:Queen + Adam Lambert members]]\n[[Category:The Cross (band) members]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of the British Empire]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English singer-songwriter and multi-instrumentalist}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Roger Taylor\n| image            = Queen And Adam Lambert - The O2 - Tuesday 12th December 2017 QueenO2121217-47 (39066610085) Cropped.jpg\n| caption          = Taylor performing with [[Queen + Adam Lambert]] in December 2017\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Roger Meddows Taylor\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1949|7|26}}\n| birth_place      = [[King's Lynn]], [[Norfolk]], England\n| genre            = [[Rock music|Rock]]\n| instrument       = {{hlist|Drums}}<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| occupation       = {{flat list|\n* Musician\n* singer-songwriter\n* record producer\n}}\n| years_active     = 1968\u2013present\n| label            = {{flat list|\n* [[EMI Records|EMI]]\n* [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n* [[Capitol Records|Capitol]]\n* [[Parlophone]]\n* [[Hollywood Records|Hollywood]]\n* [[Virgin EMI Records|Virgin EMI]]\n}}\n| associated_acts  = {{flat list|\n* [[Queen (band)|Queen]]\n* [[Queen + Paul Rodgers]]\n* [[Queen + Adam Lambert]]\n* [[The Cross (band)|The Cross]]\n* [[Smile (band)|Smile]]\n* Felix & Arty\n* [[Yoshiki (musician)|Yoshiki]]\n* [[Lydia Canaan]]\n}}\n| website          = {{URL|rogertaylorofficial.com}}\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100|OBE}}\n}}\n\n'''Roger Meddows Taylor''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|OBE}} (born 26 July 1949)  is an English musician, singer, songwriter, and multi-instrumentalist, best known as the drummer for the rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]].<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite web|last1=Macnab|first1=Geoffrey|title=Roger Taylor interview: The Queen drummer has written the soundtrack for British film Solitary|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/features/roger-taylor-interview-the-queen-drummer-has-written-the-soundtrack-for-british-film-solitary-10179509.html|website=Independent|accessdate=6 October 2016}}</ref> As a drummer, Taylor was recognised early in his career for his unique sound.<ref name=\"rs-149\">''[[Rolling Stone]]'' \u2013 Issue 149 \u2013 12 June 1973</ref>  He was voted by radio listeners as the eighth-greatest drummer in classic rock music history in a poll conducted by [[Planet Rock (radio station)|Planet Rock]] in 2005.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/music/4669597.stm |accessdate=28 January 2008 |work=  BBC News| date=10 July 2005 | title=Zeppelin voted 'ideal supergroup'}}</ref>\n\nAs a songwriter, Taylor contributed songs to Queen's albums from the beginning, composing at least one track on every album, and often singing lead vocals on his own compositions. He wrote or co-wrote three UK number 1s (\"[[These Are the Days of Our Lives]]\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sebastian.queenconcerts.com/s-tatdool.htm |title=These Are the Days of Our Lives |accessdate=28 January 2008 |work=Bechstein Debauchery |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071217074920/http://sebastian.queenconcerts.com/s-tatdool.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 17 December 2007}}</ref> \"[[Innuendo (song)|Innuendo]]\" and \"[[Under Pressure]]\") and contributed a further five major hits (\"[[Radio Ga Ga]]\", \"[[A Kind of Magic (song)|A Kind of Magic]]\", \"[[Heaven for Everyone]]\", \"[[Breakthru (song)|Breakthru]]\", and \"[[The Invisible Man (Queen song)|The Invisible Man]]\").<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sebastian.queenconcerts.com/s-im.htm |title=The Invisible Man |accessdate=28 January 2008 |work=Bechstein Debauchery |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20071217144950/http://sebastian.queenconcerts.com/s-im.htm <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 17 December 2007}}</ref> He is also the main writer on the international top-ten hit \"[[One Vision]]\", although the track is credited to the whole band. He has collaborated with such artists as [[Eric Clapton]], [[Roger Waters]], [[Roger Daltrey]], [[Robert Plant]], [[Phil Collins]], [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]], [[Jimmy Nail]], [[Kansas (band) |Kansas]], [[Elton John]], [[Gary Numan]], [[Shakin' Stevens]], [[Foo Fighters]], [[Al Stewart]], [[Steve Vai]], [[Yoshiki (musician)|Yoshiki]], [[Cyndi Almouzni]], and [[Bon Jovi]]. As a producer, he has produced albums by [[Virginia Wolf]], [[Jimmy Nail]], and [[Magnum (band)|Magnum]].\n\nIn addition to his drum work, Taylor is well known for his [[falsetto]] vocal range. He sometimes played keyboards, guitars and bass on his own songs. During the 1980s, in addition to his work with Queen, he formed a parallel band known as [[The Cross (band)|the Cross]], in which he was the lead singer and rhythm guitarist. During the early 1980s, Taylor was also a panellist on the popular UK quiz show ''[[Pop Quiz]]'', hosted by [[Mike Read]]. In 2014, he appeared in ''[[The Life of Rock with Brian Pern]]'' as himself.\n\n== Early life ==\nRoger Taylor was born on 26 July 1949 at West Norfolk & Lynn Hospital in [[King's Lynn]], [[Norfolk]]. The new maternity ward was opened by Princess Elizabeth (the future queen, [[Elizabeth II]]), where she was introduced to 16 new mothers including Winifred Taylor, his mother. Taylor first lived at 87 High Street in King's Lynn, and later moved to Beulah Street in the town. Taylor's first school was Rosebury Avenue school.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Trevor|first1=Heaton|title=Rock Star's Norfolk Childhood|url=http://www.queenarchives.com/index.php?title=Roger_Taylor_-_03-20-1999_-_Eastern_Daily_Press_-_Rock_Star%27s_Norfolk_Childhood|website=Queen Archives|publisher=Eastern Daily Press}}</ref> Taylor moved to [[Truro]], [[Cornwall]], south west England, with his mother Winifred, father Michael and younger sister Clare. When he was seven years old, he and some friends formed his first band, the Bubblingover Boys, in which he played the [[ukulele]]. He briefly attended [[Truro Cathedral School]]; at the age of 13, he joined [[Truro School]] as a day boy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://themarchoftheblackqueen.piczo.com/?g=57322673&cr=6|title=Roger|publisher=themarchoftheblackqueen.piczo.com|accessdate=8 April 2012}}</ref> At the age of 15, Taylor became a member of the Reaction, a semi-professional rock band formed mainly of boys from Truro School. Taylor had originally learned guitar, but became a drummer when he realised he had a more natural aptitude for it. Taylor taught himself to tune his drums, inspired by [[Keith Moon]] of [[the Who]] because of the \"great drums sounds\" on the early Who records.<ref name=\"Roger Taylor Interview\">{{cite web | url= http://www.queenzone.com/articles/roger-taylor-interview.aspx | title= Roger Taylor Interview | publisher= Queen Zone | accessdate= 10 August 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20150715215326/http://www.queenzone.com/articles/roger-taylor-interview.aspx | archivedate= 15 July 2015 | df= dmy-all }}</ref> Another key influence on Taylor was drummer [[Mitch Mitchell]] of [[the Jimi Hendrix Experience]], who Taylor stated was his early role model.<ref name=\"Roger's Drum Master Class\">{{cite web | url= http://www.queenonline.com/en/the-band/interviews/roger-taylor-1/drum-master-class/ | title= Roger's Drum Master Class (Music Works - BBC World Service, November 28, 1993) | publisher=Queen Online | accessdate=10 August 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1967, Taylor went to London to study dentistry at the [[Barts and The London School of Medicine and Dentistry|London Hospital Medical College]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/en/the-band/members/roger-taylor/|title=Roger Taylor |website=Queen official website|access-date=15 January 2017}}</ref> but he became bored with dentistry. He changed to biology and obtained a BSc at [[University of East London|East London Polytechnic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.queenarchives.com/index.php?title=Roger_Taylor_-_09-XX-1975_-_Circus|title=Heavy Meddows Kid|last=Rose|first=Frank|date=|website=Queen Archives|publisher=Eastern Daily Press|accessdate=}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n=== 1968\u20131970: Smile ===\n{{Main|Smile (band)}}\n\nTaylor met [[Brian May]] and [[Tim Staffell]] in 1968 after a friend saw an advert on a noticeboard at [[Imperial College London|Imperial College]] for a drummer. Smile included May on lead guitar, Staffell on lead vocals and bass, and later Taylor on drums. The band lasted for two years before Staffell departed to join [[Humpy Bong]], leaving the band with a catalogue of nine songs.\n\nSmile reunited for several songs on 22 December 1992. Taylor's band [[The Cross (band)|the Cross]] were headliners and he brought May and Staffell on to play \"Earth\" and \"If I Were a Carpenter\".<ref>[http://www.queenzone.com/queenzone/article_show.aspx?Q=11]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070208151834/http://www.queenzone.com/queenzone/article_show.aspx?Q=11 |date=8 February 2007 }}</ref>\n\n=== 1970s\u2013present: Queen ===\n{{Main|Queen (band)}}\n[[Image:Hannover7907.jpg|thumb|right|Taylor performing with [[Queen (band)|Queen]] in 1979.]]\n\nIn 1969, Taylor was working with [[Freddie Mercury]] at the Kensington Market (they were sharing a flat at around the same time). Mercury, then known as Freddie Bulsara, was an avid fan of Smile. The band split up in 1970. In the same year, Taylor turned down the chance to become drummer for [[Genesis (band)|Genesis]], which led to [[Phil Collins]] joining instead.<ref>{{cite news | url= https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/8784298/Queen-40th-anniversary-10-things-you-never-knew.html | title= Queen 40th anniversary: 10 things you never knew | work=The Daily Telegraph | date=24 September 2011 | accessdate=27 August 2015}}</ref> Bulsara convinced the remaining two members of Smile to continue and he eventually joined the band, which he renamed Queen. In 1971, they recruited bass guitarist [[John Deacon]], before going on to release their [[Queen (Queen album)|self-titled debut album]] in 1973. Taylor is the third most credited songwriter for the band, usually contributing one or two tracks per album.\n\n===1977\u2013present: Solo career===\nTaylor has had a productive solo career, releasing five albums. His first single was his 1977 \"I Wanna Testify\". He recorded it during Queen's sessions for the ''[[News of the World (album)|News of the World]]'' album. The A-side, although a cover of the Parliaments song of the same name, was completely different from the original. The B-side was a self-penned song \"Turn on the TV\".\n\nTaylor's first solo album, ''[[Fun in Space]]'', was released in 1981. Taylor performed all vocals and played all instruments aside of about half of the keyboards, which were done by engineer [[David Richards (record producer)|David Richards]]. With Queen still touring heavily and recording at the time of release, Taylor was unable to promote the album to its fullest extent, so he appeared on some European TV shows to promote the single, \"Future Management\", including ''[[Top of the Pops]]''. The only other single to come from the album was \"My Country\". The only US single released from the album was \"Let's Get Crazy\".\n\nTaylor's next venture, ''[[Strange Frontier]]'', came in June 1984. The three singles from the album were the title track, \"Beautiful Dreams\" (in Portugal only) and \"Man on Fire\", the latter becoming a live favourite for him in later years. No attempts to promote the singles were made since Queen toured to promote ''[[The Works (Queen album)|The Works]]'', and Taylor did not perform on any TV shows. ''Strange Frontier'' included guest appearances by bandmates Freddie Mercury, Brian May and John Deacon. Mercury sang backing vocals on \"Killing Time\", Deacon remixed the B-side \"I Cry For You\" and [[Rick Parfitt]] co-wrote and played on \"It's An Illusion\". David Richards, Queen's engineer and producer at the time, also co-wrote two of the tracks. The album includes covers of [[Bruce Springsteen]]'s \"[[Racing in the Street]]\" and [[Bob Dylan]]'s \"[[Masters of War]]\".\n\nIn 1986, Taylor co-produced ''[[Vigilante (Magnum album)|Vigilante]]'', the sixth studio album by rock band [[Magnum (band)|Magnum]].<ref>{{cite book |author1=Patrick Lemieux | author2=Adam Unger |title=The Queen Chronology: The Recording & Release History of the Band|year=2013|page=54|publisher=Across the Board Books|isbn=978-0991984046}}</ref>\n\nAfter Queen finished their 1986 [[A Kind of Magic|Magic Tour]], Taylor started a new band, [[The Cross (band)|the Cross]], which released three albums over their six years of existence. In 1993, the band split up, after performing one final gig at the [[Wickham Festival#History|Gosport Festival]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.biography.com/people/roger-taylor-21213223|title=Roger Taylor|website=Biography|language=en-us|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Taylor worked with [[Yoshiki (musician)|Yoshiki]], drummer and pianist of [[X Japan]] and released the song \"Foreign Sand\" and a reworking of the Cross's \"Final Destination\". The album ''Happiness?'' was \"Dedicated to the tasmanian tiger \u2013 thylacinus cynocephalus, but most especially... for Freddie\". \"Nazis 1994\" from this album became Taylor's first hit single in England and was followed by two other top 40 UK hits, \"Happiness\" and \"Foreign Sand\".\n\nIn 1998, Taylor released his fourth solo album ''[[Electric Fire]]''.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gZIjT8PgJMEC&pg=PA499&lpg=PA499&dq=In+1998,+Taylor+released+his+fourth+solo+album+Electric+Fire.&source=bl&ots=XBU0kDQe4_&sig=BBO6TCasZB87g_GSrP6vLq5xblE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwinuvqOrMvZAhVBmBQKHZAEB34Q6AEIajAI#v=onepage&q=In%201998,%20Taylor%20released%20his%20fourth%20solo%20album%20Electric%20Fire.&f=false|title=The International Who's Who in Popular Music 2002|last=Gregory|first=Andy|date=2002|publisher=Psychology Press|isbn=9781857431612|language=en}}</ref> He supported it with a small tour in the spring of 1999, on which Brian May joined him at the gig in Wolverhampton. Taylor also performed one of the first Internet-gigs \u2013 for which he got a mention in the [[Guinness Book of World Records]].<ref>[http://www.queencollector.com/Articles/Solo10/roger.html]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070930042840/http://www.queencollector.com/Articles/Solo10/roger.html |date=30 September 2007 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, after nearly twelve years between solo albums, Taylor planned to release a new studio album titled ''[[The Unblinking Eye (Everything Is Broken)|The Unblinking Eye]]''. The first single, of the same name, was released on 23 November 2009 as a digital download, but due to popular demand it was released as a limited edition single.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/news/1517/|title=QueenOnline \u2013 News |date=17 November 2009 |accessdate=1 December 2009}}</ref> Originally leaked to the official Queen fan club's website for members only, it still managed to be on YouTube within hours of the early bird release. It was announced in late 2012 that fans would be able to vote on which songs appeared on the new album, with the album itself slated for release that year.\n\nThe album is called ''[[Fun on Earth]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.planetrock.com/news/rock-news/roger-taylor-to-release-solo-album/ |title=Roger Taylor To Release Solo Album &#124; Rock News &#124; News |publisher=Planet Rock |date=22 November 2012 |accessdate=27 June 2013}}</ref> and was released on 11 November 2013.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/6296827/queen-roger-taylor-solo-record-adam-lambert|title=Queen's Roger Taylor Talks Solo Work, Hopes Band Will Record With Adam Lambert|work=Billboard|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref>\n\n=== The Cross ===\n{{Main|The Cross (band)}}\n\nThe Cross were a side project of Taylor's that existed from 1987 to 1993 and released three albums. While still the drummer for Queen, Taylor fronted the Cross as rhythm guitarist and lead vocalist. On its debut release, ''The Cross'' incorporated dance influences which they dropped on their remaining two albums. The band never enjoyed much commercial success, except in Germany.\n\n=== ''Shove It'' ===\n[[Image:The Cross 1990 Neu Isenburg 1.jpg|thumb|Taylor performing with [[The Cross (band)|the Cross]] in 1990]]\n\nAfter Queen's 1986 Magic Tour, the band members went their separate ways to do various solo work. Taylor decided to form a new band with whom he could tour. He had already written and recorded the album himself before finding a band to play the songs with. He eventually placed an ad for band members in a national newspaper, hinting he was a famous rock musician. The position of keyboard player was duly offered to [[Spike Edney]] after two successful Queen tours in which Edney had played. When the auditions were over, the line-up was completed by Peter Noone on bass, Clayton Moss on guitar and [[Josh Macrae]] on drums. Taylor himself would take the responsibility on lead vocals and rhythm guitar.\n\nThe first album, ''Shove It'', was released in 1988.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/Cross-Shove-It/release/6351445|title=The Cross (3) - Shove It|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/shove-it-mw0000651910|title=Shove It - Cross {{!}} Songs, Reviews, Credits {{!}} AllMusic|website=AllMusic|access-date=2018-03-01}}</ref> In Europe, '[[Heaven for Everyone]]\" (later a Queen song) contained Freddie Mercury on lead vocals and Taylor on backing vocals. However, on the single version and American album version the roles were switched. The European CD contained an extra track (compared to cassette and LP) in the 2nd Shelf Mix, the US version having \"Feel the Force\" as its extra track. The band promoted hard (especially in Germany), with many TV performances of singles including an appearance at the Montreux Golden Rose festival in 1988. The tour took in dates in the UK and Germany. Three singles were released from the album: \"Cowboys and Indians\", \"Heaven for Everyone\" and \"Shove It\". Another single, \"Manipulator\", was released in 1988, but it was not included on any album. It was also the only song from the time that had joint writing credits, Taylor sharing them with Edney and Steve Strange.\n\n=== ''Mad, Bad and Dangerous to Know'' ===\n[[Image:The Cross 1990 Neu Isenburg 2.jpg|thumb|Taylor performing with the Cross in 1990.]]\n\nAfter finishing Queen's 1989 album ''[[The Miracle (album)|The Miracle]]'', Taylor went into the studio with the rest of the Cross for the first time to record ''[[Mad, Bad and Dangerous to Know (The Cross album)|Mad, Bad and Dangerous to Know]]''. The band composed the opening track \"On Top of the World Ma\" with a riff bearing a resemblance to the [[Led Zeppelin]] track \"[[Whole Lotta Love]]\". The rest of the album consisted mainly of individually written songs, except for \"Power To Love\" which was the result of the combined effort of Macrae, Noone and Moss. Clayton Moss sang lead vocals on his own track \"Better Things\", and Spike Edney played [[mandolin]] on \"Final Destination\", which was written by Taylor. \"Final Destination\" was released as a single, as were \"Liar\" and \"Power To Love\", the latter being the last single to be released in the UK by the band. \"Final Destination\" came with a live rendition of Taylor's song \"Man on Fire\" as a B-side, and \"Liar\" (Noone) had a brand new track, \"In Charge of My Heart\", which was also penned by Taylor. The 12\" single and CD of \"Liar\" also included extended remixes of both \"Liar\" and \"In Charge of My Heart\". The instrumental section at the beginning of \"In Charge of My Heart\" was used as the opening to concerts on the accompanying tour. \"Closer To You\" (Edney) had been planned to be released in America, but never was. The group having seemingly given up on the UK market, the accompanying tour only included dates in Germany, Austria, Switzerland and Ibiza. Unusual for such tours, every song from the new album was played live.\n\n=== ''Blue Rock'' ===\nMade at a time when Taylor's efforts were concentrated on Queen and Mercury himself, ''[[Blue Rock (album)|Blue Rock]]'' gave the other members of the band a chance to take control of the upcoming album. It was in fact mostly written by Edney, who contributed three of his own tracks and contributed to four more. Once again the opening track was penned by the entire band, \"Bad Attitude\" was written (although not complete) by the Christmas fan club party of 1990. The album itself contained a lot of vocals not from Taylor, but mainly of Edney and Noone. Examples of this can be heard in \"Put It All Down To Love\" (Edney), \"Life Changes\" (Moss, Noone, Edney and Macrae) and \"Heartland\" (The B-side to Life Changes, penned by Noone). Blue Rock itself was only released in Germany (although promo copies were released in Italy and Japan), so copies are somewhat rare. \"New Dark Ages\" (Taylor) was released in Germany with another live version of \"Man on Fire\", whilst \"Life Changes\" was released with the B-side \"Heartland\". It was however immediately withdrawn due to Mercury's death. The tour was in support of [[Magnum (band)|Magnum]], so the concert lengths were short (45 mins.) and very few bootlegs have survived. The tour pace was rapid, covering 20 dates in one month.\n\n=== Break-up of the Cross ===\nThe band broke up in 1993 after performing a final show. Taylor continued working with Queen and produced solo albums. Drummer Macrae accompanied Taylor on his solo tours and also played percussion at the Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert. Both Taylor and keyboardist Edney participated in the [[Queen + Paul Rodgers]] tours, while Macrae worked behind the scenes as co-producer, sound engineer and Pro Tools engineer for them. In the late 1990s, Edney formed the SAS Band (\"Spike's All Stars\"), a group with an ever-changing line-up of popular '80s musicians.\n\n=== 21st century ===\nTaylor has appeared along with May for various other events and promotions, including Queen's induction into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] in 2001<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rockhall.com/inductees/queen |title=Queen: inducted in 2001 &#124; The Rock and Roll Hall of Fame and Museum |publisher=Rockhall.com |date=15 April 2013 |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref> and the \"[[Party at the Palace]]\" in 2002, celebrating the golden jubilee of [[Queen Elizabeth II]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.queenvault.com/patp.html |title=Party at the Palace |publisher=QueenVault.com |date=3 June 2002 |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref> In 2004, Taylor, May, and Mike Dixon received the [[Helpmann Award]] for Best Music Direction for the musical [[We Will Rock You (musical)|''We Will Rock You'']].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.helpmannawards.com.au/2004/past-nominees-and-winners/industry-awards|title=Past nominees and winners Helpmann Awards|accessdate=16 December 2016}}</ref>  At [[Live Earth]] in 2007, Taylor opened the concert with [[Taylor Hawkins]] of [[Foo Fighters]] and [[Chad Smith]] of [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]].\n\nTaylor and May, performing as Queen, also appeared three times on the American singing contest television show ''[[American Idol]]''. The first appearance was on 11 April 2006, during which that week's contestants were required to sing a Queen song. Songs performed included \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\", \"[[Fat Bottomed Girls]]\", \"[[The Show Must Go On (Queen song)|The Show Must Go On]]\", \"[[Who Wants to Live Forever]]\", and \"[[Innuendo (song)|Innuendo]]\". The second time Queen appeared was on the show's [[American Idol (season 8)|season 8]] finale in May 2009, performing \"We Are the Champions\" with finalists [[Adam Lambert]] and [[Kris Allen]]. The third appearance was during the [[American Idol (season 11)|eleventh season]] on 25 and 26 April 2012, performing a Queen medley with the six finalists on the first show. The following day, they performed \"[[Somebody to Love (Queen song)|Somebody to Love]]\" with the Queen Extravaganza band.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/videos/the-queen-extravaganza-somebody-to-love-on-american-idol-20120427 |title='Somebody to Love' on 'American Idol' \u2013 Video |publisher=Rolling Stone |date=27 April 2012 |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2009, Taylor appeared on the reality TV show ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]'' with May as Queen mentoring the contestants, performing \"[[Bohemian Rhapsody]]\". Also in that month, Taylor confirmed he was planning to tour with Taylor Hawkins, which Taylor described as a \"quick tour\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/53482/Queen-And-Foo-Fighters-Drummers-To-Team-Up-For-2010-Tour |title=Queen And Foo Fighters Drummers To Team Up For 2010 Tour |publisher=Gigwise |date=17 November 2009 |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref> At the [[2011 MTV Europe Music Awards]] on 6 November, Queen received the [[MTV Europe Music Award for Global Icon|Global Icon Award]], and Taylor and May closed the awards ceremony, with [[Adam Lambert]] on vocals, performing \"The Show Must Go On\", \"We Will Rock You\", and \"We Are the Champions\".<ref>{{cite web|author=Penny Newton |url=http://www.mtv.com.au/news/61c139e8-katy-perry-adam-lambert-honour-queen/ |title=Katy And Adam Honour Queen! &#124; Queen &#124; News &#124; MTV Australia |publisher=Mtv.com.au |date=6 November 2011 |accessdate=16 July 2014}}</ref> In 2011, Taylor, along with [[Steven Tyler]] and [[Roger Daltrey]], joined the advisory board of Edge Music Network. Taylor performed in the [[2012 Summer Olympics closing ceremony]] in London on 12 August.\n\nIn 2013 and 2014, Taylor served as an executive producer of the film ''Solitary'', directed by Sasha Krane. In addition to those duties, he provided original music, including the song \"When We Were Young\" and three instrumental songs which serve as incidental/background music in the film and during the closing credits. Taylor also appeared as special guest for Welsh Rock artist [[Jayce Lewis]] and his project Protafield, with Taylor providing drums on the track \"Wrath\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rogertaylor.info/guestdet.html|title=Roger Taylor of Queen guest appearances discography.|publisher=Rogertaylor.info|accessdate=29 September 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140809224804/http://www.rogertaylor.info/guestdet.html|archivedate=9 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/music-nightlife-news/will-will-rock-you-jayce-7233750|title=He will, he will, rock you! Jayce Lewis is granted an audience with Queen star \u2013 Wales Online|work=walesonline|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.walesonline.co.uk/whats-on/queen-drummer-roger-taylor-agrees-5324038|title=Queen drummer Roger Taylor agrees to play on Welsh rocker Jayce Lewis' new album|work=walesonline|accessdate=29 September 2014}}</ref> On 15 November 2014, Taylor joined the charity group [[Band Aid 30]], playing drums alongside current British and Irish pop acts on the latest version of the track \"[[Do They Know It's Christmas?]]\" at [[Sarm West Studios]] in [[Notting Hill]], London, to raise money for the [[2014 Ebola outbreaks|2014 Ebola crisis]] in Western Africa.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Band Aid 30: One Direction among celebrity line-up|newspaper=Telegraph|date=11 November 2014 |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/music/music-news/11220735/Band-Aid-30-line-up-revealed.html |accessdate=11 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 and 6 September 2015, Taylor, along with [[Led Zeppelin]]'s [[John Paul Jones (musician)|John Paul Jones]], joined [[Foo Fighters]] on stage in [[Milton Keynes]] to perform a cover of the Queen and [[David Bowie]] song \"[[Under Pressure]]\".\n\nOn 1 April 2019, Taylor released a new single called \"Gangsters Are Running This World\" and on 8 April 2019 he released a more rock version of this song called \"Gangsters Are Running This World-Purple Version\". Both versions became available for streaming on 8 April 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.queenonline.com/news/gangsters-are-running-this-world-available-now-inc-new-purple-version|title=Gangsters Are Running This World Available Now - Inc. New \u2018Purple Version\u2019}}</ref> On 10 May 2019 he and Czech [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] goalkeeper [[Petr \u010cech]] released a song called \"That's Football\" which \u010cech wrote for his retiring football career.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.queenonline.com/news/out-today-thats-football-petr-cech-ft-roger-taylor|title=Out Today! 'That\u2019s Football' - Petr Cech ft. Roger Taylor|website=www.queenonline.com|access-date=2019-05-10}}</ref>\n\nTaylor was appointed [[Officer of the Order of the British Empire]] (OBE) in the [[2020 New Year Honours]] for services to music.<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=62866|supp=y|page=N15|date=28 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Influences and favourite drummers==\nTaylor has stated that his early role model as a drummer was [[Mitch Mitchell]] of [[the Jimi Hendrix Experience]]. He said: \"I still think listening to Mitch Mitchell, especially the early stuff with Hendrix, is just fantastic. This fusion of jazz technique and wonderful riffs but with this rolling ferocious attack on the whole kit, it had lots of jazz influences I think. In fact for me he played the kit like a song, it was just wonderful. Total integration into the song. Not just marking time\".<ref name=\"Roger's Drum Master Class\"/>\n\nTaylor has also expressed great admiration for [[John Bonham]] of [[Led Zeppelin]]. Speaking of Bonham, Taylor said, \"The greatest rock and roll drummer of all time was John Bonham, who did things that nobody had ever even thought possible before with the drum kit. And also the greatest sound out of his drums \u2013 they sounded enormous, and just one bass drum. So fast on it that he did more with one bass drum than most people could do with three, if they could manage them. And he had technique to burn and fantastic power and tremendous feel for rock and roll\".<ref name=\"Roger's Drum Master Class\"/> However, for just sheer technique, Taylor described the jazz and [[big band]] drummer [[Buddy Rich]] as \"the best I've ever seen\".<ref name=\"Roger's Drum Master Class\"/>\n\nSpeaking to ''[[Modern Drummer]]'' in 1984, Taylor also described [[Keith Moon]], the drummer of [[the Who]], as \"absolutely brilliant...he had a total unique style; he didn't owe anyone anything.\"<ref name=\"Roger Taylor Interview\"/>\n\n== Tributes ==\nIn 2013, a newly-discovered species of the genus ''[[Heteragrion]]'' (Odonata : Zygoptera) from Brazil was named ''Heteragrion rogertaylori'' after Taylor, in honour of his \"powerful sound, wonderful lyrics and raspy voice \"{{spaced ndash}}one of four ''Heteragrion'' flatwing [[Damselfly|damselflies]] named after the bandmates, paying tribute to the 40th anniversary of Queen's founding.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.mapress.com/zootaxa/2013/f/z03685p080f.pdf|title = Diagnoses and discussion of the group 1 and 2 Brazilian species of Heteragrion, with descriptions of four new species (Odonata: Megapodagrionidae). Zootaxa 3685 (1): 001\u2013080.|date = 9 July 2013|accessdate = 26 September 2015|website = Zootaxa|publisher = Magnolia Press \u2013 Auckland, New Zealand|last = Lencioni|first = F.A.A.}}</ref>\n\nIn 1999, Taylor became the second living person, other than members of the British Royal Family and Sir [[Francis Chichester]] in 1967, to appear on a [[Royal Mail]] [[postage stamp|stamp]], being seen behind Freddie Mercury as part of a \"Great Britons\" issue. This caused controversy as it was an understood rule that the only living people allowed to appear on British stamps could be members of the Royal Family.<ref>{{cite news|last=Rohrer |first=Finlo |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/uk_news/magazine/7669252.stm |title=The politics of stamps |publisher=BBC News |date=14 October 2008 |accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Alex Spence |url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/uk/article636773.ece |title=Royal Mail unveils Beatles album cover stamps (''Times'' Online) |work=The Times |location=UK |accessdate=29 October 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Taylor appeared on the \"Twelve Drummers Drumming\" Christmas card in the \"[[Twelve Days of Christmas]]\" set sold at [[Woolworths Group|Woolworths]] to raise money for the [[National Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Children]] \u2013 alongside [[Duran Duran]]'s drummer [[Roger Taylor (Duran Duran drummer)|of the same name]].<ref>[http://www.moderndrummer.com/web_exclusive?mdid=900001187 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928165839/http://www.moderndrummer.com/web_exclusive?mdid=900001187 |date=28 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{Main|Roger Taylor discography}}\n{{See also|The Cross (band)#Discography}}\n{{See also|Queen discography}}\n\n=== Solo albums ===\n* ''[[Fun in Space]]'' (1981)\n* ''[[Strange Frontier]]'' (1984)\n* ''[[Happiness? (Roger Taylor album)|Happiness?]]'' (1994)\n* ''[[Electric Fire]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Fun on Earth]]'' (2013)\n\n== Portrayal in film ==\nHe was portrayed by [[Ben Hardy (actor)|Ben Hardy]] in the film [[Bohemian Rhapsody (film)|Bohemian Rhapsody]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=nm0003547}}\n* [http://www.queenincornwall.blogspot.com/ Queen in Cornwall] \u2013 includes an extensive description of Roger Taylor's early career\n* [http://www.rogertaylor.info/ RogerTaylor.info] \u2013 includes most detailed discography of Roger Taylor as a solo artist, member of the Cross, as well as his numerous guest appearances\n{{Roger Taylor}}\n{{Queen}}\n{{Queen + Paul Rodgers}}\n