ope=\"col\" | Awards\n! scope=\"col\" | Film\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2\n|align=left|''The Grave Bandits''\n|-\n|align=left|''In Nomine Matris''\n|}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Box Office gross==\nThe [[Metro Manila Development Authority]] was criticized for only releasing the official earnings of the Top 4 films in the days leading up to the festival's conclusion. \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text align: center\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#efefef\"\n!rowspan=2|Entry\n!colspan=6|Gross Ticket Sales\n|-\n!December 25<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.abs-cbnnews.com/entertainment/12/26/12/how-8-mmff-films-ranked-first-day| title=How the 8 MMFF films ranked on first day |author= Miguel Dumaual | publisher=[[ABS-CBN News and Current Affairs]]  | date=December 27, 2012 | accessdate=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n!December 26<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2012/12/28/890718/2012-mmff-grosses-p79.06m-2nd-day | title=2012 MMFF grosses P79.06M on 2nd day | newspaper=[[Philippine Star]]  | date=December 28, 2012 | accessdate=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n!December 27<ref>{{cite news | url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/73931/sisterakas-still-top-grosser-among-mmff-entries | title=\u2018Sisterakas\u2019 still top grosser among MMFF entries |author=Bayani San Diego | newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] | date=December 28, 2012 | accessdate=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n!December 31<ref>{{cite news |title= MMFF Continues to Rake in Ticket Sales |newspaper= [[Manila Bulletin]] |url-access=subscription  |via=[[HighBeam Research]] |access-date= August 10, 2015 |date= January 2, 2013  |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-324044788.html|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150924154245/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-324044788.html|url-status= dead|archive-date= September 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n!January 1<ref>{{cite news | url=http://entertainment.inquirer.net/74681/sisterakas-still-tops-mmff-on-2nd-week | title=\u2018Sisterakas\u2019 still tops MMFF on 2nd week |author=Bayani San Diego | newspaper=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] | date=January 2, 2013 | accessdate=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\n!January 8<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mmda.gov.ph/index.php/11-news/133-2012-metro-manila-film-festival-earns-record-breaking-p767-8-million | title=2012 Metro Manila Film Festival Earns Record-breaking P767.8 Million  | publisher=[[Metro Manila Development Authority]] | date=January 10, 2013 | accessdate=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n|-\n|''[[Sisterakas]]''\n|data-sort-value=\"1\" style=\"background:#BFFFC0;\"|\u20b1 39,194,312.65*\n|data-sort-value=\"1\" style=\"background:#BFFFC0;\"|\u20b1 71,600,000*\n|data-sort-value=\"1\" style=\"background:#BFFFC0;\"|\u20b1 101,000,000*\n|data-sort-value=\"1\" style=\"background:#BFFFC0;\"|\u20b1 200,100,000*\n|data-sort-value=\"1\" style=\"background:#BFFFC0;\"|\u20b1 231,878,445.67*\n|data-sort-value=\"1\" style=\"background:#BFFFC0;\"|\u20b1 342,000,000*\n|-\n|''[[One More Try (film)|One More Try]]''\n|data-sort-value=\"3\"|\u20b1 13,160,987.40\n|data-sort-value=\"3\"|\u20b1 24,400,000\n|data-sort-value=\"3\"|\u20b1 34,600,000\n|data-sort-value=\"3\"|\u20b1 76,600,000\n|data-sort-value=\"3\"|\u20b1 91,278,399.20\n|data-sort-value=\"2\"|\u20b1 170,500,000\n|-\n|''[[Si Agimat, si Enteng Kabisote at si Ako]]''\n|data-sort-value=\"2\"|\u20b1 29,393,219.10\n|data-sort-value=\"2\"|\u20b1 48,600,000\n|data-sort-value=\"2\"|\u20b1 61,000,000\n|data-sort-value=\"2\"|\u20b1 91,400,000\n|data-sort-value=\"2\"|\u20b1 104,458,871.19\n|data-sort-value=\"3\"|\u20b1 133,500,000\n|-\n|''[[Shake, Rattle and Roll Fourteen: The Invasion]]''\n|data-sort-value=\"4\"|\u20b1 10,579,339.60\n|data-sort-value=\"4\"|\u20b1 19,200,000\n|data-sort-value=\"4\"|\u20b1 20,700,000\n|data-sort-value=\"4\"|\u20b1 30,600,000\n|data-sort-value=\"4\"|\u20b1 34,582,606.14\n|data-sort-value=\"4\"|\u20b1 45,300,000\n|-\n|''[[The Strangers (2012 film)|The Strangers]]''\n|data-sort-value=\"5\"|\u20b1 4,902,627.00\n|data-sort-value=\"5\"|\u20b1 7,300,000\n|data-sort-value=\"5\"|{{center|\u2013}} \n|data-sort-value=\"5\"|{{center|\u2013}} \n|data-sort-value=\"5\"|{{center|\u2013}} \n|data-sort-value=\"5\"|{{center|\u2013}}\n|-\n|''[[El Presidente (film)|El Presidente]]''\n|data-sort-value=\"6\"|\u20b1 4,244,500.00\n|data-sort-value=\"6\"|\u20b1 7,100,000\n|data-sort-value=\"6\"|{{center|\u2013}} \n|data-sort-value=\"6\"|{{center|\u2013}} \n|data-sort-value=\"6\"|{{center|\u2013}} \n|data-sort-value=\"6\"|{{center|\u2013}}\n|-\n|''[[Sosy Problems]]''\n|data-sort-value=\"7\"|\u20b1 3,036,408.75\n|data-sort-value=\"7\"|\u20b1 4,700,000\n|data-sort-value=\"7\"|{{center|\u2013}} \n|data-sort-value=\"7\"|{{center|\u2013}} \n|data-sort-value=\"7\"|{{center|\u2013}} \n|data-sort-value=\"7\"|{{center|\u2013}}\n|-\n|''[[Thy Womb]]''\n|data-sort-value=\"8\"|\u20b1 908,859.00\n|data-sort-value=\"8\"|\u20b1 1,600,000\n|data-sort-value=\"8\"|{{center|\u2013}} \n|data-sort-value=\"8\"|{{center|\u2013}} \n|data-sort-value=\"8\"|{{center|\u2013}} \n|data-sort-value=\"8\"|{{center|\u2013}}\n|-\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|'''{{right|TOTAL}}'''\n|\u20b1 767,800,000\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website|http://www.mmda.gov.ph/mmff/}}<!--------\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/event/ev0000431/2012 |title=Metro Manila Film Festival: Awards for 2012 |publisher=[[Internet Movie Database]] }}---->\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box\n| before = [[2011 Metro Manila Film Festival]]\n| title  = [[Metro Manila Film Festival]]\n| years  = 2012\n| after  = [[2013 Metro Manila Film Festival]]\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{MMFF}}\n\n[[Category:Metro Manila Film Festival]]\n[[Category:2012 film awards|MMFF]]\n[[Category:2012 film festivals|MMFF]]\n[[Category:2012 festivals in Asia|MMFF]]\n[[Category:2013 in Philippine cinema]]\n\n[[nl:Metro Manila Film Festival]]\n[[tl:Paligsahan ng mga Pelikula ng Kalakhang Maynila]]\n", "name_user": "WOSlinker", "label": "safe", "comment": "fix bold", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012_Metro_Manila_Film_Festival"}
{"title_page": "John F. Kennedy Memorial Bridge", "text_new": "{{distinguish|John F. Kennedy Boulevard Bridge}}\n{{short description|Single-deck cantilever bridge that carries southbound I-65 across the Ohio River at Louisville}}\n{{Infobox Bridge\n|bridge_name= John F. Kennedy Memorial Bridge\n|image=JFK Memorial Bridge Louisville KY.jpg\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=The John F. Kennedy Memorial Bridge in 2006 as seen from [[Jeffersonville, Indiana]]\n|official_name=\n|carries= 6 lanes of southbound {{jct|country=USA|I|65}}\n|crosses= [[Ohio River]]\n|locale= [[Louisville, Kentucky]] and [[Jeffersonville, Indiana]]\n|maint=\n|id=\n|design= [[Cantilever bridge]]\n|mainspan= {{convert|700|ft|m|sigfig=3|abbr=on}} \u00d7 2 spans\n|length= {{convert|2498|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|width=\n|clearance=\n|below=\n|traffic=\n|open= December 6, 1963\n|closed=\n|toll= $2.10 (with EZ-Pass/RiverLink transponder)<br />$1.05 frequent user (applies to all trips in calendar month with 40+ trips)<br />$3.16 (with Pay-By-Plate account)<br />$4.20 (Pay-By-Plate with no account)\n|map_cue=\n|map_image=\n|map_text=\n|map_width=\n|coordinates= {{coord|38|15|52|N|85|44|37|W|region:US_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|map_caption ={{Location map|USA Kentucky\n|border  = infobox\n|float   = center\n|lon_dir = W\n|lat_dir = N\n|lat_deg = 38\n|lat_min = 15\n|lat_sec = 52\n|lon_deg = 85\n|lon_min = 44\n|lon_sec = 37\n|width   = 250\n|caption = Location in Kentucky\n}}\n}}\nThe '''John F. Kennedy Memorial Bridge''' is a six-lane, single-deck [[cantilever bridge]] that carries southbound [[Interstate 65]] across the [[Ohio River]], connecting [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]], [[Kentucky]] and [[Jeffersonville, Indiana|Jeffersonville]], [[Indiana]].  The main span is {{convert|700|ft|sigfig=3}} (two spans) and the bridge has a total length of {{convert|2498|ft}}.  The span carries six southbound lanes. It is named after [[U.S. President]] [[John F. Kennedy]].\n\n==History==\nDesigned by the Louisville engineering firm of Hazelet & Erdal, construction began in the spring of 1961 and completed in late 1963 at a cost of $10 million. The span was unnamed when [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[John F. Kennedy]] was [[John F. Kennedy assassination|assassinated]] on November 22, 1963. Four days later, [[Governor of Kentucky|Kentucky Governor]] [[Bert T. Combs]] announced that there was wide agreement that the bridge would be named in Kennedy's honor. The bridge was dedicated and opened for northbound traffic on December 6, and southbound traffic began flowing a few weeks later.\n\nBetween the late 1990s and 2006, the bridge was covered with rust-like spots and the [[Kentucky Transportation Cabinet]] had failed in attempts to rectify this, a subject of local controversy.  The state twice paid contractors to repaint the bridge who then failed to do so.  The attempts cost over $23 million, with little apparent result. The first of the two contracts, awarded in 1999, ended two years later in a bribery scandal that resulted in criminal prosecution.<ref>{{cite news| first=Sheldon S.| last=Shafer| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/access/1771825901.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Feb+9%2C+2006&author=&pub=Courier+-+Journal&edition=&startpage=B.1&desc=Kennedy+Bridge+painting+deal+canceled| title=Kennedy Bridge painting deal canceled; State says job only 6 percent complete |work=[[The Courier-Journal]] |accessdate=2006-07-23 |date=February 9, 2006 |location=Louisville}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2006, the state awarded a $14.7 million contract to [[Intech Contracting]] of Lexington to paint half the bridge by the summer of 2007. The new contract differed in that the project was split in two, and the original plans for a three color paint scheme were replaced with a simpler all beige colored one. The very southernmost portion of the bridge was completed in three colors (brown, beige, and green), although this will be painted over.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/access/1766271891.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=May+09,+2006&author=&pub=Courier+-+Journal&desc=State+seeks+new+Kennedy+Bridge+painter&pqatl=google |first=Sheldon S. |last=Shafer |title=State awards $14.7 million bid to paint half of Kennedy Bridge |date=October 16, 2006 |work=The Courier-Journal}}</ref>\n\nOn December 5, 2007, the painting project was completed at a cost of $59 million which included the two previous failed painting projects.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.whas11.com/topstories/stories/120407whasjdtopstorybridge.6afad7f5.html |title=The Kennedy Bridge project complete |date=2007-12-05 |work=[[WHAS-TV]] News }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n[[File:John F. Kennedy Memorial Bridge repainting job.jpg|thumb|left|280px|The bridge during the last repainting project. Note the far right part of the bridge painted in a three color scheme, originally planned for the whole bridge. This scheme was abandoned and the entire bridge was painted in a light grey.]]\n\n==Second span==\nIn 2013, Kentucky broke ground on a second span as part of the [[Ohio River Bridges Project]], a project to relieve traffic congestion in the Louisville area.  The [[Abraham Lincoln Bridge]], a [[cable-stayed bridge]] that opened in December 2015, carried all Interstate 65 traffic over the Ohio River while the Kennedy Bridge received a new deck. The Kennedy Bridge now carries six lanes of southbound I-65 traffic, while the Lincoln Bridge carries six lanes of northbound I-65 traffic. The Kennedy Bridge reopened in three phases during the final months of 2016. The first phase saw one lane reopen on September 30 for traffic traveling from surface streets in Jeffersonville to I-65.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wdrb.com/story/33357789/kennedy-bridge-open-to-southbound-traffic |title=Kennedy Bridge to reopen to one lane of traffic starting Friday |publisher=[[WDRB]] |location=Louisville |date=September 28, 2016 |accessdate=October 11, 2016}}</ref> In the second phase, which took effect on October 10, the bridge reopened for I-65 through traffic, carrying five lanes of southbound traffic; at the same time, the Lincoln Bridge began carrying only northbound traffic.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wdrb.com/story/33357789/kennedy-bridge-open-to-southbound-traffic |title=Kennedy Bridge open 5 lanes of southbound traffic |first=Katrina |last=Helmer |publisher=[[WDRB]] |location=Louisville |date=October 10, 2016 |accessdate=October 11, 2016}}</ref> The final phase was the reopening of the exit ramp from the bridge to westbound I-64, which had been closed for nearly a year, on November 14.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wdrb.com/story/33700130/update-all-lanes-of-kennedy-bridge-including-ramp-to-i-64-west-now-open-2 |title=UPDATE: All lanes of Kennedy Bridge, including ramp to I-64 West, now open |publisher=[[WDRB]] |location=Louisville |date=November 14, 2016 |accessdate=November 18, 2016}}</ref> [[Toll bridge|Tolling]] began in December 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wdrb.com/story/33698740/special-assignment-what-you-need-to-know-before-tolling-starts-on-3-louisville-bridges |title=What you need to know before tolling starts on 3 Louisville bridges |publisher=[[WDRB]] |location=Louisville |date=November 13, 2016 |accessdate=November 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Transport|Engineering|United States|Indiana}}\n* [[Kennedy Interchange]] (\"Spaghetti Junction\")\n* [[List of crossings of the Ohio River]]\n* [[Ohio River Bridges Project]], the highway project which included the repurposing of this bridge for southbound traffic only\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|John F. Kennedy Memorial Bridge}}\n*[http://bridgestunnels.com/location/kennedy-memorial-bridge/ John F. Kennedy Memorial Bridge] at Bridges & Tunnels\n\n{{John F. Kennedy}}\n{{Crossings navbox\n|structure        = Bridges\n|place            = [[Ohio River]]\n|bridge           = John F. Kennedy Memorial Bridge\n|bridge signs     = '''Southbound''' [[Image:I-65.svg|20px]]\n|upstream         = [[Abraham Lincoln Bridge]]\n|upstream signs   = '''Northbound''' [[File:I-65.svg|20px]]\n|downstream       = [[George Rogers Clark Memorial Bridge]]\n|downstream signs = [[Image:US 31.svg|20px]]\n}}\n\n[[Category:Bridges in Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Bridges over the Ohio River]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1963]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Clark County, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Interstate 65]]\n[[Category:Bridges on the Interstate Highway System]]\n[[Category:Toll bridges in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Toll bridges in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Tolled sections of Interstate Highways]]\n[[Category:Cantilever bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials to John F. Kennedy in the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|John F. Kennedy Boulevard Bridge}}\n{{short description|Single-deck cantilever bridge that carries southbound I-65 across the Ohio River at Louisville}}\n{{Infobox Bridge\n|bridge_name= John F. Kennedy Memorial Bridge\n|image=JFK Memorial Bridge Louisville KY.jpg\n|image_size=300px\n|caption=The John F. Kennedy Memorial Bridge in 2006 as seen from [[Jeffersonville, Indiana]]\n|official_name=\n|carries= 6 lanes of southbound {{jct|country=USA|I|65}}\n|crosses= [[Ohio River]]\n|locale= [[Louisville, Kentucky]] and [[Jeffersonville, Indiana]]\n|maint=\n|id=\n|design= [[Cantilever bridge]]\n|mainspan= {{convert|700|ft|m|sigfig=3|abbr=on}} \u00d7 2 spans\n|length= {{convert|2498|ft|m|0|abbr=on}}\n|width=\n|clearance=\n|below=\n|traffic=\n|open= December 6, 1963\n|closed=\n|toll= $2.10 (with EZ-Pass/RiverLink transponder)<br />$1.05 frequent user (applies to all trips in calendar month with 40+ trips)<br />$3.16 (with Pay-By-Plate account)<br />$4.20 (Pay-By-Plate with no account)\n|map_cue=\n|map_image=\n|map_text=\n|map_width=\n|coordinates= {{coord|38|15|52|N|85|44|37|W|region:US_type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|map_caption ={{Location map|USA Kentucky\n|border  = infobox\n|float   = center\n|lon_dir = W\n|lat_dir = N\n|lat_deg = 38\n|lat_min = 15\n|lat_sec = 52\n|lon_deg = 85\n|lon_min = 44\n|lon_sec = 37\n|width   = 250\n|caption = Location in Kentucky\n}}\n}}\nThe '''John F. Kennedy Memorial Bridge''' is a six-lane, single-deck [[cantilever bridge]] that carries southbound [[Interstate 65]] across the [[Ohio River]], connecting [[Louisville, Kentucky|Louisville]], [[Kentucky]] and [[Jeffersonville, Indiana|Jeffersonville]], [[Indiana]].  The main span is {{convert|700|ft|sigfig=3}} (two spans) and the bridge has a total length of {{convert|2498|ft}}.  The span carries six southbound lanes. It is named after [[U.S. President]] [[John F. Kennedy]].\n\n==History==\nDesigned by the Louisville engineering firm of Hazelet & Erdal, construction began in the spring of 1961 and completed in late 1963 at a cost of $10 million. The span was unnamed when [[President of the United States|U.S. President]] [[John F. Kennedy]] was [[John F. Kennedy assassination|assassinated]] on November 22, 1963. Four days later, [[Governor of Kentucky|Kentucky Governor]] [[Bert T. Combs]] announced that there was wide agreement that the bridge would be named in Kennedy's honor. The bridge was dedicated and opened for northbound traffic on December 6, and southbound traffic began flowing a few weeks later.\n\nBetween the late 1990s and 2006, the bridge was covered with rust-like spots and the [[Kentucky Transportation Cabinet]] had failed in attempts to rectify this, a subject of local controversy.  The state twice paid contractors to repaint the bridge who then failed to do so.  The attempts cost over $23 million, with little apparent result. The first of the two contracts, awarded in 1999, ended two years later in a bribery scandal that resulted in criminal prosecution.<ref>{{cite news| first=Sheldon S.| last=Shafer| url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/access/1771825901.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&date=Feb+9%2C+2006&author=&pub=Courier+-+Journal&edition=&startpage=B.1&desc=Kennedy+Bridge+painting+deal+canceled| title=Kennedy Bridge painting deal canceled; State says job only 6 percent complete |work=[[The Courier-Journal]] |accessdate=2006-07-23 |date=February 9, 2006 |location=Louisville}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2006, the state awarded a $14.7 million contract to [[Intech Contracting]] of Lexington to paint half the bridge by the summer of 2007. The new contract differed in that the project was split in two, and the original plans for a three color paint scheme were replaced with a simpler all beige colored one. The very southernmost portion of the bridge was completed in three colors (brown, beige, and green), although this will be painted over.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/courier_journal/access/1766271891.html?FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT&type=current&date=May+09,+2006&author=&pub=Courier+-+Journal&desc=State+seeks+new+Kennedy+Bridge+painter&pqatl=google |first=Sheldon S. |last=Shafer |title=State awards $14.7 million bid to paint half of Kennedy Bridge |date=October 16, 2006 |work=The Courier-Journal}}</ref>\n\nOn December 5, 2007, the painting project was completed at a cost of $59 million which included the two previous failed painting projects.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.whas11.com/topstories/stories/120407whasjdtopstorybridge.6afad7f5.html |title=The Kennedy Bridge project complete |date=2007-12-05 |work=[[WHAS-TV]] News }}{{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>\n\n[[File:John F. Kennedy Memorial Bridge repainting job.jpg|thumb|left|280px|The bridge during the last repainting project. Note the far right part of the bridge painted in a three color scheme, originally planned for the whole bridge. This scheme was abandoned and the entire bridge was painted in a light grey.]]\n\n==Second span==\nIn 2013, Kentucky broke ground on a second span as part of the [[Ohio River Bridges Project]], a project to relieve traffic congestion in the Louisville area.  The [[Abraham Lincoln Bridge]], a [[cable-stayed bridge]] that opened in December 2015, carried all Interstate 65 traffic over the Ohio River while the Kennedy Bridge received a new deck. The Kennedy Bridge now carries six lanes of southbound I-65 traffic, while the Lincoln Bridge carries six lanes of northbound I-65 traffic. The Kennedy Bridge reopened in three phases during the final months of 2016. The first phase saw one lane reopen on September 30 for traffic traveling from surface streets in Jeffersonville to I-65.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wdrb.com/story/33357789/kennedy-bridge-open-to-southbound-traffic |title=Kennedy Bridge to reopen to one lane of traffic starting Friday |publisher=[[WDRB]] |location=Louisville |date=September 28, 2016 |accessdate=October 11, 2016}}</ref> In the second phase, which took effect on October 10, the bridge reopened for I-65 through traffic, carrying five lanes of southbound traffic; at the same time, the Lincoln Bridge began carrying only northbound traffic.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wdrb.com/story/33357789/kennedy-bridge-open-to-southbound-traffic |title=Kennedy Bridge open 5 lanes of southbound traffic |first=Katrina |last=Helmer |publisher=[[WDRB]] |location=Louisville |date=October 10, 2016 |accessdate=October 11, 2016}}</ref> The final phase was the reopening of the exit ramp from the bridge to westbound I-64, which had been closed for nearly a year, on November 14.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wdrb.com/story/33700130/update-all-lanes-of-kennedy-bridge-including-ramp-to-i-64-west-now-open-2 |title=UPDATE: All lanes of Kennedy Bridge, including ramp to I-64 West, now open |publisher=[[WDRB]] |location=Louisville |date=November 14, 2016 |accessdate=November 18, 2016}}</ref> [[Toll bridge|Tolling]] began in December 2016.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.wdrb.com/story/33698740/special-assignment-what-you-need-to-know-before-tolling-starts-on-3-louisville-bridges |title=What you need to know before tolling starts on 3 Louisville bridges |publisher=[[WDRB]] |location=Louisville |date=November 13, 2016 |accessdate=November 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Transport|Engineering|United States|Indiana}}\n* [[Kennedy Interchange]] (\"Spaghetti Junction\")\n* [[List of crossings of the Ohio River]]\n* [[Ohio River Bridges Project]], the highway project which included the repurposing of this bridge for southbound traffic only\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|John F. Kennedy Memorial Bridge}}\n* [http://www.kentuckyroads.com/images/kennedy_bridge/ John F. Kennedy Memorial Bridge at Kentuckyroads.com]\n* [https://www.facebook.com/OhioRiverBridges Forum to discuss the bridge]\n\n{{John F. Kennedy}}\n{{Crossings navbox\n|structure        = Bridges\n|place            = [[Ohio River]]\n|bridge           = John F. Kennedy Memorial Bridge\n|bridge signs     = '''Southbound''' [[Image:I-65.svg|20px]]\n|upstream         = [[Abraham Lincoln Bridge]]\n|upstream signs   = '''Northbound''' [[File:I-65.svg|20px]]\n|downstream       = [[George Rogers Clark Memorial Bridge]]\n|downstream signs = [[Image:US 31.svg|20px]]\n}}\n\n[[Category:Bridges in Louisville, Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Bridges over the Ohio River]]\n[[Category:Bridges completed in 1963]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Clark County, Indiana]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Road bridges in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Interstate 65]]\n[[Category:Bridges on the Interstate Highway System]]\n[[Category:Toll bridges in Indiana]]\n[[Category:Toll bridges in Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Tolled sections of Interstate Highways]]\n[[Category:Cantilever bridges in the United States]]\n[[Category:Monuments and memorials to John F. Kennedy in the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Seicer", "label": "safe", "comment": "Link modification", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_F._Kennedy_Memorial_Bridge"}
{"title_page": "Hadi al-Modarresi", "text_new": "{{about|an Iraqi [[ayatollah]]|his [[Marja' (Islamic law)|Grand Ayatollah]] brother|Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi}}\n[[Ayatollah]] [[Sayyid]] '''Hadi al-Husayni al-Modarresi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0647\u0627\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u064a}}; {{lang-fa|{{nq|\u0647\u0627\u062f\u0649 \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u0649 \u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u0649}}}}; b. 1947<ref name=\":022\">{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/%D8%B9%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%A6%D8%B1_%D9%83%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%A1_%D9%88%D8%A3%D8%B3%D8%B1%D9%87%D8%A7.html?id=L3ltAAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Asha'er Karbala Wa 'Usariha|date=|publisher=Dar al-Mahaja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=197\u20138|language=ar|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>), is an [[Iraqis|Iraqi]]-[[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] [[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[Ulama|scholar]], [[Islamic leadership|leader]] and [[orator]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Shaykh|first=Mansoor|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2_fXAAAAMAAJ|title=al-Alama al-Modarresi, Mawaqifah Wa Afkaruh|date=1991|publisher=Dar Wa Maktabat al-Mustafa|year=|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=al-Modarresi the scholar, His stands and thoughts}}</ref> {{Infobox religious biography|name=Hadi al-Modarresi|native_name={{lang|fa|\u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u062f \u0647\u0627\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u064a}}|students=|denomination=[[Twelver]] [[Shia Islam|Sh\u012b\u02bf\u0101]]|religion=Islam|relatives=[[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi]] (brother)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=581|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref> <br /> [[Ali Akbar al-Modarresi]] (brother)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=581|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref> <br /> [[Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi]] (grandfather) <br /> [[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi|Muhammad al-Shirazi]] (maternal uncle)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lou\u00ebr|first=Laurence|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B8wnEtH8oDgC|title=Transnational Shia Politics: Religious and Political Networks in the Gulf|date=2011|publisher=Hurst|year=|isbn=978-1-84904-214-7|location=|pages=93|language=en}}</ref> <br /> [[Sadiq Hussaini Shirazi|Sadiq al-Shirazi]] (maternal uncle)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lou\u00ebr|first=Laurence|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B8wnEtH8oDgC|title=Transnational Shia Politics: Religious and Political Networks in the Gulf|date=2011|publisher=Hurst|year=|isbn=978-1-84904-214-7|location=|pages=93|language=en}}</ref> <br /> [[Abd al-A'la al-Sabziwari]] (uncle-in-law)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=345|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref> <br /> Muhammad-Reza Gharavi (second cousin, once removed)|website=[http://www.hadialmodarresi.com/ http://www.hadialmodarresi.com/]|children={{hlist|[[Mahdi al-Modarresi|Mahdi]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://modarresi.org/english/biography.htm|title=Office of Sayed Mahdi al-Modarresi|last=|first=|date=|website=www.almodarresi.org|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>|Muhammed-Ali|Mustafa|Husayn|Muhammad-Kadhim}}|death_place=|nationality=[[Iraq|Iraqi]] <br/> [[Iran|Iranian]] <br/> [[Bahrain|Bahraini]] (withdrawn)|birth_place=[[Karbala]], [[Kingdom of Iraq|Iraq]]|death_date=|birth_date={{Birth year and age|1947}}<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/%D8%B9%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%A6%D8%B1_%D9%83%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%A1_%D9%88%D8%A3%D8%B3%D8%B1%D9%87%D8%A7.html?id=L3ltAAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Asha'er Karbala Wa 'Usariha|date=|publisher=Dar al-Mahaja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=197\u20138|language=ar|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>|caption=al-Modarresi in a gathering in [[London]], 2019|image=Hadi al-Modarresi.jpg|honorific-prefix=[[Ayatollah]] [[Sayyid]]|background=#ABE9CC|parents=[[Mohammed Kadhim al-Modarresi]]|spouse=|title=[[Ayatollah]]}}al-Modarresi is a charismatic speaker, and has enamored many Muslims, radiating a certain magnetism in his oratory. He spent much of his career in opposition to the [[Ba'athist Iraq|Bathist government]], and he spent many years in exile, particularly in Bahrain. al-Modarresi returned to Iraq following the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], and administers humanitarian projects in there.\n\n== Family ==\nal-Modarresi was born into a distinguished Shia religious family in [[Karbala]] in [[Iraq]]. His father is Ayatollah Sayyid [[Mohammed Kadhim al-Modarresi|Muhammad-Kadhim al-Modarresi]], the grandson of grand Ayatollah Sayyid Muhammad-Baqir Golpayegani (also known as ''Jorfadiqani'').<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Tehrani|first=Agha Buzurg|url=http://alfeker.net/library.php?id=3324|title=Tabaqat A'lam al-Shia; al-Kiram al-Barara Fi al-Qarn al-Thalith Ashar|publisher=Dar Ihya' al-Turath al-Arabi|year=2009|isbn=|volume=10|location=Cairo, Egpyt|pages=165|trans-title=Levels of the Notables of the Shia (13th Century)}}</ref> His mother is the daughter of grand Ayatollah Sayyid [[Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi|Mahdi al-Shirazi]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lou\u00ebr|first=Laurence|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B8wnEtH8oDgC|title=Transnational Shia Politics: Religious and Political Networks in the Gulf|date=2011|publisher=Hurst|year=|isbn=978-1-84904-214-7|location=|pages=93|language=en}}</ref> He claims descent from [[Zayd ibn Ali]] (died c. 740 AD), the great-great-grandson of the [[Prophets in Islam|Islamic prophet]], [[Muhammad]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/%D8%B9%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%A6%D8%B1_%D9%83%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%A1_%D9%88%D8%A3%D8%B3%D8%B1%D9%87%D8%A7.html?id=L3ltAAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Asha'er Karbala Wa 'Usariha|date=|publisher=Dar al-Mahaja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=197-8|language=ar|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early life ===\nal-Modarresi began his religious education in the religious seminaries of Karbala, at the age of thirteen. He actively sought his religious studies under the auspices of many high ranking scholars, such as Sheikh Hasan al-A'lami, Sheikh Muhammad al-Karbassi, Shaykh Jafar al-Rushti, Shaykh Muhamamd-Husayn al-Mazindarani and his uncles, Sayyids [[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi|Muhammad]], Hassan and Sadiq al-Shirazi.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Mu'min|first=Ali|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6uvXAAAAMAAJ|title=Sanawat al-Jamr|date=2004|publisher=al-Markaz al-Islami al-Mu'asir|year=|isbn=|location=Iraq|pages=285|language=ar|trans-title=Years of Charcoal}}</ref><ref name=\":02\" /> In the late sixties, he and his uncle, [[Mujtaba Hussaini Shirazi|Mujtaba al-Shirazi]], attended the class of Sayyid [[Ruhollah Khomeini]], and became one of his closest students.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=al-Alawi|first=Jaffar|url=|title=al-Mujahid al-Sayed Hadi al-Modarresi Fi Muwajahat al-Tughyan al-Khalifi|publisher=|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=|trans-title=The Mujahid Sayyid Hadi al-Modarresi in the face of Al Khalifa's tyranny}}</ref> He completed the advanced level of his religious education in his early twenties.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://modarresi.org/biography/index.html|title=al-Sira al-Thatiya|last=|first=|date=|website=Office of Sayed Hadi Al-Modarresi|trans-title=The Biography|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Bathist Opposition ===\nal-Modarresi's advocacy of political freedom and strong stance against terrorism started from an early age when [[Saddam Hussein]] took power in Iraq. Seventeen members of his wife's family\u2013al-Qazwini\u2013were executed by Saddam's regime or simply disappeared in the notorious Bathist penitentiaries. al-Modarresi wrote the first book to openly attack the regime, published by a religious scholar. Published under a pseudonym in Beirut, the book was titled ''No To Rulers of Iraq'' and sparked a massive political crisis in [[Baghdad]] and caused the Bathist regime to issue an ultimatum for the removal of all Lebanese nationals from Iraq within 72 hours.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nal-Modarresi eluded execution by moving from house to house, often living in cellars for months and traveling in disguise. When his uncle, Hasan was imprisoned, and the pressures of the [[Ba'athist Iraq|Bathists]] anti-Shia sentiment peaked<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2013-03-20/saddam-husseins-legacy-sectarian-division-iraq|title=Saddam Hussein's legacy of sectarian division in Iraq|website=Public Radio International|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/iraqs-oppressed-majority-95250996/|title=Iraq's Oppressed Majority|website=Smithsonian Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>, al-Modarresi left Iraq in 1970, for [[Lebanon]], and then briefly joined his brother [[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi|Muhammad-Taqi]], in Kuwait.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5hdIAQAAIAAJ|title=al-Majallah|date=1996|publisher=al-Sharikah al-Sa\u02bb\u016bd\u012byah lil-Ab\u1e25\u0101th wa-al-Nashr|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=71|language=ar}}</ref>\n\n=== Bahraini Leadership ===\nIn 1973, he emigrated to Bahrain, and exercised his religious activism there. In 1974, he was granted [[Bahrain|Bahraini]] citizenship.<ref name=\"EhteshamiQuilliam2016\">{{cite book|author1=Anoushiravan Ehteshami|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NpLJDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA67|title=Security and Bilateral Issues between Iran and its Arab Neighbours|author2=Neil Quilliam|author3=Gawdat Bahgat|date=21 December 2016|publisher=Springer|year=|isbn=978-3-319-43289-2|location=|pages=67}}</ref> In Bahrain, al-Modarresi rose to national prominence, and was awarded with power of representation from grand religious authorities such as Muhammad al-Shirazi, Ruhollah Khomeini<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=al-Hasan|first=Abd al-Latif|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Gw5SDwAAQBAJ|title=al-Ilaqa al-Siyasiya Bayn Iran Wa al-Arab: Juthuruha Wa Marahiliha Wa Atwariha|date=2018-03-19|publisher=al-Ibikan Lil Nashr|year=|isbn=978-603-509-173-2|location=|pages=394|language=ar|trans-title=The Political relationship between Iran and the Arabs: It's roots, stages and development}}</ref>, [[Shahab ud-Din Mar'ashi Najafi|Shihab al-Din al-Marashi]], and [[Abd al-A'la al-Sabziwari]], being labelled as a scholar \"worthy of taking a leadership position\" and urging Muslims to follow his lead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://modarresi.org/biography/bio_rep_index.html|title=al-Wikalat al-Shar'iya Wa al-Ruwa'iya|last=|first=|date=|website=Office of Sayed Hadi Al-Modarresi|trans-title=Religious Power of Representation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Marschall|first=Dr Christin|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Iran_s_Persian_Gulf_Policy.html?id=zMerz59o71IC&redir_esc=y|title=Iran's Persian Gulf Policy: From Khomeini to Khatami|date=2003-12-08|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-134-42991-2|location=|pages=32|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Matthiesen|first=Toby|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cv9-wwT0tHcC&pg=PA40|title=Sectarian Gulf: Bahrain, Saudi Arabia, and the Arab Spring That Wasn't|date=2013-07-03|publisher=Stanford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-8047-8722-2|location=|pages=40|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979, the Bahraini authorities placed a travel ban on al-Modarresi, after his organisation, the [[Islamic Front for the Liberation of Bahrain|Islamic Front for Liberation of Bahrain]] (a branch of his brother's (Muhammad-Taqi) larger [[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi#Activism|risali]] movement), was announced in the press, being dubbed as an organisation that wanted to import the [[Iranian Revolution|Iranian revolution]] into Bahrain, and pointing the finger at al-Modarresi, as its leader.<ref name=\":1\" /> In August of that year, he was kidnapped by the Bahraini intelligence and locked up in a car for up to fourteen hours. However, there was an international uproar, with the interference of some of the Islamic republic's senior leaders, and [[Yasser Arafat]] personally, that pressured the Bahraini government to release him, and send him over to Iran, with an apology.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Exile in Iran===\nWhilst in Iran, al-Modarresi continued his activism and kept provoking the Bahraini population against the [[House of Khalifa|Al Khalifah]] regime. The IFLB came to prominence as the front organisation for the [[1981 Bahraini coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|1981 coup]], which attempted to install al-Modarresi as the spiritual leader of a newly established theocratic Shia state.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Blank|first=Stephen|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Low_intensity_Conflict_in_the_Third_Worl.html?id=s_RiAAAAMAAJ|title=Low-intensity Conflict in the Third World|last2=Ware|first2=Lewis B.|date=1988|publisher=Air University Press|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=8|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Ayalon|first=Ami|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gce1I2KAxdwC|title=Middle East Contemporary Survey, Volume Xii, 1988|date=1990-09-25|publisher=The Moshe Dayan Center|year=|isbn=978-0-8133-1044-2|location=|pages=429|language=en}}</ref> However the coup failed, and so al-Modarresi reorganised the structure of the Front, focusing on its information efforts in Europe.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rabinovich|first=Itamar|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=m1XjHn8rrl4C|title=Middle East Contemporary Survey: Volume Ix, 1984-1985|last2=Shaked|first2=Haim|date=1988-01-10|publisher=The Moshe Dayan Center|year=|isbn=978-0-8133-7445-1|location=|pages=393-94|language=en}}</ref> \n\nal-Modarresi became a founding member of the [[Islamic Supreme Council of Iraq|Supreme Council for the Islamic Revolution in Iraq]] (SCIRI), and was among the active figures of the Iraqi opposition in exile. He was closely involved in efforts to expose and bring down the regime in Baghdad. He managed to escape a number of assassination attempts abroad, including one in Brazil in 1991 as well as two more attempts in Syria, by the Bathist intelligence operatives, in 2001.\n\n=== Return to Iraq ===\nUpon returning to Iraq after the fall of Saddam's regime, he was greeted by over thirty thousand people in Baghdad, fifty thousand in [[Sadr City]] and a similar crowd in his hometown, Karbala.\n\nal-Modarresi established a television station upon his return to his hometown.<ref name=\":3\" /> He is also involved in several large-scale humanitarian projects in Iraq and has been involved in the building of mosques, schools, medical clinics, orphanages, and has been a staunch advocate of women's rights and consistently speaks out against the oppression of women in his lectures and books. He also facilitates marriage by providing financial help to people who wish to get married and has organized several large mass marriage ceremonies. sl-Modarresi also founded and currently heads the League of Religious Scholars which brings together many high ranking Shi\u2019ite scholars or their representatives in Iraq.\n\n== Personal Life ==\nal-Modarresi is married to the daughter of prominent scholar, Hashim al-Qazwini (d. 2009), the elder brother of [[Mortada Al-Qazwini|Murtadha al-Qazwini]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://burathanews.com/arabic/news/69843|title=Tashyee' al-Sayyid Hashim al-Qazwini al-Najl al-Akbar Li Ayatollah al-Shahid al-Sayyid Muhammad-Sadiq al-Qazwini Fi Karbala|last=|first=|date=2009-07-08|website=al-Buratha News Outlet|language=ar-iq|trans-title=Sayyid Hashim al-Qazwini, oldest son of Ayatollah Muhammad-Sadiq al-Qazwini dies in Karbala|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> He has five sons ([[Mahdi al-Modarresi|Mahdi]], Muhammad-Ali, Mustafa, Husayn and Muhammad-Kadhim). All of his sons are clerics. \n\n=== COVID-19 ===\nDuring the outbreak of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], al-Modarresi expressed the opinion that the virus was a signal of Godly punishment for the [[Chinese people|Chinese]] population, because of the foods they consume<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-causes|title=Coronavirus causes: Origin and how it spreads|website=www.medicalnewstoday.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>, that are deemed Islamically unlawful, as well as their [[Cultural genocide of Uyghurs|mistreatment]] of the [[Uyghurs|Uighur]] Muslims.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zZbOFcMt66s|title=Ayatollah Hadi al-Mudarrisi Yakshif Asbab Intishar Virus Corona Fi al-Sin|last=|first=|date=|website=YouTube|trans-title=Ayatollah Hadi al-Modarresi uncovers the reasons behind the spread of the Coronavirus|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> However al-Modarresi did clarify in his speech, that despite the disease affecting a specific nation [at the time of the statement], all nations must cooperate and not take advantage of the disease for political gain, because the disease can still affect us all, hence we must all work collectively to treat this virus, and that this is the responsibility of the entire world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TheSayed/status/1237387512902893569|title=Shahid Hatha al-Maqta' Wa Kafak Dajalan Wa Khida'a Wa Tahreedhan Lil Naas|last=al-Modarresi|first=al-Sayyid Mahdi|date=2020-03-10|website=@TheSayed|language=ar|trans-title=Watch this clip and enough deceit, lies and provocation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, it was alleged that al-Modarresi had contracted the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alhurra.com/iraq/2020/03/07/%D8%A5%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%A8%D8%A9-%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%AC%D8%B9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%82%D9%8A-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%B2-%D8%A8%D9%81%D9%8A%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B3-%D9%83%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%88%D9%86%D8%A7|title=Isabat Marji Iraqi Bariz Bi Virus Corona|last=|first=|date=|website=Al-Hurra|language=ar|trans-title=Grand Iraqi Marja Contracts Corona Virus|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> However he has since reported to be in good health.\n\n== Works ==\nal-Modarresi has authored more than 250 books. Some of them include:\n\n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|title=God's Sacrifice: The Epic Saga of Hussein and His Legendary Martyrdom|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-0994240927|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Heated Debate on Atheism|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1548180010|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=How to Beat Failure, Advise on Success and Time Management|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-9953299563|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Art of Success|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-9953299532|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}} (7 Volumes)\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=How to Enjoy Life and Live Happily|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=And They Ask You About Things|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Shortcuts To Glory|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Supplications of the Quran|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=A B Islam|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Supplications of the Quran|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Universal Challenges, Refurbishing Civilisation|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Mannerisms of the Commander of the Faithful|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}} (3 Volumes)\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Ashura|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=The Martyr and the Revolution|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=The Message of a Muslim.. To Save the World|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Critique on Marxism|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Response to [[Satanic Verses]] Book|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Friend and Friendhsip|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official|http://www.modarresi.org}} (in Arabic)\n*[http://alfeker.net/authors.php?id=13 Library of al-Modarresi's books] by ''al-Feker E-book Network'' (in Arabic)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Modarresi, Hadi}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Shia clerics]]\n[[Category:Politics of Bahrain]]\n[[Category:Politics of Iraq]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:People from Karbala]]\n[[Category:Iraqi people of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People of the Bahraini uprising of 2011]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|an Iraqi [[ayatollah]]|his [[Marja' (Islamic law)|Grand Ayatollah]] brother|Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi}}\n[[Ayatollah]] [[Sayyid]] '''Hadi al-Husayni al-Modarresi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0647\u0627\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u064a}}; {{lang-fa|{{nq|\u0647\u0627\u062f\u0649 \u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u0649 \u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u0649}}}}; b. 1947<ref name=\":022\">{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/%D8%B9%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%A6%D8%B1_%D9%83%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%A1_%D9%88%D8%A3%D8%B3%D8%B1%D9%87%D8%A7.html?id=L3ltAAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Asha'er Karbala Wa 'Usariha|date=|publisher=Dar al-Mahaja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=197\u20138|language=ar|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>), is an [[Iraqis|Iraqi]]-[[Iranian peoples|Iranian]] [[Shia Islam|Shia]] [[Ulama|scholar]], [[Islamic leadership|leader]] and [[orator]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Shaykh|first=Mansoor|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=2_fXAAAAMAAJ|title=al-Alama al-Modarresi, Mawaqifah Wa Afkaruh|date=1991|publisher=Dar Wa Maktabat al-Mustafa|year=|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=al-Modarresi the scholar, His stands and thoughts}}</ref> {{Infobox religious biography|name=Hadi al-Modarresi|native_name={{lang|fa|\u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u062f \u0647\u0627\u062f\u064a \u0627\u0644\u062d\u0633\u064a\u0646\u064a \u0627\u0644\u0645\u062f\u0631\u0633\u064a}}|students=|denomination=[[Twelver]] [[Shia Islam|Sh\u012b\u02bf\u0101]]|religion=Islam|relatives=[[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi]] (brother)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=581|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref> <br /> [[Ali Akbar al-Modarresi]] (brother)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=581|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref> <br /> [[Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi]] (grandfather) <br /> [[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi|Muhammad al-Shirazi]] (maternal uncle)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lou\u00ebr|first=Laurence|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B8wnEtH8oDgC|title=Transnational Shia Politics: Religious and Political Networks in the Gulf|date=2011|publisher=Hurst|year=|isbn=978-1-84904-214-7|location=|pages=93|language=en}}</ref> <br /> [[Sadiq Hussaini Shirazi|Sadiq al-Shirazi]] (maternal uncle)<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lou\u00ebr|first=Laurence|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B8wnEtH8oDgC|title=Transnational Shia Politics: Religious and Political Networks in the Gulf|date=2011|publisher=Hurst|year=|isbn=978-1-84904-214-7|location=|pages=93|language=en}}</ref> <br /> [[Abd al-A'la al-Sabziwari]] (uncle-in-law)<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Muhtadi|first=Abd al-Atheem|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=9PjWAAAAMAAJ|title=Qusas Wa Khawatir - Min Akhlaqiyat 'Ulama' al-Din|publisher=Mu'asasat al-Balagh|year=2009|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=345|trans-title=Stories and Memories - From the Manners of the Scholars}}</ref> <br /> Muhammad-Reza Gharavi (second cousin, once removed)|website=[http://www.modarresi.org http://www.modarresi.org]|children={{hlist|[[Mahdi al-Modarresi|Mahdi]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://modarresi.org/english/biography.htm|title=Office of Sayed Mahdi al-Modarresi|last=|first=|date=|website=www.almodarresi.org|language=English|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>|Muhammed-Ali|Mustafa|Husayn|Muhammad-Kadhim}}|death_place=|nationality=[[Iraq|Iraqi]] <br/> [[Iran|Iranian]] <br/> [[Bahrain|Bahraini]] (withdrawn) <br /> [[Austrlia|Australian]]|birth_place=[[Karbala]], [[Kingdom of Iraq|Iraq]]|death_date=|birth_date={{Birth year and age|1947}}<ref>{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/%D8%B9%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%A6%D8%B1_%D9%83%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%A1_%D9%88%D8%A3%D8%B3%D8%B1%D9%87%D8%A7.html?id=L3ltAAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Asha'er Karbala Wa 'Usariha|date=|publisher=Dar al-Mahaja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=197\u20138|language=ar|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>|caption=al-Modarresi in a gathering in [[London]], 2019|image=Hadi al-Modarresi.jpg|honorific-prefix=[[Ayatollah]] [[Sayyid]]|background=#ABE9CC|parents=[[Mohammed Kadhim al-Modarresi]]|spouse=|title=[[Ayatollah]]}}al-Modarresi is a charismatic speaker, and has enamored many Muslims, radiating a certain magnetism in his oratory. He spent much of his career in opposition to the [[Ba'athist Iraq|Bathist government]], and he spent many years in exile, particularly in Bahrain. al-Modarresi returned to Iraq following the [[2003 invasion of Iraq]], and administers humanitarian projects in there.\n\n== Family ==\nal-Modarresi was born into a distinguished Shia religious family in [[Karbala]] in [[Iraq]]. His father is Ayatollah Sayyid [[Mohammed Kadhim al-Modarresi|Muhammad-Kadhim al-Modarresi]], the grandson of grand Ayatollah Sayyid Muhammad-Baqir Golpayegani (also known as ''Jorfadiqani'').<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Tehrani|first=Agha Buzurg|url=http://alfeker.net/library.php?id=3324|title=Tabaqat A'lam al-Shia; al-Kiram al-Barara Fi al-Qarn al-Thalith Ashar|publisher=Dar Ihya' al-Turath al-Arabi|year=2009|isbn=|volume=10|location=Cairo, Egpyt|pages=165|trans-title=Levels of the Notables of the Shia (13th Century)}}</ref> His mother is the daughter of grand Ayatollah Sayyid [[Mirza Mahdi al-Shirazi|Mahdi al-Shirazi]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=Lou\u00ebr|first=Laurence|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=B8wnEtH8oDgC|title=Transnational Shia Politics: Religious and Political Networks in the Gulf|date=2011|publisher=Hurst|year=|isbn=978-1-84904-214-7|location=|pages=93|language=en}}</ref> He claims descent from [[Zayd ibn Ali]] (died c. 740 AD), the great-great-grandson of the [[Prophets in Islam|Islamic prophet]], [[Muhammad]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite book|last=\u1e6cu\u02bbmah|first=Salm\u0101n H\u0101d\u012b|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/%D8%B9%D8%B4%D8%A7%D8%A6%D8%B1_%D9%83%D8%B1%D8%A8%D9%84%D8%A7%D8%A1_%D9%88%D8%A3%D8%B3%D8%B1%D9%87%D8%A7.html?id=L3ltAAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Asha'er Karbala Wa 'Usariha|date=|publisher=Dar al-Mahaja al-Baydha'|year=1998|isbn=|location=Beirut, Lebanon|pages=197-8|language=ar|trans-title=Tribes and Families of Karbala}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\n=== Early life ===\nal-Modarresi began his religious education in the religious seminaries of Karbala, at the age of thirteen. He actively sought his religious studies under the auspices of many high ranking scholars, such as Sheikh Hasan al-A'lami, Sheikh Muhammad al-Karbassi, Shaykh Jafar al-Rushti, Shaykh Muhamamd-Husayn al-Mazindarani and his uncles, Sayyids [[Mohammad al-Husayni al-Shirazi|Muhammad]], Hassan and Sadiq al-Shirazi.<ref>{{Cite book|last=al-Mu'min|first=Ali|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=6uvXAAAAMAAJ|title=Sanawat al-Jamr|date=2004|publisher=al-Markaz al-Islami al-Mu'asir|year=|isbn=|location=Iraq|pages=285|language=ar|trans-title=Years of Charcoal}}</ref><ref name=\":02\" /> In the late sixties, he and his uncle, [[Mujtaba Hussaini Shirazi|Mujtaba al-Shirazi]], attended the class of Sayyid [[Ruhollah Khomeini]], and became one of his closest students.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=al-Alawi|first=Jaffar|url=|title=al-Mujahid al-Sayed Hadi al-Modarresi Fi Muwajahat al-Tughyan al-Khalifi|publisher=|year=2012|isbn=|location=|pages=|trans-title=The Mujahid Sayyid Hadi al-Modarresi in the face of Al Khalifa's tyranny}}</ref> He completed the advanced level of his religious education in his early twenties.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://modarresi.org/biography/index.html|title=al-Sira al-Thatiya|last=|first=|date=|website=Office of Sayed Hadi Al-Modarresi|trans-title=The Biography|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Bathist Opposition ===\nal-Modarresi's advocacy of political freedom and strong stance against terrorism started from an early age when [[Saddam Hussein]] took power in Iraq. Seventeen members of his wife's family\u2013al-Qazwini\u2013were executed by Saddam's regime or simply disappeared in the notorious Bathist penitentiaries. al-Modarresi wrote the first book to openly attack the regime, published by a religious scholar. Published under a pseudonym in Beirut, the book was titled ''No To Rulers of Iraq'' and sparked a massive political crisis in [[Baghdad]] and caused the Bathist regime to issue an ultimatum for the removal of all Lebanese nationals from Iraq within 72 hours.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nal-Modarresi eluded execution by moving from house to house, often living in cellars for months and traveling in disguise. When his uncle, Hasan was imprisoned, and the pressures of the [[Ba'athist Iraq|Bathists]] anti-Shia sentiment peaked<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pri.org/stories/2013-03-20/saddam-husseins-legacy-sectarian-division-iraq|title=Saddam Hussein's legacy of sectarian division in Iraq|website=Public Radio International|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.smithsonianmag.com/history/iraqs-oppressed-majority-95250996/|title=Iraq's Oppressed Majority|website=Smithsonian Magazine|language=en|access-date=2020-01-15}}</ref>, al-Modarresi left Iraq in 1970, for [[Lebanon]], and then briefly joined his brother [[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi|Muhammad-Taqi]], in Kuwait.<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=5hdIAQAAIAAJ|title=al-Majallah|date=1996|publisher=al-Sharikah al-Sa\u02bb\u016bd\u012byah lil-Ab\u1e25\u0101th wa-al-Nashr|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=71|language=ar}}</ref>\n\n=== Bahraini Leadership ===\nIn 1973, he emigrated to Bahrain, and exercised his religious activism there. In 1974, he was granted [[Bahrain|Bahraini]] citizenship.<ref name=\"EhteshamiQuilliam2016\">{{cite book|author1=Anoushiravan Ehteshami|first=|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NpLJDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA67|title=Security and Bilateral Issues between Iran and its Arab Neighbours|author2=Neil Quilliam|author3=Gawdat Bahgat|date=21 December 2016|publisher=Springer|year=|isbn=978-3-319-43289-2|location=|pages=67}}</ref> In Bahrain, al-Modarresi rose to national prominence, and was awarded with power of representation from grand religious authorities such as Muhammad al-Shirazi, Ruhollah Khomeini<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=al-Hasan|first=Abd al-Latif|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Gw5SDwAAQBAJ|title=al-Ilaqa al-Siyasiya Bayn Iran Wa al-Arab: Juthuruha Wa Marahiliha Wa Atwariha|date=2018-03-19|publisher=al-Ibikan Lil Nashr|year=|isbn=978-603-509-173-2|location=|pages=394|language=ar|trans-title=The Political relationship between Iran and the Arabs: It's roots, stages and development}}</ref>, [[Shahab ud-Din Mar'ashi Najafi|Shihab al-Din al-Marashi]], and [[Abd al-A'la al-Sabziwari]], being labelled as a scholar \"worthy of taking a leadership position\" and urging Muslims to follow his lead.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://modarresi.org/biography/bio_rep_index.html|title=al-Wikalat al-Shar'iya Wa al-Ruwa'iya|last=|first=|date=|website=Office of Sayed Hadi Al-Modarresi|trans-title=Religious Power of Representation|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Marschall|first=Dr Christin|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Iran_s_Persian_Gulf_Policy.html?id=zMerz59o71IC&redir_esc=y|title=Iran's Persian Gulf Policy: From Khomeini to Khatami|date=2003-12-08|publisher=Routledge|year=|isbn=978-1-134-42991-2|location=|pages=32|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|last=Matthiesen|first=Toby|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=cv9-wwT0tHcC&pg=PA40|title=Sectarian Gulf: Bahrain, Saudi Arabia, and the Arab Spring That Wasn't|date=2013-07-03|publisher=Stanford University Press|year=|isbn=978-0-8047-8722-2|location=|pages=40|language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn 1979, the Bahraini authorities placed a travel ban on al-Modarresi, after his organisation, the [[Islamic Front for the Liberation of Bahrain|Islamic Front for Liberation of Bahrain]] (a branch of his brother's (Muhammad-Taqi) larger [[Mohammad Taqi al-Modarresi#Activism|risali]] movement), was announced in the press, being dubbed as an organisation that wanted to import the [[Iranian Revolution|Iranian revolution]] into Bahrain, and pointing the finger at al-Modarresi, as its leader.<ref name=\":1\" /> In August of that year, he was kidnapped by the Bahraini intelligence and locked up in a car for up to fourteen hours. However, there was an international uproar, with the interference of some of the Islamic republic's senior leaders, and [[Yasser Arafat]] personally, that pressured the Bahraini government to release him, and send him over to Iran, with an apology.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Exile in Iran===\nWhilst in Iran, al-Modarresi continued his activism and kept provoking the Bahraini population against the [[House of Khalifa|Al Khalifah]] regime. The IFLB came to prominence as the front organisation for the [[1981 Bahraini coup d'\u00e9tat attempt|1981 coup]], which attempted to install al-Modarresi as the spiritual leader of a newly established theocratic Shia state.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Blank|first=Stephen|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Low_intensity_Conflict_in_the_Third_Worl.html?id=s_RiAAAAMAAJ|title=Low-intensity Conflict in the Third World|last2=Ware|first2=Lewis B.|date=1988|publisher=Air University Press|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=8|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|last=Ayalon|first=Ami|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gce1I2KAxdwC|title=Middle East Contemporary Survey, Volume Xii, 1988|date=1990-09-25|publisher=The Moshe Dayan Center|year=|isbn=978-0-8133-1044-2|location=|pages=429|language=en}}</ref> However the coup failed, and so al-Modarresi reorganised the structure of the Front, focusing on its information efforts in Europe.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Rabinovich|first=Itamar|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=m1XjHn8rrl4C|title=Middle East Contemporary Survey: Volume Ix, 1984-1985|last2=Shaked|first2=Haim|date=1988-01-10|publisher=The Moshe Dayan Center|year=|isbn=978-0-8133-7445-1|location=|pages=393-94|language=en}}</ref> \n\nal-Modarresi became a founding member of the [[Islamic Supreme Council of Iraq|Supreme Council for the Islamic Revolution in Iraq]] (SCIRI), and was among the active figures of the Iraqi opposition in exile. He was closely involved in efforts to expose and bring down the regime in Baghdad. He managed to escape a number of assassination attempts abroad, including one in Brazil in 1991 as well as two more attempts in Syria, by the Bathist intelligence operatives, in 2001.\n\n=== Return to Iraq ===\nUpon returning to Iraq after the fall of Saddam's regime, he was greeted by over thirty thousand people in Baghdad, fifty thousand in [[Sadr City]] and a similar crowd in his hometown, Karbala.\n\nal-Modarresi established a television station upon his return to his hometown.<ref name=\":3\" /> He is also involved in several large-scale humanitarian projects in Iraq and has been involved in the building of mosques, schools, medical clinics, orphanages, and has been a staunch advocate of women's rights and consistently speaks out against the oppression of women in his lectures and books. He also facilitates marriage by providing financial help to people who wish to get married and has organized several large mass marriage ceremonies. sl-Modarresi also founded and currently heads the League of Religious Scholars which brings together many high ranking Shi\u2019ite scholars or their representatives in Iraq.\n\n== Personal Life ==\nal-Modarresi is married to the daughter of prominent scholar, Hashim al-Qazwini (d. 2009), the elder brother of [[Mortada Al-Qazwini|Murtadha al-Qazwini]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://burathanews.com/arabic/news/69843|title=Tashyee' al-Sayyid Hashim al-Qazwini al-Najl al-Akbar Li Ayatollah al-Shahid al-Sayyid Muhammad-Sadiq al-Qazwini Fi Karbala|last=|first=|date=2009-07-08|website=al-Buratha News Outlet|language=ar-iq|trans-title=Sayyid Hashim al-Qazwini, oldest son of Ayatollah Muhammad-Sadiq al-Qazwini dies in Karbala|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> He has four daughters and five sons ([[Mahdi al-Modarresi|Mahdi]], Muhammad-Ali, Mustafa, Husayn and Muhammad-Kadhim). All of his sons are clerics. \n\n=== COVID-19 ===\nDuring the outbreak of the [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]], al-Modarresi expressed the opinion that the virus was a signal of Godly punishment for the [[Chinese people|Chinese]] population, because of the foods they consume<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/coronavirus-causes|title=Coronavirus causes: Origin and how it spreads|website=www.medicalnewstoday.com|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>, that are deemed Islamically unlawful, as well as their [[Cultural genocide of Uyghurs|mistreatment]] of the [[Uyghurs|Uighur]] Muslims.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zZbOFcMt66s|title=Ayatollah Hadi al-Mudarrisi Yakshif Asbab Intishar Virus Corona Fi al-Sin|last=|first=|date=|website=YouTube|trans-title=Ayatollah Hadi al-Modarresi uncovers the reasons behind the spread of the Coronavirus|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2020, it was alleged that al-Modarresi had contracted the virus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alhurra.com/iraq/2020/03/07/%D8%A5%D8%B5%D8%A7%D8%A8%D8%A9-%D9%85%D8%B1%D8%AC%D8%B9-%D8%B9%D8%B1%D8%A7%D9%82%D9%8A-%D8%A8%D8%A7%D8%B1%D8%B2-%D8%A8%D9%81%D9%8A%D8%B1%D9%88%D8%B3-%D9%83%D9%88%D8%B1%D9%88%D9%86%D8%A7|title=Isabat Marji Iraqi Bariz Bi Virus Corona|last=|first=|date=|website=Al-Hurra|language=ar|trans-title=Grand Iraqi Marja Contracts Corona Virus|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref> However he has since reported to be in good health.\n\n== Works ==\nal-Modarresi has authored more than 250 books. Some of them include:\n\n* {{Cite book|last=|first=|title=God's Sacrifice: The Epic Saga of Hussein and His Legendary Martyrdom|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-0994240927|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Heated Debate on Atheism|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-1548180010|location=|pages=|language=en}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=How to Beat Failure, Advise on Success and Time Management|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-9953299563|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Art of Success|publisher=|year=|isbn=978-9953299532|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}} (7 Volumes)\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=How to Enjoy Life and Live Happily|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=And They Ask You About Things|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Shortcuts To Glory|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Supplications of the Quran|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=A B Islam|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Supplications of the Quran|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Universal Challenges, Refurbishing Civilisation|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Mannerisms of the Commander of the Faithful|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}} (3 Volumes)\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Ashura|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=The Martyr and the Revolution|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=The Message of a Muslim.. To Save the World|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Critique on Marxism|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Response to [[Satanic Verses]] Book|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=|first=|title=Friend and Friendhsip|publisher=|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=ar|trans-title=}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official|http://www.modarresi.org}} (in Arabic)\n*[http://alfeker.net/authors.php?id=13 Library of al-Modarresi's books] by ''al-Feker E-book Network'' (in Arabic)\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Modarresi, Hadi}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Shia clerics]]\n[[Category:Politics of Bahrain]]\n[[Category:Politics of Iraq]]\n[[Category:Iraqi Shia Muslims]]\n[[Category:People from Karbala]]\n[[Category:Iraqi people of Iranian descent]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People of the Bahraini uprising of 2011]]\n", "name_user": "Sourceofgrace", "label": "safe", "comment": "Uncited information removed.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hadi_al-Modarresi"}
